<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Namibia     08-16 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Namibia,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>African Nations Say South Africa Endangers Namibia's Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   African nations on Wednesday appealed to
the Security Council to foil alleged attempts by South Africa to rig
the outcome of Namibia's pre-independence elections in November.
   The African nations told a special council meeting that South
Africa was trying to stop the South-West Africa People's
Organization, known as SWAPO, from taking power.
   Ghana's ambassador, James V. Gbeho, called on the Security
Council to adopt a new resolution giving the United Nations interim
control over Namibia, rather than the South African
administrator-general for Namibia.
   But South African U.N. representative, Jeremy Shearar, said SWAPO
was the real threat to Namibian independence.
   In response to criticism of the continued South African presence
in Namibia, South Africa said Tuesday it was confining former
members of a feared police unit to base for retraining.
   But Gbeho said it was not good enough to place former members of
the Koevoet police under U.N. supervision. He said the veterans, who
have been integrated into the South African-led Namibian police,
should be fired.
   Ghana's ambassador also said the proposed election laws are
unfair because they allow white South Africans who worked or were
born in Namibia to register to vote there.
   Gbeho also objected to proposed Namibian laws that disqualify
those convicted of crimes, including treason and sedition, from
voting or being candidates for the constituent assembly. He said
these provisions would bar many SWAPO leaders from running for
assembly seats, and prevent SWAPO activists from voting.
   SWAPO has accused South Africa of trying to manipulate November's
pre-independence elections, which it is expected to win.
   Shearar said it was a ``great pity'' the Security Council had
been convened by the Africans.
   He said fewer than 2,300 South Africans with Namibian citizenship
had registered to vote so far. Up to 700,000 people are expected to
vote.
   Shearar said SWAPO poses the true threat to Namibian
independence. He said that 1,900 armed SWAPO guerrillas entered
Namibia from Angola the day the U.N.-backed peace plan went into
effect on April 1.
   Hundreds of guerrillas and dozens of soldiers and police died in
subsequent fighting between SWAPO and the South African-led security
forces.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
