<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0016EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PTLChronology     08-16 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PTL Chronology,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-PTL Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of the major events involving PTL and Jim
Bakker since his resignation as head of the Fort Mill, S.C.-based
ministry and its Heritage USA Christian theme park:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1987</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   March 19 _ Bakker resigns amid sex and money scandal involving
former New York church secretary Jessica Hahn. The Rev. Jerry
Falwell takes over as chairman of the board and Richard Dortch
becomes president of PTL.
   May 6 _ Assemblies of God leaders defrock Bakker and Dortch.
   June 12 _ PTL files for protection from creditors under Chapter
11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code.
   Oct. 8 _ Falwell, the PTL board of directors, the co-hosts of the
``PTL Show'' and other top executives resign from PTL during a
dispute over bankruptcy reorganization plan and fears that Bakker
will be allowed to return. David Clark, a Christian Broadcasting
Network executive, becomes trustee.
   Dec. 22 _ U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds approves the
ministry's bankruptcy plan, which divides PTL into separate
ministerial and for-profit entities and involves a schedule for
repaying creditors.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1988</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 31 _ PTL sues Bakker and his chief aide, David Taggart, for
$52 million for recovery of unwarranted compensation and funds lost
through mismanagement.
   April 22 _ The IRS revokes PTL's tax-exempt status.
   May 20 _ Clark resigns as PTL trustee to become president of
Heritage Ministries, the non-profit ministerial entity. Former
Winston-Salem, N.C., Mayor M.C. Benton becomes the new trustee.
Clark later resigns as president of Heritage Ministries.
   June 7 _ Jim and Tammy Bakker return from California, open an
office for Jim and Tammy Ministries and move into a condominium paid
for by supporters.
   Aug. 31 _ Bakker and Benton agree on terms for Bakker to buy
Heritage USA, paving the way for Bakker's return as leader of PTL.
   Sept. 9 _ Bakker misses deadline for $3 million deposit. Benton
says he will no longer negotiate with Bakker.
   Nov. 3 _ U.S. Attorney Charles Alexander notifies the Bakkers and
Taggart they are subjects of a grand jury investigation.
   Nov. 10 _ Reynolds rules that the Bakkers and Taggart must pay
$7.6 million in damages to PTL.
   Dec. 5 _ Federal grand jury hands up indictments of Bakker and
Dortch on charges of mail fraud and wire fraud. They also are
accused of conspiring to defraud ministry contributors to support
extravagant lifestyles and of diverting more than $4 million in PTL
money for their personal benefit. Bakker aides James and David
Taggert are charged with evading taxes, conspiring to impede the IRS
in tax collection, and using more than $1.1 million in PTL money for
personal expenditures.
   Dec. 13 _ Toronto real estate magnate Stephen Mernick, an
Orthodox Jew, buys the assets of PTL for $65 million at a hearing
before Judge Reynolds.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1989</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   January _ The Bakkers begin broadcasting ``The Jim and Tammy
Show'' from their leased home in Charlotte.
   Feb. 13 _ Mernick assumes joint management of the Heritage USA
property with a bankruptcy trustee but title questions delay the
sale's closing.
   March 29 _ Bakker arrives at a Florida retreat for ministers, but
continues to tape his program. Bakker had to cease his broadcasts
from his Charlotte home since they violated zoning ordinances.
   May 8 _ The Bakkers broadcast ``The Jim and Tammy Show'' live
from their new studio in a boarded-up department store in a nearly
abandoned mall in southwest Orlando, Fla.
   July 25 _ The Taggart brothers are convicted of tax evasion
charges.
   Aug. 8 _ Dortch agrees to plead guilty four counts _ mail fraud,
wire fraud by telephone, wire fraud by television and conspiracy _
and testify against Bakker.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
