<DOCNO> AP890816-0007 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0017EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-QuebecIndependence     08-16 0791</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quebec Independence,0813</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quebec Separatist Issue Back in Canadian Politics</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A public opinion poll has thrust the issue of
Quebec independence back into the Canadian political arena, although
Quebeckers rejected separatism in a referendum nearly a decade ago.
   The Gallup poll indicated that 28 percent of Canadians believe
French-speaking Quebec should become an independent country.
According to Gallup, it was the strongest support for separatism
nationally since the company's pollsters first asked the question
more than 20 years ago.
   Perhaps the most startling finding of the poll of 1,034 Canadians
was that 27 percent of English-speaking Canadians and 36 percent of
French-speaking Canadians favored Quebec's becoming a separate
nation.
   There long has been resentment in parts of English-speaking
Canada, especially in the West, of what is perceived as favoritism
or special treatment for Quebec. But the percentage of those who
would just as soon see it separate from Canada had not been
perceived to be as high as the poll indicated.
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, a native of Quebec, brushed the
poll findings aside.
   ``The heartbeat of the nation is strong, it's vigorous and it's
resolved to even greater unity,'' he said.
   ``It's kind of silly to ask Canadians whether they want to divide
their country or to strip their country. The answer, when you strip
away the varnish, is absolutely `no.'''
   Mulroney conceded that some linguistic tensions exist in Canada
but said that always has been the case.
   Indeed, a focus in the Canadian news media on the national unity
issue may be as much a result of a languid summer without much else
attracting attention as to any concrete developments in Quebec.
   Premier Robert Bourassa of Quebec, who opposes separatism,
appears virtually certain to win the election expected in early
fall, possibly with an even greater margin of victory for his
provincial Liberal Party than in 1985 when it won 99 of 122 seats in
the Quebec legislature.
   The Parti Quebecois, which found success with its separatist
message in the 1970s, has fallen on hard times, and the economic
prosperity that has lasted in Quebec along with most of Canada for
seven years makes this an unlikely time for a comeback.
   Quebec, Canada's largest and second most populous province with
6.5 million people, is 81 percent French-speaking.
   No one is predicting a new surge of the separatist movement. The
poll results were a reminder of how intractable the French-English
issues are in Canada and the difficulties of running a country in
which nine provinces are majority English-speaking and one
French-speaking.
   Among those expessing unease, however, was John Turner, the
retiring leader of the naional Liberal Party, which sits in
opposition to Mulroney's Progressive Conservatives.
   ``I have, during the course of the last six or nine months,
experienced and felt a deterioration in the mood of the country,''
Turner said. ``I believe all those who share with me the view of a
tolerant, bilingual federation working in equilibrium should be
concerned.''
   Quebec barely surfaced as an issue in the national election this
past November when the big issue was the free trade agreement with
the United States.
   Mulroney's victory allowed the pact to take effect as scheduled
Jan. 1, and Quebec was a center of support for the agreement and its
native son. Mulroney's Progressive Conservatives do not run in
Quebec's provincial elections.
   But the Quebec government's refusal last winter to remove its
restrictions on bilingual signs despite a Supreme Court of Canada
decision touched off resentment among the province's English
minority and in English-speaking provinces.
   French is required throughout Quebec as the only language on most
outdoor signs.
   There also has been growing realization that the Meech Lake
Accord, a constitutional agreement recognizing Quebec as a
``distinct society,'' may not make its deadline on June 23 for
ratification by all 10 provinces.
   The Atlantic coast province of New Brunswick and Manitoba in the
West have yet to ratify the agreement, and threats have been made to
reconsider ratification elsewhere before the deadline.
   The Meech Lake Accord developed because Quebec had refused to
join the nine other provinces in signing the national constitution
at the outset of the decade. The constitution still applies to
Quebec even without its signature, but the impasse makes it more
difficult for changes to be made on such national issues as native
rights and the way the Senate operates.
   Quebec voters rejected sovereignty in a 1980 referendum after a
dizzying decade in which power shifted from the English minority to
the French majority.
   The Parti Quebecois governed the province from 1976 to 1985 but
lost its spirit after 60 percent of Quebec's voters in the 1980
referendum rejected separation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
