<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--WomanJustice     08-16 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Woman Justice,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Don't Tell Women's Caucus, But Montana Court Appointment is a First</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Montana's first female Supreme Court justice
was named to the bench just this week, no matter what the National
Women's Political Caucus directory says.
   The organization listed Chief Justice Jean Turnage as one of the
women holding top elective offices around the country, in its
National Directory of Women Elected Officials.
   Trouble is, Turnage is a man. His first name, French for John,
has been Anglicized.
   Turnage said his name hasn't caused him problems in recent years,
but he recalled receiving written invitations to join sororities
when he was in college.
   ``I once knew a guy named Pearl, but I never knew a boy called
Sue,'' he joked Monday.
   The women's caucus will be able to cite one female justice on the
state's Supreme Court in its next directory, though. Gov. Stan
Stephens on Monday appointed Diane Barz, a state district judge in
Billings, to fill a vacancy on the bench.
</TEXT>
