<FIRST>r a AM-ElvisVigil 1stLd-Writethru a0744 08-16 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Elvis Vigil, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0744,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elvis Fans Stream Past His Grave in Annual Vigil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with vigil. Picks up 12th graf
pvs, `Graceland and...' ^By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn.(AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Elvis Presley faithful walked
with candles up a winding quarter-mile driveway to his former
mansion Tuesday night to pass the singer's grave and mark the 12th
anniversary of his death.
   The crowd walked single file and carried candles lit from an
eternal flame at the mansion, called Graceland. Many left single
roses at Presley's graveside beside the swimming pool. The rock 'n'
roll pioneer died Aug. 16, 1977.
   ``He just had everything,'' said Laurie Cousins, who waited on a
sidewalk for 13 hours to be first in line for the procession. ``He
had looks. He had charisma. He had everything.''
   The candlelight vigil, expected to draw more than 4,000
participants through the night, is the largest single event of a
nine-day lineup of concerts, memorials, trivia contests, film
festivals and souvenir fairs that make up Elvis International
Tribute Week.
   The 7-year-old Tribute Week is organized and promoted by managers
of Presley's former residence, Graceland, which draws 650,000
visitors a year, including some 40,000 over the anniversary
celebration, said Jack Soden, executive director of the Graceland
division of Elvis Presley Enterprises Inc.
   The vigil was begun 11 years ago by the Elvis Country Fan Club,
one of more than 250 Presley fan clubs around the world.
   Georgann Reynolds of Austin, Texas, president of the Elvis
Country club, said her group has more than 1,200 members worldwide,
many of whom are too young to have been Presley fans when he was
alive. She said she expects the annual graveside vigils to continue
for years to come.
   ``One reason for a fan club is to pass the torch, to keep the
candle burning,'' she said.
   Ms. Cousins, 38, of Winnipeg, Canada, said her daylong wait to be
first in line was worth it. It was the third year in a row that she
and her friend-in-Elvis Sheryl Fordin, 38, of New York, have been at
the front of the procession.
   Graceland and its 36,000-square-foot souvenir shopping center
take in about $12 million a year. The complex is run for the
financial benefit of Presley's only child, Lisa Marie.
   Tickets to tour the house, two of Presley's former airplanes and
a museum of his cars and motorcycles cost $15.95 each for adults and
$10.25 for children. A tour of the house alone is $7.50.
   Presley bought the three-story, white-columned residence in 1957
when his rock 'n' roll career began to blossom, and he called
Memphis home for most of his professional life. Presley died at age
42 of heart disease.
</TEXT>
