<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0038EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PreschoolMolest     08-16 0824</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Preschool Molest,0847</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marathon Trial Is `Cottage Industry Event' in Bloated Justice System</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defense attorney sees the McMartin preschool
molestation trial as ``a cottage industry event'' and legal experts
say its protracted length is symptomatic of a bloated, unworkable
justice system.
   With the trial in its third year and the charges against Raymond
Buckey and his mother 6 years old, the McMartin case has set records
in criminal law. And it's not over yet.
   In April, the trial became the longest in U.S. history,
surpassing the two-year record of the Hillside Strangler case. Its
cost was estimated recently at $15 million and climbing.
   ``This trial has become a cottage industry event,'' said Buckey's
attorney Danny Davis. ``It made experts out of people who testified.
It became an annuity for attorneys. It has regularly been a ratings
focus for television. ... Lots of carpet baggers glom on and make
hay.''
   The chief prosecutor, Deputy District Attorney Lael Rubin, says
that although McMartin is the longest trial it's not that unusual.
   ``I would say that in many respects the McMartin case is like
other cases that take much too long to go through the system and
come to a conclusion,'' she said.
   Ms. Rubin blames the defense for the trial's length, citing
interminable cross-examinations. She says 80 percent of the 14
months she spent presenting her case was taken up by defense
inquiries.
   The defense blames the prosecution.
   ``McMartin is a case that may have been doomed to excesses,''
Davis says. ``It started in excess. Its core defect was numbers _
numbers of counts, numbers of defendants, numbers of children.
Whatever you think of guilt or innocence, there was no necessity to
bring such a large case.''
   It began with Buckey's arrest in 1983 and escalated to include
six other teachers at the prestigious McMartin Pre-school in the
seaside community of Manhattan Beach. Prosecutors alleged that
Buckey, his mother, sister, grandmother and three other women
teachers had molested hundreds of tots at the school over five years.
   But after an 18-month preliminary hearing, District Attorney Ira
Reiner dropped charges against five of the defendants, saying there
was insufficient evidence to prosecute them.
   Buckey, now 31, and his mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey, 62, were
left to face trial on 64 counts of molestation and a shared count of
conspiracy involving alleged molestation of 11 children.
   Since the trial began in April 1987, the jury of 12 with a backup
panel of six alternates has been dwindling due to illness and
employment problems. With only one alternate left, Superior Court
Judge William Pounders worries that the case will be aborted if more
jurors are lost. A jury of 12 is required to decide a criminal case.
   ``It is a probability this case will end in a mistrial,''
Pounders said recently, vowing to do everything he can to avert
that. He has limited defense witnesses and lengthened the trial day
to six hours. Attorneys hope to submit the case to jurors this year.
   ``The system can't survive too many more McMartins because it's
so long and expensive,'' says Peter Aranella, professor of criminal
law at the University of California at Los Angeles.
   Aranella suggests that the time and money consumed by such a case
reduces the chance for other defendants to receive trials.
   In order to work, he said, the system must rely on plea
bargaining to dispose of 80 percent to 90 percent of criminal
prosecutions.
   ``The adversarial trial system is too time consuming, cumbersome
and expensive to provide to every criminal defendant,'' he said.
``That's a fact of life that every actor in the criminal justice
system understands.''
   ``The irony,'' Aranella says, ``is that as long as the system can
rely on plea bargaining to settle the majority of criminal
prosecutions, we can go on for a long time with these occasional
show trials.''
   The national trend is toward longer and longer trials, says
Albert Alschuler, professor of law at the University of Chicago who
calls the length of the McMartin case ``incomprehensible.''
   ``American trials are just ridiculously too long with the result
that we don't give them to everyone,'' he said. `` We pressure
almost all defendants into plea bargains.''
   Alschuler, citing legal history, says trials have been growing in
length for the last century.
   ``I think it was the late 18th century when the first criminal
trial lasted longer than a day,'' he said. ``... It's been a gradual
process of increasing trial complexity.''
   Ms. Rubin thinks that McMartin will lead to reforms with
legislators moving to limit the length of jury selection and
preliminary hearings. But Alschuler sees little chance for reform.
   ``This is a great system for lawyers, and lawyers control the
criminal justice system,'' Alschuler said. ``It's not a great system
for defendants and taxpayers. But, by God, it's a great system for
lawyers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
