<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0039EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Vatican-Jews     08-16 0886</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vatican-Jews,0912</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disputes Over Auschwitz, Covenant Hurt Jewish-Catholic Relations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relations between Roman Catholics and Jews have
suffered new setbacks that threaten long-term efforts aimed at
mending centuries of mistrust and misunderstanding.
   Officials on both sides are appealing for moderation to deal with
the disputes involving a Roman Catholic convent at Auschwitz and
Pope John Paul II's recent remarks about God's covenant with the
Jews, in which he said history showed Israel had not always been
faithful to God's law.
   While expressing anger and disappointment, Jewish leaders in
Europe and the United States said relations with the church have
improved substantially since the 1962-65 Second Vatican Council, and
they want to continue the interfaith dialogue.
   ``Our relations have to overcome 2,000 years of
misunderstanding,'' said Rabbi Leon Klenicki, director of interfaith
affairs of the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith in New York
and the group's liaison representative to the Vatican. ``You can't
do it in 20 years. What is crucial is to continue the dialogue and
the relationship.''
   It has been a bumpy relationship during the 10{-year papacy of
John Paul.
   Rabbi Marc H. Tanenbaum, former chairman of the International
Jewish Committee on Interreligious Consultations, said relations
have gone ``two steps forward, one step backward.''
   The steps forward included John Paul's visit to Rome's main
synagogue in 1986, the first recorded visit by a pope to a Jewish
shrine, and his talks with a delegation of American Jews in 1987.
   A step backward was the pope's meeting at the Vatican in 1982
with PLO leader Yasser Arafat. Then came the pope's audience in 1987
with Austrian President Kurt Waldheim, accused of complicity in Nazi
war crimes.
   The Holocaust has been a particular source of friction.
   Jews and others have questioned whether Pope Pius XII did enough
during World War II to stop Hitler's campaign to exterminate the
Jews. John Paul was criticized for not mentioning Jewish victims
during his 1988 visit to the Mauthausen concentration camp in
Austria, although a few weeks later he spoke of the ``particular
measure of extermination'' suffered by Jews.
   In a 1987 papal letter released in the United States, John Paul
said Christians ``approach with fearsome respect the terrifying
experience of the extermination ... suffered by the Jews'' during
the war.
   Still, some Jewish groups say the pope has not gone far enough
and that he treats the Holocaust as not exclusively a Jewish tragedy.
   Nobel laureate Elie Wiesel, a Holocaust survivor and author,
recently accused John Paul of trying to ``de-Judaize'' the Holocaust
by ignoring Jewish suffering in speeches and comments about that era.
   The Holocaust is at the root of the latest dispute, which
involves a Carmelite convent at Oswiecim, Poland, a few feet from
the fence surrounding the Auschwitz concentration camp.
   Jewish groups say the convent and its Christian symbols, such as
a 23-foot cross, offend the memory of the 2.5 million Jews who died
there.
   Under an accord signed by Catholic and Jewish leaders in 1987,
the nuns were supposed to have moved by Feb. 22 to a prayer center
to be built several thousand yards away.
   The deadline passed, and the center has yet to be built. Jewish
groups accused the Polish church of reneging.
   ``What was supposed to be and should have been a discreet and
loving gesture of conciliation and reconciliation, because of delays
has become a stumbling block on the path of Jewish-Catholic
relations,'' said Tullia Zevi, president of the Union of Italian
Jewish Communities and a signatory to the 1987 accord.
   After a series of demonstrations at the convent by American
Jewish activists, Cardinal Franciszek Macharski announced Aug. 10 he
was suspending the agreement to move the nuns. He blamed Western
Jewish groups for launching ``a violent campaign of accusations and
slanders'' and creating an ``atmosphere of aggressive demands.''
   Many Jews want the pope to intervene.
   The pope himself sparked a controversy with his remarks during
two recent general audiences about God's covenant with Moses on
Mount Sinai.
   On Aug. 2, the pope said God selected Jews as the chosen people
``on condition that they remained faithful to his law.''
   ``But the history of the Old Testament shows many instances of
Israel's infidelity to God,'' he said. ``Hence God sent the Prophets
as his messengers to call the people to conversion, to warn them of
their hardness of heart and to foretell a new covenant still to
come.''
   The Anti-Defamation League of B'Nai B'rith protested, expressing
``profound concern'' at the comments and said it hoped the ``clock
of Catholic-Jewish relations has not been tragically set back.''
   The group said the pope's remarks suggested the new covenant with
Christianity had replaced and superseded the alliance with Jews, who
believe that God's covenant with them is everlasting.
   Jewish leaders said the pope's remarks contradicted the Second
Vatican Council's 1965 document Nostra Aetate (In Our Times), which
officially rescinded the accusation that the Jews killed Christ.
That document is considered a turning point in Catholic-Jewish
relations.
   The Rev. Pier Francesco Fumagalli, an official of the Vatican's
office for relations with Jews, confirmed he received the
Anti-Defamation League's letter of protest and said it would be
studied. Otherwise, the Vatican has not commented publicly on the
issue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
