<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0051EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LibelSuit     08-16 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libel Suit,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Exec Files $80 Million Libel Suit Against Business Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOINA CHIACU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former chief executive for Allegheny
International Inc. has filed an $80 million libel suit against
Business Week magazine, claiming a defamatory cover story cost him
his job and reputation.
   The lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court said false statements
about Robert J. Buckley's business dealings and professional
competency were made in the Aug. 11, 1986, issue of the magazine
published by McGraw-Hill Inc.
   ``He was the featured cover article in a national publication, he
was held up to ridicule and scorn, he was accused falsely of ruining
the company and he lost his position at the company as a direct
result of this and follow-up articles,'' Buckley's lawyer, Dort S.
Bigg of Manchester, said Tuesday.
   The suit also cites a July 3, 1989, article that mentions Buckley
in another cover story on corporate directors under the heading
``Horror Stories.''
   Buckley was fired as Allegheny's chief executive officer shortly
after the 1986 article hit the newsstands and the Pittsburgh-based
appliance manufacturer later went bankrupt. Buckley has been
unemployed since then, Bigg said.
   ``He has found it virtually impossible to pursue the type of
business dealings it was his experience and his pleasure to
pursue,'' Bigg said. ``He has been seriously damaged economically
and in the national and world business community.''
   Buckley's son, Christopher Buckley, currently has a lawsuit
pending against the publishing house in federal court in Pittsburgh,
claiming he was defamed in the 1986 story.
   Robert Buckley initially filed his libel suit in a Pennsylvania
court in 1986, but dropped it after McGraw-Hill moved the state
court action to federal court, McGraw Hill attorney Ken Vittor said.
   ``We feel it has no merit. We stand by our story,'' said Betsy
Russo, director of public affairs for McGraw-Hill. ``The story was
exhaustively researched and we intend to vigorously defend it.''
   Robert Buckley filed his suit in New Hampshire on July 28, only
days before the state's three-year statute of limitations ran out,
Bigg said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
