<DOCNO> AP890816-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0106EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Names     08-16 0921</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0957</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Colin L. Powell said goodbye to Atlanta's
business and government leaders at a reception commemorating his
short stint as commander-in-chief for Forces Command at Fort
McPherson.
   Powell, who was nominated last week to serve as chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff, said he enjoyed his four-month stint at the
Atlanta post.
   ``I leave here loaded with Southern hospitality,'' he said
Tuesday.
   Delta Air Lines Chairman Ron Allen, chairman of the Atlanta
Chamber of Commerce, presented a picture of the symbol of Atlanta,
Phoenix Rising, inscribed to Powell, ``who was in our midst the
shortest time of any Forscom Commander but will leave the longest
shadow.''
   Mayor Andrew Young praised Powell for his work as former
President Reagan's national security adviser, saying he was ``the
last person the president talked to before he made a decision and he
made some very good decisions on your watch.''
   ``We really hate to see you go,'' Young said, ``but we couldn't
find anybody better to entrust our military to.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former ``Charlie's Angels'' TV star Kate
Jackson underwent cancer surgery in which doctors removed a
malignant part of her breast, a spokeswoman said.
   Miss Jackson, 40, was resting comfortably at an undisclosed Los
Angeles-area hospital and ``her prognosis is excellent,'' publicist
Lisa Kasteler said Tuesday.
   Surgeons performed a modified mastectomy and reconstructive
plastic surgery, Kasteler said.
   ``I'm making this disclosure public in order to help other women
facing this difficult situation, encourage early detection of breast
disease through mammography and to save inquiring minds 50 cents,''
Miss Jackson said in a statement.
   The actress, who starred in the movie ``Making Love'' and the
short-lived 1989 television series ``Baby Boom'' on NBC, will return
to work Sept. 6 in a still-untitled television movie for CBS, her
publicist said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Candy loves his wisecracking roles in
comedy films, but he regards viewing his own movies as a horror.
   ``I don't watch my movies,'' the hefty actor said. ``I just get
too critical of myself.''
   Candy, who got his start in television with ``SCTV,'' said he
watches daily prints during shooting and often views rough-cut
versions. But he won't go further in fear of second-guessing his
performances and editing room decisions.
   ``You get frustrated thinking, `I would do this and I would do
that,''' he said. ``Instead of putting myself through that, I don't
even bother with it anymore.''
   Candy plays an irresponsible bachelor baby-sitting his brother's
children in ``Uncle Buck.'' The film, scheduled for release this
week, is his third collaboration with moviemaker John Hughes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Jill Ireland, whose battle with cancer
was described in two best-selling books, is ``pretty much stable,
looking good and feeling good,'' her publicist said.
   ``The cancer has not recurred in her neck and shoulder,''
publicist Lori Jonas said Tuesday. ``She is undergoing chemotherapy
and still has the catheter in her chest. But she is doing very
well.''
   The English-born actress, wife of movie star Charles Bronson,
first underwent surgery for removal of a cancerous right breast and
eight lymph nodes under her arm in 1984. She wrote about the ordeal
in ``Life Wish.''
   In April 1988, Miss Ireland began feeling pain in her shoulder
and was diagnosed with cancer that had spread to her lungs, hip,
femur and thyroid.
   The 53-year-old actress underwent a drastic form of treatment in
Arlington, Texas, called hypothermia that involved injecting 9-inch
metal skewers into her shoulder and heating them to 160 degrees in
an attempt to burn the tumors.
