<DOCNO> AP890816-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0148EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-UnwantedBuffalo     08-16 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Unwanted Buffalo,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Herd Eating Chippewa Tribe's Budget</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELCOURT, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Indian reservation sounded like a good
home for a buffalo herd, but the Chippewa tribe wishes someone would
take them away.
   ``We don't want a herd of buffalo,'' said Fred ``Fritz'' Monette,
a Chippewa tribal councilman. ``Unfortunately, we got stuck with a
herd of buffalo, and we don't know what to do with them.''
   Feeding the herd is costing the tribe about $100 a week and will
become more expensive come winter, he said Monday.
   The National Park Service gave the herd to the Turtle Mountain
Indian Reservation under a program that distributes surplus animals
to reservations.
   The herd has grown from nine head in 1984 to 29.
   Louise Crosby claims the tribe is trying to cut expenses by
starving the buffalo. ``To see them starve like that is a horrible
thing,'' she said.
   Crosby, who ran a game farm before selling her animals to the
Minot Zoo, said she offered to buy the buffalo to show the tribe how
extreme she thinks the situation is. But she said she doesn't really
want them because she too is daunted by feed costs.
   Monette and Tribal Chairman Twila Martin-Kekahbah deny the
buffalo are starving.
   ``They cost some money to the tribe, which we really can't
afford,'' Martin-Kekahbah said. ``However, the buffalo are not
starving. Some believe the buffalo are better taken care of than the
membership.''
   Richard Peltier, caretaker for the buffalo, said the animals
usually are fed between 15 gallons to 30 gallons of ground barley a
day. The tribe also buys 80 to 90 bales of hay a year for the herd,
he said, and provides a barrel of canned food supplement and a salt
block. The herd also has a large spring-fed water hole, he said.
   ``I think they are fed better than a lot of places,'' Peltier
said.
   Complaints from people like Crosby may stem from a
misunderstanding about how buffalo should look, he said. ``A person
has to get pretty close to them to see what shape they are in,'' he
said.
   Monette said the tribe is asking for suggestions on how it might
reduce the herd to a manageable size, possibly by auctioning or
donating animals.
</TEXT>
