<FIRST>r w PM-MysteryPilot     08-16 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mystery Pilot,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Investigating Pilot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury is investigating whether
Alexandria mystery pilot Thomas Root or his law firm falsified a
Federal Aviation Administration document last year, the Washington
Post reports in today's editions.
   The document reportedly shows the FAA signed off on a broadcast
tower proposed by one of Root's clients, saying the radio tower
would pose no danger to aircraft.
   The document was needed to continue plans for a new FM radio
station in Kirksville, Mo., the newspaper reports. It was approved.
   But for several months federal officials have been trying to
determine whether the FAA ever filled out the approval form, the
Post quotes sources as saying.
   An FAA official said the technician whose name appears on the
suspect document has testified before the grand jury.
   Falsifying a government document is a criminal violation, an FAA
spokeswoman said.
   The grand jury investigation is one of several legal questions
facing the 36-year-old pilot and lawyer, who survived a bizarre
six-hour plane trip, a crash into the Atlantic Ocean and an
unexplained gunshot wound last month.
</TEXT>
