<FIRST>r w PM-NissanProbe     08-16 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nissan Probe,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>NHTSA Steps Up Nissan Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal engineers say they are stepping up
their investigation into complaints that as many as 1.5 million
Nissan cars manufactured between 1982 and 1984 have a dangerous
seating defect.
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said Tuesday
that it had received 96 complaints that the cars' seat backs shifted
backward suddenly and without warning.
   The agency considers the allegations serious enough to upgrade a
preliminary evaluation into an engineering analysis, said spokesman
Tim Hurd. The change means engineers will study actual seat backs to
determine whether they are defective, as opposed to paperwork
analysis.
   Nissan spokesman Don Spetner said the company was reviewing the
decision and would have no immediate comment.
   The Nissan action was among several announced Tuesday, including
new or upgraded investigations of models sold under the nameplates
of Ford, Mercury, Peugeot, Toyota, Hyundai, BMW, Buick, Oldsmobile
and Pontiac and the closing of other investigations involving
Hyundai, Lincoln, Chevrolet and Ford.
   ``We've had large recalls of other cars for seat-back failures,''
Hurd said of the Nissan action. ``It's a hazard. You can lose
control of your car if the seat back suddenly fails.''
   Complaints to NHTSA have blamed 22 accidents and 13 injuries on
the alleged defect, he said.
   The agency's engineers are examining these Nissan models
manufactured during the 1982, 1983 and 1984 model years: Maxima,
Pulsar, Sentra, Stanza, 200SX, 300ZX, 510 and 720.
   NHTSA also launched an investigation of 1987 and 1988 Ford
Escorts and Mercury Lynxes after 13 complaints that safety belts had
failed. Four injuries have been blamed on the belts' alleged failure
to restrain occupants during accidents, Hurd said.
   Also, NHTSA granted a petition requesting an engineering analysis
of the 1989 Peugeot Model 405. Six complaints have been filed about
malfunctions of the passive restraint system in 2,200 cars, Hurd
said.
   The agency also reported opening preliminary investigations of:
   _Stabilizer bar breakage in 400,000 Toyota Tercels from model
years 1982 through 1988.
   _Passive restraint system problems in the 1987 Hyundai Excel.
   _Rear-belt failure in the 1989 Ford Festiva.
   _Brake dragging and locking in 30,000 BMW models _ the 325,
524TD, 528E and 5351 from the 1985 through 1987 model years.
   _Parking cable wearing in several 1985-1987 General Motors cars:
the Chevrolet Monte Carlo, the Pontiac Grand Prix, the Oldsmobile
Cutlass and the Buick Regal.
   _Front wheel drive steering column locking in 500,000 Chrysler
cars with tilt steering wheels sold under Chrysler, Plymouth and
Dodge nameplates.
   The agency also raised several preliminary evaluations to the
engineering analysis level. One was a probe of 1,064 Buick LeSabres,
Oldsmobile 98s and Pontiac Bonnevilles from 1986 and 1987 in the
wake of complaints about jammed brakes. Another involved safety belt
failures in 6,282 Toyota Land Cruisers.
   The agency reported discontinuing a probe into seat-back failures
in Ford passenger cars made between 1983 and 1986, finding
insufficient grounds to proceed.
   The agency closed three other investigations, finding there was
``no defect trend.'' The investigations were into complaints of:
   _Heater core failure in the 1986 Hyundai Excel GL.
   _Fuel filler pipe spurting in the 1988 Lincoln Town Car.
   _Brake lamp switch problems in the 1989 Chevrolet Celebrity.
</TEXT>
