<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0232EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-SmallBusiness     08-16 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Small Business,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>SBA Overhauls Set-Aside Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Small Business Administration is
overhauling its minority set-aside program in response to the
Wedtech bribery and influence-peddling scandal.
   The regulations, issued Tuesday and effective immediately, put
into effect legislation signed nine months ago by President Reagan.
They are designed to minimize political influence on the agency's
21-year-old program under which companies owned by blacks,
Hispanics, Asians, Indians and economically disadvantaged women are
given preference in the awarding of government contracts.
   Among the changes:
   _The director of the program will be a career employee of the
agency, rather than a political appointee. SBA Administrator Susan
Engeleiter named Erline Patrick, a former staff aide to the Senate
Small Business Committee, to the post.
   ``The person in charge will not have to respond as much to the
political pressures,'' Patrick said.
   _Companies that misrepresent their status as minority-owned will
be subject to stiffer penalties. The maximum fine was increased from
$50,000 to $500,000 and the top jail term from five years to 10
years.
   _For the first time, competitive bidding is required among
minority-owned companies for manufacturing contracts over $5 million
and product and service contracts over $3 million.
   _The length of time a company may get special preference was
lengthened from seven years to nine years, but companies will be
expected to derive a steadily decreasing percentage of their
revenues from contracts awarded under the program.
   _Owners of eligible companies must have net worth of less than
$250,000, excluding equity in their home or business, when they
enter the program. The old standard was $750,000, including home or
business equity.
   _The agency must rule on applications within 90 days.
   Patrick, at a news conference, said about 3,000 companies
participate. She said the net worth requirement and the initiation
of competitive bidding may discourage new participants, but she said
she hoped the deadline for decisions would boost participation.
   When Congress passed the law last year, Sen. Dale Bumpers,
D-Ark., chairman of the Senate Small Business Committee, said it was
aimed at preventing the recurrence of Wedtech-type scandals.
   Wedtech Corp., a South Bronx military contractor, was awarded
more than $250 million in no-bid contracts in just four years but
became the subject of five different state and federal criminal
investigations.
   E. Robert Wallach, a San Francisco lawyer and close friend of
former U.S. Attorney General Edwin Meese, was convicted earlier this
month of illegally receiving $425,000 from Wedtech to influence
government officials in the company's bids for contracts.
   Rep. Robert Garcia, D-N.Y., faces trial next month on charges he
and his wife illegally accepted cash and jewelry from Wedtech.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
