<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0203EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-France-DisgruntledGendarmes Bjt   08-16 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Disgruntled Gendarmes, Bjt,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Police Flood Newspapers with `Dirty Laundry'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspapers are being flooded with anonymous letters
from an unusual source _ disgruntled gendarmes, the military
corpsmen who make up almost half of France's 200,000 police officers.
   Government officials have replied by saying reforms will be
proposed this fall, and in the meantime the gendarmes should think
about the soldier's duty not to air the military's dirty laundry in
public.
   National and regional newspapers have received dozens of letters,
each purporting to speak for a large number of gendarmes who are
unhappy about pay scales, long hours and poor living conditions in
barracks.
   The 90,000 gendarmes are responsible for police duties on most
French highways and in rural areas, although they also sometimes
patrol in cities. Special squads fight terrorism, monitor river
traffic and patrol airports, among other tasks.
   The line between the duties of the gendarmerie and the national
police is not always clear, and leads to frequent conflict between
the two bodies. It occasionally leads to arrests of gendarmes by
police or vice-versa.
   The gendarmerie traces its origins back centuries to the
``Marechaussee,'' medieval soldiers called to catch bandits and
highwaymen. It got its name and current status in 1791, at the
height of the French Revolution.
   ``It's a unique organization that exists in no other country in
Europe,'' Napoleon once said, according to a history of the
gendarmes. ``It's the most efficient way to maintain the tranquility
of a country. ... It's a half-civil, half-military surveillance,
spread over the entire territory.''
   Gendarmes answer to the Defense Ministry. They are trained, paid
and expected to work and live like soldiers, while doing exactly the
same tasks as police. Unlike police, they cannot form unions, and
are not paid overtime.
   Speaking out publicly means certain disciplinary action under
military rules.
   An anonymous letter published in the regional daily Ouest-France
complained about ``the 120 hours on-call each week, including 60 to
80 hours working, no overtime pay or compensatory time off and no
compensation for working weekends and holidays.''
   Starting pay is $1,135 monthly for the unmarried, and pay
increases on a sliding scale for those with families. Several
letters said that, once unpaid overtime is taken into account,
gendarmes barely get the minimum wage.
   A letter published by the national daily France-Soir from an
anonymous gendarme's wife who signed herself ``Madame X'' denounced
``the degradation of family life.'' She said the gendarmerie makes
life ``abominable for couples, leading many of them to divorce.''
   Married gendarmes live in apartments built into the barracks,
with widely varying amenities.
   The first anonymous letters appeared in regional newspapers in
eastern France in early August and only gradually attracted national
attention. Soon there was a flood, with the French news agency
Agence France-Presse counting almost 20 over the weekend of Aug.
12-13.
   Gerard Renon, the junior minister in the Defense Ministry, said
in a television interview that the letters dealt with ``problems we
know about and are working on.''
   Other government officials said a proposal would be presented in
the fall to redistribute the work force, upgrade the barracks,
assure at least some free time to the gendarmes and possibly
increase the number of draftees allowed to do their military service
as auxiliary gendarmes.
   The director-general of the gendarmerie, Regis Mourier, issued a
statement saying he was aware of the problems and was working on
them.
   Meanwhile, he said, the gendarmes should keep quiet, ``not just
from respect for the obligations of the military status, but from
respect for the institution, its history and its place in the
nation,'' Mourier said.
   The call to silence just unleashed more letters.
   ``It's not by telling us to shut up that the problems will be
solved,'' said an anonymous letter published in the daily Le
Populaire du Centre de Limoges in central France. ``Watch out,
general officers and elected officials, disgust and discontent is
getting established in this good old Marechaussee.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890816-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0316EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     08-16 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Museum of Natural History has
decided that three heads are better than one when it comes to
dinosaurs.
   The museum has revised its opinion of what the head of an
apatosaurus _ commonly known as a brontosaurus _ looked like.
   But because the museum's 17-foot-tall, 66-foot-long apatosaurus
skeleton was assembled in 1905 and contains bones that are 140
million years old, it was too fragile to withstand a head transplant.
   So the museum has created an exhibit featuring three heads. One
is a copy of the head now on the apatosaurus skeleton, another is a
model that scientists now believe more closely resembles the
apatosaurus' real head, and the third is the head of a close
relative of the extinct beast.
   ``We may have to change our minds again once we find a skeleton
with a skull attached, but we think this is the most likely guess
based on the available evidence until we actually find a complete
skeleton with a skull attached,'' said Lowell Dingus, exhibit
coordinator.
   No one has ever found an apatosaurus skeleton with a skull
attached. The skull created for the 1905 model skeleton was based on
that of a dinosaur believed to be close kin, a camarasaurus.
   Since then, paleontologists have changed their minds about the
apatosaurus' likely relatives. A paper published in 1978 argued that
the diplodocus was a closer kin than the camarasaurus, implying the
apatosaurus had a longer, sleeker head than had been believed.
   When the museum tried to behead its apatosaurus in preparation
for a new skull, ``it sent vibrations down the skeleton and a couple
of the ribs fell off and broke,'' Dingus said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 7-year-old who can't get enough baseball
figured a way to get neighborhood kids to come out to his local
sandlot. He bribed them with soda pop.
   ``I like baseball a lot,'' Billy Green said Tuesday. ``I played
little league for Bartonville `Little Dream Hut' this summer. But
the season's over now. I didn't have anyone to play with.''
   He tried to interest some ``big kids'' in a game, but they turned
him down because they considered him too small.
   Not to be deterred in his quest for one last game before he
enters third grade Aug. 24, Billy decided to up his offer.
   With the help of his 10-year-old sister, Angie, Billy passed out
hand-lettered fliers: ``Baseball Game, Held By Billy Green at
Pleasant Vallay School, Friday, Aug. 11, 1989. 3:00.''
   The key to the flier was the fine print at the bottom: ``Water
and cups supplied. Also Coke, 7-Up and Root Beer. Bring your bats,
gloves and balls!''
   Billy stuck fliers under doors in the neighborhood, and got more
than a dozen boys and girls ages 7 to 14 to turn out.
   ``Some of the big kids are kind of lazy,'' Angie said. ``You kind
of need a bribe to get them to play.''
   The game had a story-book ending as well. Billy doubled and his
team won, 5-1.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARKER, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southfork Ranch can claim a real Ewing now.
   Cheryl Lee McClanahan gave birth to the first baby born at the
ranch on Sunday. So she decided to make a concession in naming her
10-pound baby boy: Tory Lee Ewing Crick.
   ``We couldn't fit in J.R.,'' Ms. McClanahan said.
   The Dallas woman was a week away from her expected delivery date,
but she decided to accompany her fiance, Chase Crick, to the ranch
just east of Parker. Crick had won a two-day stay at the ranch,
where exterior scenes for the ``Dallas'' television series are shot.
   When she realized she was about to give birth, she called a
midwife who helped her deliver the child.
</TEXT>
