<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0317EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TridentLaunch     08-16 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trident Launch,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trident 2 Missile Failure Could Set Back Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second explosion of a
submarine-launched Trident 2 missile in five months could again
delay Navy plans to send its newest, deadliest weapon on operational
patrol.
   The original December target was put off until March 1990 by the
first failure. Now the March goal is in jeopardy.
   One of the 44-foot, $23.7 million missiles exploded Tuesday
seconds after it was launched from the nuclear submarine Tennessee
while it cruised submerged about 200 miles southeast of Cape
Canaveral.
   The Navy said the blowup caused no injuries nor did it damage the
submarine or a nearby support ship.
   Officials said the problem occurred shortly after the missile
cleared the surface and ignited, reminiscent of the first Trident 2
submarine launch on March 21. That missile blew apart four seconds
after it was launched by the crew of the Tennessee.
   Investigators traced the problem in March to a mechanical linkage
responsible for moving the rocket steering nozzles back and forth.
The faulty part was redesigned.
   On Aug. 2, the Tennessee launched a Trident 2 with the design
changes on the missile's first underwater success, and Navy hopes
were buoyed.
   There was no immediate indication whether the two failures were
related, and officials said they won't know exactly what went wrong
Tuesday until they study radio telemetry tapes of the missile's
behavior.
   There was no immediate assessment of what impact the latest
failure will have on the Trident 2 operational schedule. The first
failure set back the plan three months.
   The Navy had planned about six more underwater tests before
sending the Tennessee on operational patrol in March with 24 of the
nuclear-tipped weapons. Nine Trident 2 submarines are planned.
   Each missile is capable of propelling as many as 10 nuclear
warheads to different targets more than 4,600 miles away.
   Nineteen Trident 2s were test-fired from a land launch pad before
sea trials began. The Navy rated 15 of them successful.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
