<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0334EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RiverboatGambling     08-16 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Riverboat Gambling,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Riverboat Gambling Passes in Two of Three Iowa Counties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUBUQUE, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposal to allow riverboat gambling
passed in two Iowa counties, but a third county surprised some
people by sinking the floating casinos plan by a wide margin.
   Voters in Dubuque County, the largest of the three counties,
approved the proposal by a 2-1 margin. With about 25 percent of
voters going to the polls, 7,793 or 66 percent voted yes and 3,913
or 33 percent disapproved.
   The Dubuque County vote was expected, but Allamakee County's
rejection didn't seem to be in the cards, some said, because there
was little organized opposition.
   ``It was very quiet. There were a couple of letters to the
editor. It's surprising,'' said deputy county auditor Marian Smith.
   With 23 percent of eligible voters in the extreme northeast Iowa
country going to the polls, 1,099 turned down the measure and 645
voted for it.
   In Clayton County, with about 20 percent of voters going to the
polls, the measure narrowly passed 1,122 to 1,060.
   ``It was hard to get an indication of what was going to happen.
There wasn't any organized opposition,'' said Robyn Denning, mayor
of McGregor in Clayton County. ``I'm just glad it passed.''
   Terry Harrmann, chairman of Dubuque's Riverboat Referendum
Committee, said he didn't expect a close vote.
   ``Dubuque is on the move,'' Harrmann said. ``Dubuque voters have
seen fit to say `Let's move forward, let's not rest on our
laurels.'''
   Six more Iowa counties along the Mississippi River will hold
special elections this month on the plan.
   Iowa's new riverboat gambling law allows gambling on excursion
boats, beginning April 1, 1991, in counties where voters first
approve it by a majority vote in a referendum. The Legislature
limited betting to $5 per play and set a $200 limit on losses.
   Boats can offer blackjack, roulette, slot machines, dice games
and video gambling.
   The state Racing and Gaming Commission will decide how many
licenses to grant and where the boats will dock, but that decision
isn't expected until next year.
   Harrmann said the City Council will select a possible site for a
dock if Dubuque acquires a license. He said supporters have
contacted three or four excursion boat operators to possibly operate
a floating casino.
   One of them is Fried-Schegan and Associates of San Diego.
   Company President Frank Fried said: ``We're confident that
Dubuque County made the right decision and applaud their efforts.
Passage of this referendum means that this region is one step closer
to bringing a first-class national tourist attraction to the
Midwest.''
   Special elections are scheduled Aug. 22 for voters in Lee and Des
Moines counties. An Aug. 29 referendum is set for voters in Scott,
Jackson, Clinton and Muscatine counties.
   In western Iowa, along the Missouri River, petitions are being
circulated in Mills and Woodbury counties. No dates have been set
for referendums there, the secretary of state's office said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
