<FIRST>r a PM-TranquilizedBear     08-16 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tranquilized Bear,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Gets Criticism For Tranquilizing Pole-Sitting Bear</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state agency said it was only
concerned about the safety of residents when it tranquilized a bear
that had ambled up a utility pole, causing her to tumble to the
ground in a shower of sparks.
   The state Department of Game and Fish was criticized Tuesday for
tranquilizing the bear atop the 25-foot pole without first cutting
electrical power or providing a safety net.
   Mark Birkhauser, a conservation officer with the department, said
he received nearly 30 calls Tuesday after television and a local
newspaper showed the bear falling from the pole, contacting
transformer coils that generated the spray of sparks, then trailing
smoke 25 feet to the ground.
   The singed bear survived with a limp after the 7,200-volt shock
and the fall, officials said, but that didn't deter callers.
   ``We've received quite a bit of calls _ primarily criticism.
Public opinion in general seems to think it wasn't handled as well
as it could have been,'' Birkhauser said. ``Most of them would have
liked to have seen us put a net under the pole or let the bear come
back down off the pole on its own.''
   But Birkhauser said public safety was the main concern.
   ``To have put a net would have been difficult and not terribly
smart,'' he said. ``That bear could have came back to and latched on
to the person holding the net.''
   ``The main concerns of callers were that the bear was
tranquilized while too high on the utility pole and no attempt was
made to cushion its fall, and that electrical power wasn't shut off
before the animal was shot down,'' said Merrilyn Segrest, deputy
supervisor at the Animal Humane Association in Albuquerque.
   Department officers shot the bear once on Monday with a
tranquilizer dart on a Northeast Heights rooftop, then again after
it reached the top of the utility pole.
   The bear, believed to be from the Sandia Mountains, was taken to
the Rio Grande Zoological Park, where she is doing well, officials
said. She sustained an electrical burn on her right hind leg.
   The bear was believed to have been searching for her lost cub. A
6-month-old cub was captured Sunday in a mulberry tree in
Albuquerque. The cub, which was being held in the Albuquerque zoo,
is fine, Birkhauser said.
   ``It's just scared and looking for mama,'' he said.
</TEXT>
