<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Fires     08-16 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Fires,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>11 Arrested on Charges They Set Jungle on Fire in the Yucatan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven people have been arrested on charges
they set fires that scorched 370,000 acres of jungle in southeastern
Mexico, the Attorney General's office said.
   The group started fires in the state of Quintana Roo ``for the
purpose of exploiting lumber resources and creating areas for
cultivation and uncontrolled human settlements,'' the office said in
a communique Tuesday.
   Residents near one of the fires told authorities they saw two of
the suspects pour gasoline across a wide area of jungle, then set it
ablaze, the communique said.
   The fires advanced slowly through the jungle for five months
until rain extinguished them in early August.
   Dry wood and other forest litter from Hurricane Gilbert last
September and the late start of the rainy season helped spread the
fires, authorities have said.
   Mexican and foreign experts estimate recovery of the jungle will
take more than 30 years, a spokesman for the Group of 100 Artists
and Intellectuals, an ecological organization, said Tuesday.
   Eight of the 11 were arrested in Mexico City, two in Quintana Roo
and one in the state of Veracruz.
   With 30 others, they had taken over land in Campeche state, also
in the southeast, and set fire to it to open land for cultivation,
the Attorney General's office said. Unable to control the blaze,
they fled to Quintana Roo in late March.
   They were charged with property damage, carrying weapons without
a license, criminal asociation and violation of forestry and
ecological protection laws.
   The communique said some of those arrested Monday have been
involved in fires and illegal land dealings on Ajusco, a mountain at
the southern edge of Mexico City.
   Two of the group were also wanted for various homicides in Mexico
City, the communique said.
</TEXT>
