<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     08-16 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC and NBC Get Last Laugh in Television Ratings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC and NBC laughed all the way to the ratings
bank as their comedy shows took over the top spots in the latest
Nielsen survey.
   ABC's ``Roseanne'' led the pack, and NBC claimed the most places
with six while CBS failed to place a single program in the Top 10
for the week ended Aug. 13.
   NBC's ``Cheers,'' in a tight race all summer with ``Roseanne''
for first, was second.
   Other comedies in the Top 10: ABC's ``Wonder Years,'' NBC's
``Dear John,'' NBC's ``A Different World,'' NBC's ``Golden Girls''
and ABC's ``Coach'' tied, NBC's ``The Cosby Show,'' ABC's ``Who's
the Boss?'' and NBC's ``Empty Nest.''
   NBC was first in the A.C. Nielsen Co. survey with an average of
10.9. ABC followed with 9.8 and CBS with 9.1.
   For the season to date, from Sept. 19, 1988, NBC leads with 14.6.
ABC has 11.8 and CBS 11.7. The ratings are the percentage of the
90.4 million homes with television in the United States. The share
is the percentage of sets in use.
   CBS had only three shows in the Top 20 for the week: ``60
Minutes'' in 12th place, ``Designing Women'' in 18th, and part one
of the miniseries ``If Tomorrow Comes'' tied for 19th.
   ABC's new program, ``Primetime Live,'' which made its debut the
week before in 37th place, was in 43rd place.
   It hasn't been a good time for summer shows. ``Knight &amp; Daye''
was in a tie for 44th place and ``13 East'' fell to a tie for 47th
place. ``13 East'' has dropped in the ratings each week since its
debut in 10th place.
   Fox Broadcasting's top show was ``Married ... With Children'' in
36th place. Fox's ``Totally Hidden Video'' was 39th and ``America's
Most Wanted'' was tied for 47th with ``13 East.''
   The only good news for CBS was a victory for its evening news
program. It was first among the news shows with a 9.0 rating. ABC
was second with 8.7 and NBC third with 8.3.
</TEXT>
