<DOCNO> AP890816-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0451EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-UN-Lebanon     08-16 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Lebanon,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Council Calls for Cease-Fire, Arab League Mediation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council condemned the bitter
fighting in Lebanon and called for an immediate truce and renewed
mediation efforts by the Arab League.
   The council's 15 member nations unanimously passed the statement
Tuesday night after Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
invoked a rarely used power to convene a session when the council
failed to act on its own.
   The Arab League ministers who have tried to mediate a peace
settlement in Lebanon also called for an immediate truce and
denounced the intensified fighting.
   France, to get the council to act as soon as possible, pushed for
the Security Council to adopt a statement rather than a stronger,
binding resolution, said diplomats who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   But minutes before midnight the Security Council passed a
statement, read by Algerian Ambassador Hocine Djoudi, this month's
council president.
   It said the council ``profoundly deplores the intensification of
the shelling and bitter fighting in recent days.''
   ``It expresses its great disquiet at the loss of human lives and
the untold suffering it causes to the Lebanese people,'' the
statement said.
   The council ``urgently appeals to all the parties to put an
immediate end to all operations and to all firing and all shelling
on land and at sea. It further appeals to all parties to observe a
total and immediate cease-fire.'' When no council member was willing
to call for a meeting on Lebanon, Perez de Cuellar invoked Article
99 of the U.N. Charter for the first time since he became
secretary-general in 1982.
   The article allows the secretary-general to call emergency
meetings on any threat to ``international peace and security.''
   The secretary-general only had to resort to this twice before in
the 44-year history of the world body, said U.N. officials.
   In 1960, Secretary-General Dag Hammarskjold invoked Article 99 to
call a meeting on the Congo Crisis; in 1979, Secretary-General Kurt
Waldheim used it to convene a meeting after Iran took American
hostages at the U.S. Embassy in Tehran.
   Some diplomats said the fact that Perez de Cuellar had to invoke
Article 99 showed the Security Council had little hope for the
situation in Lebanon, where Christian troops are battling Syrian
forces and their Lebanese Moslem allies.
   The council's statement said it supports an Arab League committee
that has tried to arrange a cease-fire and political settlement that
would end Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war.
   The members of the league's Tripartite Committee are King Hassan
II of Morocco, King Fahd Bin Abdul-Aziz al Saud of Saudi Arabia; and
President Chadli Benjedid of Algeria.
   Late Tuesday night they they issued a statement that said they
were ``saddened and profoundly moved by the recent evolution in
Lebanon, marked by a significant deterioration in security, without
precedent,'' the Moroccan news agency MAP reported in a dispatch
from Rabat.
   The leaders did not single out any party for blame. In a
statement Aug. 1, however, the foreign ministers of their nations
specifically condemned Syrian's actions and said their peace efforts
had come to ``a dead end in both the political and security fields.''
   That was the second Arab mediation effort to collapse this year,
and the diplomats said Arab members of the Security Council were not
eager to join in a declaration would make them responsible for a
solution to Lebanon's problems.
   The council may try to pass a resolution later in the week if the
warring parties do not respond to the statement and to other
diplomatic initiatives, the diplomats said.
   The permanent members of the Security Council are the United
States, Soviet Union, Britain, France, and China. The current
temporary members are Algeria, Brazil, Canada, Colombia, Ethiopia,
Finland, Malaysia, Nepal, Senegal and Yugoslavia.
</TEXT>
