<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0555EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Anderson     08-16 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Anderson,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Treasury Chief Dies at 79</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert B. Anderson, a former Treasury secretary
under President Eisenhower whose career was tarnished in recent
years when he was convicted of income tax evasion and disbarred, has
died at age 79.
   Anderson died Monday at New York Hospital, which he entered July
25 suffering from cancer of the esophagus, his son, Gerald L.
Anderson, said Tuesday. He died from surgery complications.
   As Treasury secretary from 1957 to 1961, Anderson was known as a
conservative who put a higher priority on preserving the dollar's
value than cutting taxes or paying for additional outlays.
   It was on his recommendation that Eisenhower decided that the
projected surplus for fiscal 1961 be used to pay off some of the
national debt rather than cutting taxes.
   After leaving government, Anderson was a limited partner in the
New York-based investment banking firm of Loeb, Rhoades &amp; Co. from
1961 until 1973.
   He also served as a director for several companies, including Pan
American World Airways and Goodyear Tire &amp; Rubber, and served as an
economic adviser to the Sultan of Oman and as a lobbyist and
consultant for the Rev. Sun Myung Moon's Unification Church.
   Anderson pleaded guilty in U.S. District Court in Manhattan to
evading taxes on more than $127,000 in income in 1983 and 1984, and
to operating an illegal offshore bank in which investors lost more
than $4 million. In 1987, he was sentenced to a month in prison and
five months' house arrest.
   He served his prison term in August 1987 and completed his house
arrest in January 1988, authorities said.
   Judge Edmund L. Palmieri also sentenced him to five years'
probation and directed him to make restitution to victims of the
bank operation who lost money on his advice.
   The judge said he was aware Anderson had been hospitalized for
alcoholism 10 times since 1981 and ordered him to enter a treatment
program.
   In January, the Appellate Division of the state Supreme Court
disbarred Anderson, saying the illegal banking had been
unconscionable.
   Originally a Democrat, Anderson supported Eisenhower in his first
presidential campaign in 1952 and switched to the GOP in 1956.
   He served as secretary of the Navy in 1953-54, during which time
he carried out Eisenhower's request to desegregate Navy posts in
Charleston, S.C., and Norfolk, Va. He also was deputy secretary of
defense in 1954-55. In those positions, he was known as a quiet and
efficient administrator.
   Besides his son Gerald, Anderson is survived by another son,
three grandchildren and two sisters. His wife, the former Ollie Mae
Rawlings, died in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
