<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Galvin 1stLd-Writethru a0489 08-16 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Galvin, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0489,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-IRA Lawyer Deported from Britain to United States</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Home Office quotes, details.
Picks up graf 8 pvs, `Britain says ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pro-IRA activist Martin Galvin was deported to the
United States today after violating an order barring him from
British territory, the government said.
   Galvin, publicity director for the New York-based Irish Northern
Aid Committee, or NORAID, was flown out of Britain on a Royal Air
Force flight heading to Washington, the Home Office said.
   The 39-year-old New York lawyer was arrested Tuesday in
Londonderry, Northern Ireland, after taking a walk through the city
on the 20th anniversary of the deployment of British troops in the
troubled province.
   ``He was flown out on a regular RAF flight to the United
States,'' said a spokesman for the Home Office, speaking anonymously
in keeping with British custom.
   ``It was a point that we wanted him out of the country as soon as
possible and the RAF had a plane available at about 5 a.m.''
   Galvin has been banned from entering British territory since July
1984 when he gave a speech endorsing violence one day after a
soldier was killed in Londonderry.
   A month later police tried to arrest him during a public
appearance in west Belfast. Galvin fled, but a young man was killed
by a plastic bullet fired by police trying to break up fighting in
the crowd of Irish Republican Army supporters.
   Galvin has visited Northern Ireland illegally on at least three
other occasions.
   He said Tuesday he had been in the province for three days before
police in bullet-resistant vests arrested him. He was flown Tuesday
night to Royal Air Force base Brize Norton, about 50 miles northwest
of London.
   During his walk, Galvin was accompanied by Martin McGuinness,
vice president of Sinn Fein, the IRA's legal political wing, and by
several local IRA leaders. They openly walked past a security
checkpoint on their way to the mainly Roman Catholic Bogside area of
Londonderry.
   Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams said Galvin was not permitted to
speak to lawyers before being deported, but would be challenging the
exclusion order on his return to the United States.
   Britain says NORAID collects money to buy arms for the outlawed
IRA. Galvin denies this, saying the money goes to families of
victims of violence in the province.
   The IRA is fighting to unite the province and its Protestant
majority with the predominantly Catholic Republic of Ireland under
socialist rule.
</TEXT>
