<FIRST>r a PM-PhoneContest     08-16 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone Contest,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Phone Company Not Amused with Disc Jockeys' Stunt</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Phone Strikes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michigan Bell officials weren't amused when
a radio station offered prizes to listeners who used operator
assistance to call the station during the telephone company's strike.
   Six people used directory assistance to call WJXQ-FM, and they
won free admission to a music festival. Several others told the
station they'd tried, but failed, said disc jockey Paul Sutherland.
   ``I fail to see the merit in this type of program,'' said Bob
Lacinski, Michigan Bell public relations director for Lansing.
``This is not the time to do those types of things, just to see how
Michigan Bell can react.''
   Sutherland said he and his partner, Dave Marcum, decided not to
do it again Tuesday after a Bell official called them.
   ``We weren't really trying to screw anybody up. We were just
trying to have some fun and _ even more so _ just see how tied up
things were,'' Sutherland said.
   Nearly 200,000 operators, clerks, technicians and other workers
are on strike against four so-called Baby Bell companies in 20
states and the District of Columbia.
