<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0640EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SpillLawsuit     08-16 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill Lawsuit,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Sues Exxon, Other Oil Companies Over Alaska Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a lawsuit, Alaska accused Exxon Corp.
and six other oil companies of deliberate and gross negligence in
not preventing and properly cleaning up the nation's worst oil spill.
   The lawsuit does not specify damages, but could amount to
billions of dollars, a state official said Tuesday.
   The state alleges that Exxon Corp. and Exxon Shipping Co., the
subsidiary that owned the tanker Exxon Valdez, are responsible for
the tanker running aground by failing to staff it adequately and
supervise the crew properly.
   The lawsuit, filed in state Superior Court at Anchorage, also
says Alyeska Pipeline Service Co., a consortium of oil companies
that runs the trans-Alaska oil pipeline, failed to take prompt and
adequate measures to contain and remove the spilled oil or prevent
it from spreading into environmentally sensitive areas.
   Alyeska was in charge of the initial response to the spill.
   The March 24 tanker disaster left nearly 11 million gallons of
crude oil in Prince William Sound.
   ``If you assume that the damages haven't been half mitigated and
then you add in any potential punitive damages, this is probably in
the multiple billions,'' said Robert LeResche, the state oil-spill
coordinator who announced the lawsuit at a news conference.
   The lawsuit names Alyeska and each of the consortium companies:
Exxon Pipeline Co., an Exxon Corp. subsidiary; Arco Pipeline Co.; BP
Alaska Pipelines Inc.; Mobil Alaska Pipeline Co.; Amerada Hess
Pipeline Corp.; Phillips Alaska Pipeline Corp.; and Unocal Pipeline
Co.
   Those companies controlled Alyeska's budget to a degree that
makes them responsible for Alyeska's response to the spill, the
lawsuit says.
   ``We feel that Alyeska as a corporation was merely a sham, a
corporate shell if you will, behind which these partners have been
hiding for the last 12 or 15 years,'' LeResche said.
   The lawsuit also charges that the oil companies misrepresented
their ability to contain and clean up oil spills, violated federal
marine pilotage laws and inflicted ``severe emotional distress on
Alaska residents.''
   In a statement issued at its New York headquarters, Exxon said it
had not seen the complaint ``but it appears to completely disregard
the fact that Exxon's response to the accident has been massive and
responsible.''
   ``Our goal continues to be to leave the water and shorelines in
an environmentally stable condition such that animals, birds and
fish are not harmed and no restrictions on commerical use or
subsistence hunting and fishing are necessary,'' Exxon said.
   The lawsuit seeks monetary damages for destruction of the
environment and harm to the region's fisheries-based economy.
   ``The state recognizes that more than 1,000 square miles of its
lands, waters and resources in or near Prince William Sound, the
Kenai Peninsula and Kodiak Island suffered severe environmental
damage, including the devastation of beaches and coastal waters, the
death or injury of thousands of animals, the curtailment of
important commercial fisheries, and the impairment of recreational
opportunities,'' a state news release said.
   The lawsuit seeks punitive damages, its cleanup costs, its costs
of studying and monitoring the spill, and a negligence fine under
state law of up to $100 million. The state also asks for an
injunction to ensure Exxon and Alyeska continue the cleanup until
the environment is restored.
   LeResche said he expected the lawsuit would take a decade to
resolve.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890816-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0642EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Obit-Genda     08-16 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Genda,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Genda, Pearl Harbor Planner, Dies on Anniversary of Japan Surrender</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minoru Genda, one of the chief planners of Japan's
surprise attack on Pearl Harbor, has died of heart failure in a
hospital, his family said.
   Genda, who died Tuesday on the anniversary of Japan's surrender
in World War II, would have been 85 today.
   A graduate of Japan's naval academy, he was a young aviation
staff officer who was called in early to plan for the daring attack
that severely damaged the U.S. Pacific fleet in Hawaii and brought
the United States into the war.
   He directed much of the secret training in Japanese waters before
the attack and, on Dec. 7, 1941, Genda was aboard one of the
Japanese carriers that launched the raid.
   In June 1942, however, he was involved with the unsuccessful
Japanese attack on Midway Island. Some analysts partially faulted
him for failing to order enough search planes to find the U.S. fleet
in the assault. The U.S. defense of Midway ended with many Japanese
warships sunk or damaged in one of the great sea battles of modern
times.
   After the war, Genda joined Japan's revived air force in 1954 and
became its chief of staff in 1959. After retiring from the military,
he was elected in 1962 to the upper house of Parliament for the
governing Liberal Democratic Party, and was re-elected three times
before he retired in 1986.
   Regarded as a hawk among the ruling party's defense experts,
Genda said in 1968 that if Japan had possessed an atom bomb it
should have used one during the war.
   Genda was a native of Hiroshima, the western city that was
leveled in the first atomic attack on Aug. 6, 1945.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
