<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Strike     08-16 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Strike,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Estonian President Meets with Kremlin Leaders on Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associate Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kremlin leaders met today with the president of
Estonia to consider ways to end a weeklong strike by Russians
complaining of discrimination in the Baltic republic, Soviet media
said.
   The strike by tens of thousands of ethnic Russians and other
non-Estonians is in response to a new law that limits the right to
vote and hold office to long-term residents of the small republic.
The workers are also upset about a new law requiring many of them to
learn to speak Estonian.
   The People's Front of Estonia, a pro-democracy group that also
has been a moving force behind pro-Estonian changes in the republic,
called for a national law guaranteeing the rights of minorities, the
labor newspaper Trud reported today.
   ``We will be living together for a long time and if the tension
keeps increasing, our lives and that of our children will be
intolerable,'' the group's statement said.
   While Estonian President Arnold Ruutel met in the Kremlin with
the ruling council of the Soviet government, a group of
parliamentarians toured Estonian factories and spoke with workers,
strike committee member Mikhail Lysenko said.
   The legislators met Tuesday night with the strike committee,
Lysenko said in a telephone interview.
   Maarika Saarna, an editor with Estonian state radio, said from
Tallinn Tuesday night that 26,000 workers at about 40 enterprises
were believed to be on strike. Lysenko said tens of thousands of
workers at 50 enterprises were involved.
   The walkout has paralyzed rail cargo around Tallinn, Estonia's
capital. Izvestia said more than 3,000 rail cars were idle while
Pravda said 2,000.
   To assure that necessary supplies get to the city of 480,000,
goods are being shipped to other cities in the republic, Pravda
quoted the republic's deputy premier, P. Palu, as saying. ``That
way, we'll supply Tallinn with everything needed,'' Palu said.
   Estonia's new election law limits voting to adults who have lived
in the same district for two years, or anywhere in the republic for
five years. Candidates for elected office must live in the same
place for five years, or in Estonia for 10 years.
   State-run Radio Moscow said the law will take the right to vote
away from more than 100,000 recent non-Estonian arrivals. That was
the aim of backers of the law, who fear an influx of outsiders is
making ethnic Estonians a minority in their homeland.
   However, Estonian journalists said the number of people affected
was 10,000 to 20,000, since most of the republic's non-Estonians
have lived in the republic more than two years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
