<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Iran     08-16 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Iran,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nephew of Briton Jailed in Iran Offers to Take his Place</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 17-year-old nephew of jailed businessman Roger
Cooper offered today to take his place if Iran would allow Cooper to
return to Britain for his mother's funeral.
   Cooper, 53, has been held in Tehran as an alleged spy for nearly
four years, and his family and the British government have appealed
to Iran to let him attend the funeral on Saturday.
   Simon Cooper, son of Roger Cooper's brother Paul Cooper, offered
to go to Iran as collateral for his uncle.
   ``I am a little scared, obviously, because I have never been to
Iran, but my father has been there three times,'' he said on British
Broadcasting Corp. radio.
   ``He has had no problems with the Iranians. They have treated him
well. I cannot see any reason why they would not treat me properly.''
   Paul Cooper said his son's offer was contained in an appeal he
sent to Iran.
   ``If they wanted a surety that Roger would return to jail, since
officially he is still a spy or is being held for who knows what, I
have said my son, Simon, would be happy to go as surety,'' Paul
Cooper said on the BBC.
   ``That was Simon's own proposal when we discussed the matter a
couple of days ago.''
   He said the move was a personal initiative rather than one
approved by the Foreign Office.
   ``It is very important to us that Roger is at his mother's
funeral,'' Paul Cooper said. ``She is the woman who brought him into
this world. She has been a wonderful mother.''
   Their mother, Dr. Rosaleen Cooper, died Aug. 3.
   Roger Cooper, who had lived in Iran for more than 20 years, was
detained in November 1985 and formally charged with espionage one
year later. Iranian officials have claimed that he also has been
tried and sentenced but the sentence has not been disclosed.
</TEXT>
