<SECOND>PM-Iran-Soviets,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Considering Purchase of Soviet Airplanes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iranian delegation will visit Moscow to
discuss the possible purchase of commercial airliners from the
Soviet Union, according to news reports today.
   Quoting a report in the Tehran Times, the Islamic Republic News
Agency said the delegation will leave for Moscow on Thursday.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, quoted an unidentified source
as telling the newspaper that ``avenues for closer cooperation
between Iran and the Soviet Union in the aviation field will be
explored,'' and that Iran might buy some passenger planes.
   IRNA had earlier quoted aviation sources as saying Iran has been
in the market for new jetliners, and that the European Airbus was
among the aircraft being considered.
   Iran Air, the national airline, has a fleet of 23 aging Boeing
and Airbus jetliners. Another domestic airline, Aseman, has three
Dutch-built Fokker aircraft and a few Cessnas.
   The Soviet Union and Iran have become close trade partners in
recent months.
   Following the August 1988 cease-fire in the eight-year Iran-Iraq
war, the Soviets have been helping Iran rebuild many war-battered
industrial complexes and refurbish other facilities.
