<FIRST>r i PM-Singapore-Refugees     08-16 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Singapore-Refugees,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Naval Vessel Rescues Vietnamese Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnamese boat people were rescued by the U.S.
Navy vessel whose former captain was punished for not picking up
refugees who later resorted to cannibalizing dead shipmates,
officials said today.
   A U.S. Embassy official said the Dubuque, an amphibious transport
ship, brought 30 Vietnamese into Singapore on Monday after rescuing
them from a wooden boat in the South China Sea early Sunday.
   The Dubuque, now commanded by Capt. D.L. Wetherwell, was
permitted to put the refugees ashore on the embassy's guarantee that
the Vietnamese would be resettled in another country within 90 days,
said the U.S. official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Wetherwell would not be interviewed about the rescue, said the
U.S. official, who was not certain whether the present crew members
were aboard in June 1988 when the Dubuque gave food and water to
Vietnamese refugees but left them to continue sailing on their own.
   The skipper at that time, Capt. Alexander Balian, was tried by
court-martial in the Philippines and found guilty Feb. 24 of
dereliction of duty for failing to recognize their distress or act
to see that they survived.
   The case highlighted the mariner's code that requires giving help
to a vessel in distress and the dangers faced by Vietnamese boat
people, who risk death in storms, by starvation and at the hands of
pirates.
   In the 1988 incident, the refugees had been drifting without
engine power for several weeks.
   Eighteen days after the Dubuque sailed away, Filipino fishermen
found the disabled boat, and survivors said 31 people had died. The
survivors later admitted they had cannibalized the dead.
   Balian was relieved of his command before his court-martial. His
conviction resulted in a reprimand and he was transferred to
Washington.
   On Sunday, the Dubuque's crew spotted a wooden, 35-foot refugee
boat about 460 miles north-northeast of Singapore, the U.S. Embassy
official said.
   The boat, carrying 23 adults and seven children, was out of food
and fresh water and low on fuel, he said, and some of the refugees
were suffering from dehydration. The vessel was determined not to be
seaworthy, and the refugees were taken aboard the Dubuque, the
official said.
   The Navy ship then brought them to Singapore, where it was making
a routine port call.
</TEXT>
