<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief, 1st Ld-Writethu,a0463,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Boeing Emplpoyee Charged in Documents Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-4 in first item to restore dropped words.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Boeing Co. executive is facing
charges he stole and reproduced classified Pentagon and National
Security Council documents.
   Richard Lee Fowler, 64, was indicted Tuesday on charges that he
stole secret Pentagon planning documents while he was selling Boeing
products to the military from 1979 to 1985.
   Reached at his Springfield, Va., home Tuesday night, Fowler
declined to comment.
   The classified documents described the Pentagon's Planning,
Programming and Budgeting System, which is used to plan future
weapons purchases.
   ``Possession of these documents would provide a competitive edge
to anyone in the business of supplying the (Defense Department) with
tactical and strategic weaponry,'' Pentagon Inspector General June
Gibbs Brown said in a statement.
   Fowler, who had been a senior marketing analyst with Boeing, was
charged with 39 felony counts, including a charge he removed the
``secret'' classification stamp from some documents and reproduced
them for other Boeing executives.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>US Hopes to Work on Anti-Apartheid Discussions</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department says it hopes to conduct
an ``active dialogue'' with the new South African leadership to
press for an end to apartheid.
   However, the department declined comment Tuesday on the
resignation of President P.W. Botha, calling it an internal South
African affair.
   ``We look forward to an active dialogue with the new South
African government as part of our efforts to promote real
negotiations leading to a non-racial democracy in South Africa,''
department spokesman Richard Boucher said.
   Asked whether acting President F.W. de Klerk would be invited to
visit the United States, Boucher said that ``will be determined
mutually in our discussions.''
   De Klerk, who is expected to be elected president in September,
was to be the first South African leader to visit the United States
in 30 years. But he postponed his summer visit, citing a heavy
campaign schedule, under pressure from Congress.
