<NOTE>Court Will Hear North's Appeal Next February</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver North's appeal of his convictions in the
Iran-Contra scandal will be heard Feb. 6 before a three-judge panel.
   U.S. Court of Appeals judges Abner Mikva, Laurence Silberman and
David Sentelle will review the case, according to a notice issued by
the court. The court notice, made available Tuesday, was signed last
week.
   North was convicted May 4 of aiding and abetting an obstruction
of Congress, destruction of National Security Council documents and
accepting an illegal gratuity.
   He was fined $150,000, given two years probation and ordered to
serve 1,200 hours of community service. He is proceeding with the
community service while appealing the three felony convictions.
