<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Drug Czar Says Nostalgia for Woodstock Mistaken</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug czar William J. Bennett says part of the
legacy of Woodstock was tolerance of drugs and that Americans should
be glad that times have changed.
   Bennett emerged Tuesday from a White House meeting on anti-drug
strategy with President Bush to complain about ``memory distortion''
going on about the rock concert in upstate New York that captivated
a generation 20 years ago.
   The 45-year-old Bennett, a onetime guitar player and fan of early
rock 'n' roll, recited what he called ``the casualty list from
Woodstock'': rock performers who died in later years from drug
overdoses.
   They included Janis Joplin, Jimi Hendrix, Keith Moon of the Who
and Paul Butterfield of the Paul Butterfield Blues Band.
   ``Part of the legacy of Woodstock was tolerance of drugs and let
us be glad that is over rather than wishing it were back,'' Bennett
said. ``We do not want 1969 back in terms of its view of drugs.
We've come too far.''
</TEXT>
