<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0858EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-USBases     08-16 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-US Bases,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Lawmaker: Our Bases Will Find Home Elsewhere If Needed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Stephen Solarz said today he
hopes the United States can reach an agreement to keep its military
bases in this country, but he said Washington will find other host
nations if necessary.
   The lease on the six military installations, including the Clark
Air Base and Subic Bay Naval Base, expires in 1991. Many Filipinos,
including lawmakers, have said it should not be renewed.
   Solarz, D-New York, was scheduled to meet later today with
President Corazon Aquino. She has not stated her position on the
issue.
   ``If they come to the conclusion that it is to the best interest
of the Philippines to permit us to continue using the facilities,
then we will gladly and willingly continue to utilize them,'' Solarz
said.
   He added, however, that the American government would develop
``operative facilities elsewhere'' in case the Philippines decides
to close the bases.
   Solarz, who is chairman of the Asian and Pacific affairs
subcommittee in the House, arrived in this country today with Rep.
Robert Dornan, R-Calif., and Eni Faleomavaega, a legislator from
American Samoa.
   In other comments to reporters, Solarz said Singapore's proposal
to host some American forces was a ``constructive offer'' _ but not
a substitute for the bases in the Philippines.
   Singapore extended its offer earlier this month.
   However, Defense Minister Tengku Ahmad Rithauddeen of neighboring
Malaysia said the proposal could jeopardize political stability in
Southeast Asia.
   Some Filipino opponents of the bases, wary of the heavy American
presence, have suggested the facilities could instead be used for
such things as commercial ship repair and industrial parks.
   The Philippines and United States are expected to begin talks
this year on whether to extend the current agreement. Mrs. Aquino is
expected to discuss the issue during a visit to the United States in
November.
   In October, the two countries reached an agreement allowing the
bases to remain until 1991 in return for $962 million in U.S.
military and economic aid over two years. About 40,000 American
troops, civilian workers and military dependents are stationed at
the facilities.
</TEXT>
