<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Israel     08-16 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Israel,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armenia Quake Victims Complete Treatment in Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of people injured by the devastating
earthquake in Soviet Armenia were back home today after receiving
treatment by Israeli medical experts.
   The Soviet news agency Tass said 61 people injured in the
earthquake arrived aboard an Israeli airliner Tuesday in Yerevan,
the capital of the Armenian republic. Tass said some patients had
received artificial limbs during their seven weeks of care in
Israeli hospitals.
   At least 25,000 people were killed, 31,000 were injured and more
than 100,000 left homeless in the earthquake that decimated large
areas of Armenia on Dec. 7.
   Tass reported that Soviet television said the flight ``meant the
end of operation `Healing.'''
   ``The passengers of today's unusual flight spent seven weeks in
the best Israeli hospitals,'' the agency said. ``Very complicated
operations were made on them, and they received prosthetic
appliances produced according to the latest methods in medical
science and engineering.''
   The Soviet Union cut diplomatic ties with Israel to protest its
occupation of territories belonging to Moscow's Arab allies in the
1967 Middle East war. But relations between the countries have
improved in recent years under the government of President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev.
   Tass said operation ``Healing'' was undertaken by what it called
the ``amalgamated distribution committee,'' and said it represented
the largest Jewish charity organization in the United States.
   Tass said operation ``Healing, which cost some $500,000, ended.
But it continues its aid to Armenia.''
   The report said Aria Kuperstog, the project's chief organizer,
told Soviet television: ``We want to establish a children's
rehabilitation center in Leninakan. The project hopes that its
construction will begin soon. The design is ready.'' Leninakan is a
city in Soviet Armenia near the border with Turkey. It was
particularly hard hit during the earthquake.
   Tass also said the charity organization ``intends to shoulder
training of Soviet doctors who will work at the center.''
</TEXT>
