<SECOND>PM-Condo Doors,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Condo Bars Couple From Using Their Own Patio Door</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple living on the first floor
of a condominium are asking a judge to decide whether they may use
their patio door.
   Henrietta and Alfred Binns have made a habit of using the door as
a shortcut to the parking lot.
   But the condominium association complained July 13 that their
back-door ways are destroying the landscaping and are ``viewed as an
eyesore by other owners.'' It ordered the couple to use the
building's main entrance.
   So on Aug. 8, the Binns sued in Broward County court.
   ``I laugh about it, but it really isn't a laughing matter,'' said
the Binns' lawyer, Benjie Sperling. ``You don't give up all your
rights when you enter a condo. Entering and exiting a door is about
as basic as you can get.''
   Taking the shortcut is ``the natural thing to do,'' said Mrs.
Binns. She said the grass outside the door is thick, green and looks
fine.
   The condo association's lawyer, Michael Hyman, said Tuesday he
had not yet reviewed the lawsuit.
   ``I would doubt if there is any precedent on something like
this,'' Sperling said, ``because it's too ridiculous.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
