<FIRST>r a PM-InterstateFire     08-16 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Interstate Fire,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire-Buckled Interstate Reopens in New Jersey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An interstate highway taken by tens of
thousands of New York City-bound commuters reopened this morning
more than a week after a fire in a pile of rubbish buckled the road.
   Four lanes of 10-lane Interstate 78 were opened to traffic before
rush hour.
   Three elevated sections of the road were seriously damaged Aug. 7
when debris piled beneath the highway caught fire, warping support
beams. Engineers salvaged a fourth elevated section with $385,000 in
emergency repairs.
   The owners of a recycling company responsible for the debris were
arrested last week on charges including endangering the public.
   Interstate 78, which is used by more than 100,000 motorists a
day, links western New Jersey's heavily populated suburbs with the
New Jersey Turnpike and ultimately New York. Commuters have had to
take detours, causing long tie-ups.
   Repairs are expected to take about eight months and cost about $5
million, said Randy Linthurst, a spokesman for the state Department
of Transportation.
</TEXT>
