<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0945EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan     08-16 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Less Than Half the Public Supports New Japanese Administration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of new Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu
has more public support than the previous administration, but its
approval rating remains below 50 percent, according to results of a
poll released today.
   The governing Liberal Democratic Party has pinned its hopes for
recovering its popularity on Kaifu, 58, who became prime minister
Aug. 9. His predecessor, Sousuke Uno, resigned after only 69 days in
office following the party's heavy losses in July 23 elections for
the upper house of Parliament.
   Kyodo News Service said 46.5 percent of those responding to a
poll conducted last week approved of Kaifu's new administration,
compared with 35.5 percent who supported the Uno Cabinet when it was
formed on June 2.
   Forty-three percent of respondents said they disapproved of
Kaifu's administration, compared to 49 percent who opposed the Uno
Cabinet, it added.
   It said the poll showed support for the conservative governing
party rose 9.6 percentage points from June to 40.8 percent, while
support for the biggest victor in the elections, the Japan Socialist
Party, rose 5.3 percentage points to a record 33.8 percent.
   Kaifu's initial support rating was the third lowest since Kyodo
began conducting approval polls in the 1960s, the news agency said.
The lowest rating for a newly formed Cabinet was for the
administration of Takeo Fukuda, formed in November 1976, it said.
   Uno's predecessor, Noboru Takeshita, began his administration
with a support rating of 58.6 percent in November 1987, but that
dropped to an all-time low of 3.9 percent in April of this year,
largely because of a stock-trading scandal that forced him to resign.
   Asked why they supported the Kaifu administration, the largest
number of respondents, 28.9 percent, said there was no other
appropriate person for the post, Kyodo said.
   The main reason given for opposing the new government, cited by
33.7 percent of respondents, was that it was backed by the Liberal
Democratic Party, it said.
   Kyodo said 3,000 eligible voters were contacted in the poll,
conducted Aug. 11-12, and 1,968 responded. It did not provide a
margin of error.
</TEXT>
