<FIRST>r a PM-HelmsleyTrial     08-16 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helmsley Trial,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helmsleys Had No Friends, Witness Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leona Helmsley _ the self-annointed hotel queen
portrayed in court as a tight-fisted tyrant _ had no friends, a
former aide says.
   That was exactly what Mrs. Helmsley's lawyer wanted the jury to
hear.
   Mrs. Helmsley, 69, is charged with evading about $1 million in
federal taxes by charging about $4 million in personal expenses to
Helmsley businesses. Her husband, Harry, 80, was previously ruled
mentally incompetent to stand trial.
   Defense attorney Gerald Feffer has sought to show that the couple
were entitled to bill Helmsley businesses for expenses at their
Greenwich, Conn., mansion because they used it to do work and
entertain business associates.
   Feffer on Tuesday opened his case by calling Mrs. Helmsley's
former personal assistant, Martin Goldstein, to the stand. Goldstein
had also testified for the prosecution.
   Goldstein testified that Mrs. Helmsley and her husband spent most
of their time on the weekends working at Dunnellen Hall. He said
they read correspondence, financial reports and other business
documents.
   ``Mr. Goldstein, did the Helmsleys have any personal friends?''
Feffer asked.
   ``No,'' he replied.
   Goldstein said he once presented Harry Helmsley with a stack of
financial reports and told Helmsley they might put him to sleep.
   ``Put me to sleep? This is the most exciting reading I can get,''
he said Helmsley replied.
   Previous witnesses had portrayed Mrs. Helmsley as an abusive boss
who extorted kickbacks from liquor suppliers, didn't pay her bills
and forced suppliers to charge personal expenses to her business.
   Even her attorney conceded she was ``demanding'' and ``abrasive.''
   Also Tuesday, U.S. District Judge John Walker reserved decision
on whether to admit an accounting report that Feffer says shows the
Helmsleys are actually owed $681,000 in tax refunds in 1983-85, the
years charged in the indictment.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney James DeVita said the defense gave him a
copy on Monday. He complained that the documents should have been
turned over much earlier under the rules of evidence.
   The judge admonished Feffer for not furnishing the material
earlier. ``To me, it is inexcusable and I can't understand why it
didn't happen,'' he said.
</TEXT>
