<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-GuardianAngels     08-16 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Guardian Angels,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guardian Angels Win Award for Subway Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group formed to promote solutions to social
problems today honored the Guardian Angels for their patrols on the
London subway and said they led authorities to improve security on
the system.
   ``Whatever the government's reservations about this group may be,
they have had a salutary effect on the authorities, who have been
shamed into placing more police on the Underground system as a
result,'' said the citation from the Institute for Social Inventions.
   ``Rigorously self-disciplined, unpaid and imaginatively trained,
they are visibly succeeding not only in New York, but in other
cities,'' it said.
   The Guardian Angels began patrolling the London subway in May,
wearing their trademark T-shirts and red berets. They underwent
three months of training supervised by the organization's American
founder, Curtis Sliwa.
   British police and government officials opposed the Guardian
Angels setting up in London, saying law enforcement should be left
to professionals.
   But after their arrival, the government said it would temporarily
assign an additional 80 police officers to patrol the subway system.
   British Transport Police refused comment on the award.
   The Institute for Social Inventions each year gives out 12 awards
worth a total of $1,500 to groups or individuals who come up with
``new and imaginative ideas to improve the quality of life.''
