<FIRST>r a PM-DrugArrest     08-16 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Arrest,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>DEA Arrests One of Its Own</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVE EPSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decorated U.S. drug agent whose undercover work
goes back to the French Connection days was himself arrested in a
sting by colleagues after he allegedly walked into a setup carrying
62 pounds of cocaine.
   Edward K. O'Brien devised some of the federal Drug Enforcement
Administration's best undercover operations during an 18-year
career, said fellow Agent John J. Coleman, who described himself as
a friend of O'Brien's.
   O'Brien, 44, was arrested late Monday at Logan International
Airport while delivering suitcases filled with cocaine to
informants, authorities said.
   ``This is a very sad, sad moment in drug enforcement,'' Coleman
said Tuesday.
   Coleman said he and O'Brien worked together in southern France
trying to uncover heroin labs in the 1970s.
   ``Those were the hotbeds of activity in the French Connection
days,'' he said.
   Coleman said O'Brien's knowledge of how sting operations worked
made his arrest particularly difficult. To conduct the sting that
netted O'Brien, the DEA used private citizens who cooperated with
the agency, Coleman said.
   ``You're dealing with someone in every respect who would be
knowledgeable of everything,'' Coleman said.
   O'Brien headed the DEA's Springfield office from 1982 to 1988 and
received a special citation from Gov. Michael S. Dukakis in 1984 for
supervising a crackdown on a major cocaine ring in western
Massachusetts.
   Before his arrest O'Brien worked at agency headquarters in
Arlington, Va., helping set up a DEA museum, said spokesman George
Festa. O'Brien has been placed on leave.
   Coleman said O'Brien received the cocaine earlier Monday from an
informant in Miami. O'Brien received $14,000 to transport the drugs
and was expecting to receive another $14,000 on delivery in Boston,
Coleman said.
   O'Brien was charged with possession with intent to distribute
cocaine, and could get 10 years in prison and fines up to $4 million
if convicted, said U.S. Attorney Wayne Budd said.
   O'Brien's brothers Paul, 34, and John were arrested Tuesday and
charged with conspiring to possess cocaine with intent to distribute.
   Edward and John O'Brien, who is from Bourne, Mass., were held
pending a bail hearing Thursday. Paul O'Brien, of Sandwich, Mass.,
was released on $25,000 bail.
   Coleman said that in July, O'Brien, under DEA surveillance,
Miami, obtained about 55 pounds of cocaine and sham cocaine and
brought it to Boston from Miami for $25,000.
</TEXT>
