<FIRST>r i PM-Spain-USJets     08-16 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spain-US Jets,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Military Jets Involved in Near Collision With Airliner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZARAGOZA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four U.S. Air Force jets came dangerously
close to colliding with a Spanish commercial jetliner carrying 50
people, an aviation official said today.
   Antonio Yus, the director of air traffic at Zaragoza's airport,
said the incident occurred the afternoon of Aug. 10 when the U.S.
A-10A Warthog jets were returning to the air base at Zaragoza and
the Aviaco jet was approaching to land.
   The air base and Zaragoza airport share a landing strip.
   The pilot of the DC-9 saw the Warthogs coming at him and had to
climb at 60 degrees, at 2,000 feet per minute, to avoid a crash, Yus
said in an interview with The Associated Press.
   The normal climbing speed is 500 feet per minute.
   ``It was clearly a dangerous situation because neither the
airline pilot nor air traffic controllers had been informed of the
jets' flight, and they were not in contact with the tower,'' Yus
said.
   The American jets, NATO anti-tank aircraft normally stationed in
West Germany, were at the Zaragoza base to practice firing at nearby
Bardenas Real training range, he said.
   A U.S. Air Force spokesman, Lt. Cliff Atkinson, said the air
force was preparing a statement on the incident.
</TEXT>
