<HEAD>Principal Who Cut Own Job is Reinstated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A principal who cut his own job so
teachers would not be laid off is back at work after an outpouring
of support from townspeople.
   A cheer rattled the rafters of Town Hall after the school
committee voted unanimously Monday night to reinstate Norman Najimy.
   The committee said it did not know where it would get the $43,000
to pay Najimy, who has been teaching for 37 years. But members said
they were bowing to the overwhelming desire of parents and others in
the Berkshire town of 1,600.
   Four weeks earlier, Najimy, whose country elementary school of
200 pupils was cited for excellence by the U.S. Education
Department, had suggested the board eliminate his job to protect
teachers from sharp budget cuts.
   ``The parents have been just wonderful and so have the senior
citizens. It's a myth they don't care about the schools. Richmond's
senior citizens were ready to make cash donations out of their own
pockets,'' Najimy said Tuesday.
   ``If there is one lesson I have learned from all this, it is that
there are a lot of people in this country that believe in education
and were eager for someone to speak out about reordering our
national priorities.''
   Najimy had received job offers from schools all over the country.
   Even Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, whose cuts in state aid have been
blamed for much of the town's financial problems, telephoned.
   ``He asked if there was any way he could help get me back into
the job,'' Najimy said. ``I told him that my concern was not that,
but what we are going to do to preserve good schools.''
</TEXT>
