<FIRST>u i PM-SouthAfrica     08-16 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Apartheid Leaders Announce Major Opposition Unity Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-apartheid leaders today
announced plans for a national conference aimed at unifying
opposition to the government. They called on foreign countries to
ensure the meeting was not banned.
   Organizers of the ``historic conference'' on Oct. 7 include
Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu, black miners' union leader Cyril
Ramaphosa, and Albertina Sisulu, co-president of the banned United
Democratic Front coalition.
   ``The aim of the conference will be to map out the most
effective, shortest path to the ending of oppression and
exploitation, and the creation of a democratic country,'' the
organizers said in a statement.
   ``We expect the conference to be attended by thousands of
delegates from all walks of life, representing millions of poeple.''
   A similar broad-based, anti-apartheid conference was scheduled to
be held in Cape Town last year but was banned by the government.
   Predicting another ban this year, the conference organizers said,
``We are alerting the international community to monitor the actions
of the regime in relation to this gathering of the people.''
   They said officials from the United States, Soviet Union, Western
Europe and southern Africa had been briefed about the conference, to
be held in Johannesburg.
   ``The current mood of our people is such that we believe they
will defy any attempt by the state to prevent the conference from
going ahead,'' the organizers said.
   They noted that a nationwide defiance campaign already was under
way, challenging various segregation laws as the Sept. 6
parliamentary elections approach.
   The organizers said any group would be welcome to join the
conference which shared support for seven basic demands.
   These were a one-person, one-vote political system, lifting of
the state of emergency, unconditional release of political
prisoners, unbanning of political organizations, freedom of
association and expression, press freedom, and a ``living wage'' for
all workers.
   The announcement made no mention of the forced resignation of
P.W. Botha this week and the appointment of F.W. de Klerk, leader of
the governing National Party, as acting president.
   De Klerk has promised a five-year program to bring the black
majority into the political structure, but activists say his
proposal is too vague and too slow.
   The specific issue which triggered Botha's split with his Cabinet
was the planned trip by de Klerk on Aug. 28 to confer with Zambia's
President Kenneth Kaunda, a vehement critic of apartheid.
   Tom Langley, foreign affairs spokesman for the far-right
Conservative Party, today described Kaunda as ``an outspoken enemy
of South Africa'' and urged de Klerk to call off the meeting.
   If the meeting takes place, Langley said, de Klerk should ``give
a public assurance that no internal affairs will be discussed.''
   Langley said Kaunda in effect would be representing the African
National Congress guerrilla movement, which wages a bombing and
sabotage campaign aimed at toppling the National Party government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
