<DOCNO> AP890816-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1109EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Iran-Parliament     08-16 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Parliament,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Karrubi Voted New Parliament Speaker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's Parliament today elected as its new
speaker Mehdi Karrubi, a middle-ranking clergyman who has been
instrumental in trying to export Iran's Islamic revolution to other
Moslem countries.
   State-run Tehran Radio, monitored in Nicosia, said 145 of the 243
deputies at today's vote supported Karrubi.
   Karrubi, who has long experience in the Majlis, or Parliament,
was appointed deputy speaker last year to Hashemi Rafsanjani, who
had served as speaker since 1980.
   Rafsanjani resigned Tuesday to take over the presidency, which he
won with 94.5 percent of the vote last month.
   As head of the Pilgrimage Bureau, Karrubi has been a leader in
the movement to spread Iran's fundamentalist revolution.
   In 1987, he led his country's pilgrims to Mecca, where Saudi
troops were called in to quell political rioting allegedly
instigated by the Iranian contingent. The violence left 400 pilgrims
dead, mostly Iranians.
   At an anti-Saudi demonstration this year, Karrubi said the 1987
riots were ``a calculated plot designed by American and Israeli
advisers to prevent the spread of the Islamic revolution to other
parts of the world.''
   Karrubi is believed to have considerable influence with radicals
in the Iranian hierarchy, headed by Interior Minister Ali Akbar
Mohtashemi, who oppose moves to improve ties to the West.
   Karrubi also had good relations with the late Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, who appointed him head of the Martyrs' Foundation, a vast
conglomerate that controls more than 700 enterprises.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
