<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   08-16 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0737</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout
the country:
   Aug. 15
   Portland (Maine) Press Herald on the death of Congressman Mickey
Leland:
   The death of Rep. Mickey Leland of Texas while on a famine-relief
trip tp Ethiopia reminds us of the nobler side of politics.
   Congress is not held in particularly high esteem these days.
Still, many individual members of Congress _ perhaps even most _ are
highly principled, dedicated, hard-working public servants who are
genuinely interested in serving the public good.
   Leland was one of them, although not all of his colleagues or his
constituents were captivated by his driving humanitarianism. He was
sometimes criticized for his obsession with bringing relief to the
starving people of Africa; his detractors said he should have
concentrated on the hungry people of the United States instead.
   But Leland had an answer for that: ``I am as much a citizen of
this world as I am of my country,'' he said. ``To hell with those
people who are critical of what I am able to do to help save
people's lives. I don't mean to sound hokey but I grew up on a
Christian ethic which says we are supposed to help the least of our
brothers.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 15
   St. Louis Post-Dispatch on the death of Congressman Mickey Leland:
   Mickey Leland, 44, died last week in the country that was birth
to his mission as a politician.
   The U.S. Representative from Houston had always fought on behalf
of people in need, but in 1983 he toured Ethiopia and was shaken by
the desolation and deprivation he saw visited upon the people there.
   When he returned to Washington, ... Leland began his crusade to
create a select committee on hunger. That committee, with ... Leland
at its head, has been the conscience of the Hill _ not just
concerning famine relief for Ethiopia, but the plight of the poor in
the United States. ...
   The impetus behind the formation of the hunger committee was a
trip to an Ethopian refugee camp, where a little girl died before
his eyes from the hunger that consumed her. It was on his fifth trip
to such refugee camps that his plane crashed.
   The tributes to him from President Bush, from House Speaker
Thomas Foley, from activist Jesse Jackson go properly to one who, in
... Foley's words, ``represented the best in compassion that we as a
nation possess.''
   Real tribute to Mickey Leland will come as such leaders work to
ensure that a commitment to feed the hungry is always a top priority
of this land of plenty.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 13
   The Union Leader, Manchester, N.H., on quiet diplomacy and the
hostages:
   President Bush, who could have restored not only American faith
and world respect but given himself just a tremendous boost as our
new leader, seems to have hunkered down to threats against American
hostages in the Middle East.
   He talks of long, quiet ``diplomacy'' to get back some _ not all
_ of our hostages.
   This is wrong, terribly wrong. We cannot allow the remaining
hostages (most of whom knew the risks they were taking to stay in
Lebanon) to handcuff our foreign policy. Nor can we allow our
enemies to continue to kill Americans with impunity.
   We must not, but we fear that is what is happening.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 13
   The Providence (R.I.) Sunday Journal on Collin Powell as JCS
chairman:
   If the Senate concurs, and there really isn't the slightest doubt
that it will, Gen. Colin Powell, 52, will soon become the youngest
man to be named chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, as well as
the first black ever to hold that powerful position.
   President Bush has chosen well.
   Not that the selection was all that surprising. ...
   Powell made his mark under the Reagan administration, so he is
well known and highly respected by ... Bush and the members of his
national security team.
   And so while the naming of ... Powell will understandably be
accorded added symbolic significance because he is black and
relatively young, this should not draw attention from the main
point: The nominee is eminently suited for the job.
</TEXT>
