<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   08-16 0798</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0824</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: his job.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 14
   The Arizona Daily Star, Tucson, Ariz., on babies without brains:
   In a civilized society, doctors trying to save life cannot be
allowed to profane the dying. Yet that's just what the medical
community would do if it comes out on the wrong side of the debate
involving brain-absent babies and organ transplants.
   Although the debate involves a small number of potential organ
donors _ fewer than 200 brain-absent babies are born alive in the
United States each year _ it has far-reaching implications.
   By the time an anencephalic baby dies, usually within a few days
of birth, its organs often have deteriorated to the point that they
are not usable for transplant purposes. Those who want to speed up
the process, by declaring living children dead and maintaining them
on life-support systems until their organs are needed, would do a
terrible thing.
   A disturbing report appeared recently in the New England Journal
of Medicine. Authors argued that anencephalic babies are not alive,
and that doctors should therefore be allowed to ignore the usual
standards of brain death in order to use such an infant's organs
earlier.
   The suggestion is chilling.
   What Dr. Robert D. Truog of Harvard Medical School and
bioethicist John C. Fletcher of the University of Virginia propose
is the creation of an artificially sustained class of ever-ready
organ donors. ...
   Currently, most transplant centers will not traffic in
anencephalic organs, because such donors are not considered dead
under standards set by either states or medical societies. With
today's technological advances, however, doctors have the ability to
blur the fine line between life and death, morality and immorality.
   Those who misuse brain-absent babies leap across that line.
   The precedent such transplants would set would be devastating. If
doctors succeed in keeping brain-absent babies alive on machines
until their organs are needed, it's not much of a jump for them to
consider the same fate for comatose adults, or anyone else the
medical community has given up on.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 11
   St. Cloud (Minn.) Times on 900-number phone calls:
   The phone bill arrives. It's unusually high. Ah, hah. Someone's
been making calls to those 900 numbers _ the ones promising all
sorts of exciting messages.
   Unfortunately, children comprise a big share of the market for
services offered by a 900 number. Who else would respond to a sleazy
television commercial advertising the chance to talk to Mickey
Mouse, the Tooth Fairy or horror movie king Freddy Krueger?
   Action for Children's Television, the national advocacy
organization for quality young people's programming, has filed a
petition with the Federal Trade Commission demanding that AT&amp;T
provide consumer safeguards on special-charge 900 numbers.
   The group wants the company forced to give refunds to parents who
get surprise phone bills for 900 calls by their children _ at least
the first one _ and requests AT&amp;T offer blocking of 900 calls on
their phone line if requested. They also want bills itemized to
clearly indicate services directed to children aged 12 and under.
   It's a good theory on the surface.
   And in reality, it's not feasible to expect one company, which
only provides the lines and billing for the information providers,
to excuse all bills claimed to be made by a child. If that were the
case, a precedent would be set for erasing responsibility for what
our children do. It would also teach children the lesson that they
can get away with irresponsible behavior because their parents will
get them out of it.
   Temptations such as 900 recordings are here to stay, and until
blocking is available on all telephone companies, large phone bills
are a danger. Parents must teach their children to make responsible
choices and take the consequences when they don't.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 11
   The Register-Guard, Eugene, Ore., on airline deregulation:
   The current financial state of America's domestic airline
industry can be summed up in four words: profits up, bargains down.
   The relatively few airlines that made it through the
post-deregulation chaos are reporting record profits. The good news
for the industry, however, translates into bad news for travelers.
Fares are up _ by more than 15 percent in the past year. And
discounts, frequent flier programs and other enticements ... are
fewer and more restrictive.
   More disturbing, however, is the fact that only eight airlines _
United, American, Delta, Northwest, TWA, USAIR, Pan Am and
Continental _ control more than 90 percent of the domestic market.
That concentration of market control is the antithesis of what
deregulation was supposed to be all about. ...
   The free market has worked and the fittest have survived, but at
what cost to those companies that died along the way and those
cities that no longer have air service?
</TEXT>
