<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   08-16 0778</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0809</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: air service?</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 11
   Herald Times Reporter, Manitowoc-Two Rivers, Wis., on the atomic
bomb:
   Almost without notice two significant anniversaries passed last
week.
   Sunday was the 44th anniversary of the first atomic bomb attack
on Japan carried out by a U.S. B-29 bomber. And Wednesday was the
same for the second and the world's last nuclear attack to date.
   It was Aug. 6, 1945, that about 140,000 people lost their lives
in a firestorm that engulfed the Japanese city of Hiroshima. Three
days later nearly half that amount lost their lives at Nagasaki.
   Those two days did as much as anything in this century to change
the course of the world. While the attacks resulted in a swift end
to the U.S.'s Pacific involvement in World War II, it was the
beginning of the atomic age, the nuclear age. And it was the
beginning of awareness of the power of nuclear energy and the horror
of it if used improperly.
   Every day the world lives in fear of a nuclear holocaust. Will it
ever happen? No one can know, but the sheer thought of it should
never leave the minds of those who are in global decision-making
positions.
   And just remembering Hiroshima and Nagasaki should make everyone
strive for peace every day of their lives.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 12
   The Hutchinson (Kan.) News on the HUD scandal:
   Not even solid, conservative columnist James J. Kilpatrick can
stand the stench seeping from the records of Ronald Reagan's
Department of Housing and Urban Development.
   ``The more one learns of this rotten affair, the worse it gets,''
Kilpatrick wrote ... in his nationally syndicated column, ``A
Conservative View.''
   He called the scandal shameful, and correctly put the blame
squarely where it belongs. Ronald Reagan and his handpicked aide,
Samuel Pierce, did absolutely nothing in all those years to close
the spigots of money going to those who were looting the Treasury.
   Kilpatrick's discovery of Reaganesque incompetence is better late
than never, and it is a discovery that should be embraced promptly
by others who have tolerated as merely unique a management style
that was essentially a non-management effort. ...
   Kilpatrick could go one step further in his assignation of blame
and accountability. Beyond Reagan and Pierce, the blame lies with
those who embraced the virtues of illusions, jokes and old movie
scripts to take their minds off the difficult business of running a
decent government.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 14
   Seattle Post-Intelligencer on the embryo fight:
   In London's Observer in 1950, the British clergyman Lord Fisher
declared that ``the only thing that science has done for man in the
last 100 years is to create for him fresh moral problems.'' Almost
40 years later, science continues to create such problems.
   Take the embryo imbroglio in ... Tennessee. There, in a bizarre
custody dispute, a divorcing couple is arguing over control of what
one lawyer has called the ``preborn children'' of their union.
   The estranged wife, Mary Sue Davis, had been unable to carry
naturally fertilized embryos to term. A fertility program at a
Knoxville hospital artificially fertilized eggs taken from the
woman's body with sperm of her now estranged husband, Junior Lewis
Davis.
   The result was nine fertilized human eggs. Two subsequently were
implanted in the woman's womb with no success. Then came the
divorce, and the dispute over the remaining seven fertilized eggs.
...
   While we may not completely share ... Fisher's morose evaluation
of scientific accomplishment, we cannot debate his assertion that
scientific progress has shoved us up against more and more
complicated if not more difficult moral dilemmas. Progress has not
only blessed us with the wonders of medical science but with its
horrors, too.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 9
   The Times, Trenton, N.J., on the investigation into the crash
Flight 103:
   President Bush's decision to reverse himself and create a study
commission on the Flight 103 disaster was just plain common sense.
   Flight 103 exploded last Dec. 23 over Lockerbie, Scotland,
killing 270 people.
   Among other things, the commission will look into allegations
that airline security was lax and that the lack of uniform
counterterrorism policy increased the chances for such disaster.
   Families of the victims have questioned why the United States
failed to make public the terrorist threats against the airline,
especially since some U.S. officials abroad were advised against
taking the flight.
   It's time to resolve the questions concerning the disaster, and
it's time to separate fact from rumor. It's also time to look for
better ways to protect air travelers. The commission is the right
way to achieve these goals. ...
   Bush was right to change his mind.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Editorial Rdp</NOTE>
