<FIRST>r a PM-ThumbsDown     08-16 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thumbs Down,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Journalists Denounce NBC, Buchanan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Association of Black Journalists
gave its ``Thumbs Down Awards'' for negative portrayals of blacks to
NBC News and syndicated columnist Patrick Buchanan.
   The NABJ objected to what it said was the derisive tone and
terminology used by NBC anchorman Tom Brokaw and reporter Robert
Hager in a 1988 obituary on Max Robinson, the first black network TV
anchorman and a founder of NABJ. Robinson died of AIDS.
   In a letter to the network, two NABJ officials said Brokaw's
introduction ``insinuated that Mr. Robinson contracted AIDS in a
decadent, shameful fashion, though there were no facts reported to
support that presumption.''
   ``We reviewed our piece on Max Robinson and we remain convinced
that it was fair and objective,'' said Peggy Hubble, speaking for
NBC News.
   Buchanan got the dubious designation in the print category for a
May 8 column calling for a coalition ``to liberate black America
from a worse enemy than the Klan ever was, the black criminal.''
   Buchanan wrote that ``if a young black, or young white male,
sidles up to ask directions, and one of the two is a robber, rapist
or killer, the odds are at least 11-to-1 that it is the black male.''
   Lisa Dallos, a spokeswoman for Buchanan, said Tuesday that she
would try to relay the news to him, but he had not commented by
today.
   The Thumbs Down awards were issued Tuesday and NABJ was notifying
recipients by letter.
   ``Mr. Buchanan uses too broad a brush to stereotype all black
men,'' said Gayle Pollard of the Los Angeles Times, NABJ vice
president for print.
   ``Crime is not a function of race; it is a function of economic
advantage or disadvantage,'' said NABJ president DeWayne Wickham of
the Gannett News Service. He said such depictions ``serve to fuel
the engines of racism in this country.''
</TEXT>
