<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1212EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Quayle-Poll 2ndLd-Writethru a0555 08-16 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle-Poll, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0555,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Says He's Off to Good Start</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs of Fitzwater reax after 4th graf, Asked how</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle said today a new poll
shows ``I'm off to a very good start,'' even though it found that
more than half the people surveyed thought he isn't qualified to be
president.
   The Washington Post-ABC News poll found nearly a 2-1 approval
ratio for the way Quayle is handling the vice presidency. However,
52 percent of those questioned said he wasn't qualified to take over
the presidency.
   ``I am very delighted to see that by a ratio of 2-1 Americans
think I am doing a good job as vice president,'' Quayle said today
at a photo session. ``I feel I'm off to a very good start.''
   Asked how he explained the 52 percent figure, Quayle said, ``I
tend to accentuate the positive and I have a very positive ratio of
support with the American people of 2-1 on how I am doing the job.
They approve of the way I am doing the job. That's good news for
me.''
   Presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater dismissed the
poll's findings. ``We think the public does have confidence in the
vice president,'' he told reporters en route to Miami with President
Bush.
   Fitzwater said Bush ``thinks the vice president is doing an
excellent job; he has outstanding qualities in many areas.'' Asked
whether he had faith in public opinion polls, the spokesman said:
``I never believe in the bad ones.''
   Quayle talked about the poll as he posed for pictures with Han
Xu, who is returning to Beijing after serving as ambassador to the
United States.
   Quayle called it a ``final courtesy call'' and said the two would
have ``a frank discussion.''
   ``Clearly I will be giving him messages that he can take back to
his government,'' the vice president said.
   David Beckwith, the vice president's press secretary, said Quayle
raised concerns about human rights and ``what China will have to do
to improve its relations with the United States'' in the aftermath
of the bloody crackdown on pro-democracy forces.
   The poll on Quayle's performance was conducted by telephone with
1,022 people Aug. 4-8, about a year after George Bush selected
Quayle as his running mate. It showed little change from earlier
polls that indicated a widespread lack of confidence in Quayle's
qualifications to take over the government in an emergency.
   Fifty-two percent said Quayle wouldn't be qualified to take over
as president. Thirty-eight percent said Quayle is qualified to be
president and the rest offered no opinion.
   Forty-three percent said Bush should seect another running mate
if he runs for re-election.
   But the respondents had less trouble with Quayle in his current
job: 43 percent approved of the way he's handling the vice
presidency, 22 percent disapproved and 34 percent said they didn't
know.
   The results were similar to national polls taken last spring that
showed slightly more than half of those responding said Quayle was
not qualified to be president.
   Quayle told the Post that his continued poor showing in polls is
a result of last year's campaign in which Democrats attacked him as
unprepared to step into the Oval Office.
   ``I don't think people have the knowledge and information about
me they do about the president,'' Quayle said.
   White House Chief of Staff John Sununu said Bush was unconcerned
with such poll results.
   ``The president likes the job he is doing,'' Sununu said.
   The results were sharply different for party members. Two-thirds
of those who said they were Republicans approved of the job Quayle
is doing, while only a third of the Democrats approved.
   The poll found 43 percent believe Bush made a mistake in
selecting Quayle, while 47 percent said it was not a mistake and the
rest had no opinion.
   The survey has a margin of error of 3.5 percentage points.
</TEXT>
