<FIRST>u a PM-SCLCConvention 1stLd-Writethru a0450 08-16 0786</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SCLC Convention, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0450,0805</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Group Turns Toward its Political Agenda</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with early discussions; PICKS
UP 6th graf pvs, ``I know ...'; INSERTS two grafs after 14th graf pvs,
``I was ...' with background on Lucas appointment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Speakers at a civil rights convention today
stressed the need for black participation in both the Republican and
Democratic parties and urged voters to watch for persecution of
black elected officials.
   ``We don't want our folks singled out,'' said Spiver Gordon, a
commissioner in Greene County, Ala., said at the annual convention
of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference. ``We are concerned
where there seems to be a special effort to prosecute
African-American elected officials.''
   Gordon, a national SCLC board member, was convicted of vote fraud
in a Justice Department probe of election irregularities in Alabama,
but the conviction was overturned on appeal. Gordon had contended he
was the victim of selective prosecution based on race, a charge
denied by the Justice Department.
   Emmanuel Cleaver, vice mayor of Kansas City, Mo., noted the
absence of Republican National Committee chairman Lee Atwater after
the Bush administration's apparent courtship of black voters with
Tuesday's appearance of Vice President Dan Quayle. Atwater had been
scheduled to appear.
   ``The Republican Party just has not offered the kind of
sensitivity needed if we are going to participate,'' Cleaver said.
   At the same time, Cleaver cautioned Democrats not to assume
blacks are satisfied with the party. ``We have been bludgeoned
politically by Democrats,'' he said. He added it will be
``infinitely easier'' for blacks to progress in both parties.
   Civil rights leaders have been meeting with the Bush
administration over what they say is a trend toward overturning
civil rights victories with Supreme Court rulings.
   The group has said it intends to decide a course of action for
``reversing the assault on affirmative action and minority set-aside
programs.'' The theme for this year's conference is ``Rebirth of
Hope In The Struggle.''
   Quayle on Tuesday told participants that recent Supreme Court
rulings against affirmative action and minority set-asides do not
reflect Bush's attitude toward their cause.
   The crowd of about 500 board members and staffers applauded him
enthusiastically at times and seemed cool at others. Quayle said
afterward he had ``no expectations going in there'' but felt good
about the response.
   ``I know there are concerns among you,'' Quayle said. ``We will
make America open and make America equal for all.
   ``We may differ from time to time as to the course this nation
must travel, but we do not differ on the ultimate destination.''
   Later, Quayle declined to comment on what those differences were.
Civil rights leaders have said they are focusing upon the Bush
administration's actions, not its words.
   In introducing Quayle, SCLC President Joseph Lowery urged Bush to
``put some music'' behind the discussions.
   ``Let me take this opportunity to provide some music,'' Quayle
said. ``This president has, in fact, gone beyond the rhetoric. ...
Yes, we can do better and yes, we will do better.
   ``This is not rhetoric. This is not politics. This, my friends,
is the right thing to do.''
   Quayle referred to last week's appointment of Gen. Colin Powell
as chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff and said the SCLC ``can
rest assured we will not be deterred'' in reaching out to appoint
blacks in the administration.
   ``I feel confident we can work together and build an America we
all envision,'' Quayle said.``There is no place for the Klan,
neo-Nazis, skinheads or any other racist group in our country.''
   ``I was surprised to hear about some of the things he knew about
the movement,'' Lowery had said after a recent meeting with Quayle.
``He was tossing out names and places and asking a lot of
questions.''
   Lowery was one of the few civil rights leaders to support the
Bush administration's failed nomination of William Lucas as the
nation's top civil rights enforcer. Others had charged that the
black Republican lacked experience.
   The nomination was killed two weeks ago in the Senate Judiciary
Committee; Bush subsequently appointed Lucas to another position in
the Justice Department that didn't require Senate confirmation.
   The convention, which runs through Friday, is being held in
Atlanta for the first time since Lowery took over the leadership in
1977.
   Martin Luther King Jr., with Lowery and the Revs. Ralph Abernathy
and Fred Shuttlesworth, founded the SCLC in 1957 in Montgomery,
Ala., to carry on the movement started with bus boycotts in that
city.
   It has long been considered the grass-roots arm of the movement,
working on issues such as homelessness, unemployment and economic
empowerment.
</TEXT>
