<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Rightist     08-16 0151</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Rightist,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pistol-Wielding Rightist Protests Taxing Emperor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man protesting the taxation of Japan's new emperor
fired a pistol shot and briefly barricaded himself inside a tax
office near the Imperial Palace on Wednesday afternoon before
surrendering, police said.
   The man, who identified himself as Kazuyoshi Fududa, a platoon
leader of a rightist group, went to the Kojimachi Tax Office,
shouted, ``Taxing the imperial family is not forgivable!'' and fired
one shot, police said. Nobody was hurt.
   Fududa, 31, forced his way to a second-floor room and barricaded
himself in with office furniture before surrendering to police about
40 minutes later, police officials said.
   Investigators were questioning him, they said.
   Emperor Akihito has paid an inheritance tax of $3.06 million on
$12.9 million in personal wealth inherited from his father,
Hirohito, who died in January.
   Rightist groups in Japan have expressed opposition to taxing the
imperial family.
</TEXT>
