<DOCNO> AP890816-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1240EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-CamilleRemembered Bjt   08-16 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Camille Remembered, Bjt,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>Killer Hurricane Ravaged Mississippi Gulf Coast 20 Years Ago</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY64</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASS CHRISTIAN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time has erased most of the scars
left along the Mississippi Gulf beachfronts by Hurricane Camille,
but for survivors the horrors of the 1969 killer are as vivid as
yesterday.
   ``We live with the memory of Camille,'' said Civil Defense
Director Wade Guice. ``There's another Camille out there somewhere
and I just pray it doesn't come in here.''
   The most powerful storm in U.S. history, Camille danced along the
coast for days before roaring ashore in Mississippi the night of
Aug. 17, 1969. Camille's 200 mph winds smashed everything in its
path and it unleashed a wall of water as high as 30 feet.
   Two hundred forty-eight people died, including 141 in Mississippi.
   Structures that had withstood major hurricanes of the past,
including Betsy in 1965, vanished under Camille's tidal wave. Large
ships were tossed onto dry land, with a 200-foot barge coming to
rest across what was left of U.S. 90, at the time the major traffic
artery along the coast.
   ``I flew down there the next morning and it was incredible,''
recalled U.S. Rep. G.V. ``Sonny'' Montgomery, D-Miss. ``I had seen
total destruction in battle zones in Europe and in Vietnam, but
nothing like this.''
   ``There were no cars, no people moving. It was very
frightening,'' he said.
   In the weeks following Camille, National Guardsmen patrolled
streets to prevent looting. Volunteers from across the country
arrived to help remove debris and provide food and shelter for
hundreds of homeless.
   Losses from the storm, which also caused extensive damage along
coastal Louisiana and Alabama and spawned scores of tornadoes
inland, was placed at $1.5 billion, with most of the loss coming in
Mississippi, Guice said.
   Camille destroyed 6,744 homes and damaged 46,709 more, while
destroying or damaging 746 businesses.
   Harbor facilities have been rebuilt and the sand beach reclaimed
over the years, but there are reminders _ driveways leading to empty
lots, twisted, aging trees and even a souvenir shop built next to a
shrimp boat that rests near where it was blown ashore.
   ``When a hurricane gets in the Gulf you see people looking out
over the Mississippi Sound, wondering if another Camille is
coming,'' said George Byrd, harbor master at the Gulfport small
craft harbor. ``Before that storm people always felt things wouldn't
be as bad as the weather people were predicting. Well, Camille
changed all that.''
   The storm left another calling card for shrimpers along the coast
as receding waters sucked debris back into the Gulf.
   ``There were lots of shrimp out here after Camille but you
couldn't drag but about 10 minutes before you would have to pull the
nets in to clean out the referigerators, car batteries, pilings and
things like that,'' said Mike Sevel, who as a 16-year-old at the
time worked with his father aboard their shrimp boat.
   ``We even had `zippers' on our nets so they could be opened
quickly to dump the debris.''
   Jacqueline Hines and her husband had ridden out hurricanes for
more than 50 years and saw no reason to abandon their beachfront
home in Gulfport despite the urging of friends and neighbors.
   Within a few hours, the two were clinging for life, 30 feet up a
television antenna, watching as gulf waters crushed their home and
covered the two-story house next door.
   ``How can one forget a night like that?'' asked Mrs. Hines, 79.
``Everything we had, things that can never be replaced, are gone
forever.''
   Mrs. Hines recalls the violent wind that pinned her head back for
hours, the blinding flashes of lightning in a night with no stars or
street lights, and the hours she hung onto her unconscious husband
in a sea of debris.
   The two, suffering broken ribs and other injuries, were rescued
the next morning.
   ``There are so many stories of horror from that storm,'' said
Guice, who has headed Harrison County's emergency agency for 28
years. ``There was the apartment complex where at least 24 people
drowned during a hurricane party and an Episcopal Church built in
1849 where 13 members of one family died.''
   ``I keep thinking about the loss of life, if only those people
had responded to our evacuation call.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890816-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1258EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Economy Bjt   08-16 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economy, Bjt,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Reports More Evidence of `Soft Landing'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industrial production rose for the first time
in three months in July while housing starts continued to rebound,
the government said Wednesday in reports seen as further evidence a
recession will be avoided this year.
   The Federal Reserve said its industrial production index last
month stood at 141.7 percent of its 1977 base, compared with 141.4
percent in June.
   The 0.2 percent increase in July followed consecutive declines of
0.1 percent in May and June. Overall production was up 2.7 percent
over a year ago.
   In another report, the Commerce Department said housing starts
rose 0.8 percent in July after posting declines for four consecutive
months through May. They started to rebound with an 8.5 percent
increase in June.
   At the same time, the Fed reported that the factory operating
rate remained steady at 83.6 percent in July, continuing to ease
inflationary pressures.
   ``It's consistent with the soft-landing scenario, modest growth
without tipping into a recession,'' Thomas Holloway, senior
economist at the Mortgage Bankers Association of America, said of
the reports.
   David Berson, chief economist for the Federal National Mortgage
Association, said that several months of stagnant production at
manufacturing plants had been causing fears of a recession.
   But Wednesday's report ``indicates that manufacturing may have
bottomed out and we're seeing some moderate strength that should
help with the soft-landing scenario,'' he said.
   The Fed has been walking a fine line between keeping interest
rates high enough to cool inflationary pressures without slowing
growth so much that the economy slides into a recession. It began
letting rates drop in June as inflation seemed to lessen.
   ``The July gain mainly reflected a rebound in the output of total
materials as well as continued strength in business equipment
excluding motor vehicles,'' the central bank said Wednesday in
releasing the industrial production report.
   ``In contrast, automobile and truck production fell sharply, and
output of construction supplies, on balance, remained weak,'' it
said.
   Production at manufacturing plants making both durable and
non-durable goods rose 0.2 percent after remaining flat in May and
June. That was a 3.3 percent increase from July 1988.
   Output at mines and oil wells rose 0.3 percent following a
revised 1.1 percent decline in June caused in part by a coal strike.
The July output was 3.5 percent lower than a year ago.
   Production at utilities, reflecting increased use of air
conditioning, rose 0.8 percent in July, following a 1.3 percent
decline in June. Utility production was up 1.2 percent from July
1988.
   William D. Kelleher, manager of the Community Resources Section
of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, said he was encouraged by the
housing report.
   ``This month's rebound in housing starts shows that the country's
economic expansion is continuing,'' he said.
   The July level of construction totaled 1.43 million units at a
seasonally adjusted annual rate, up from 1.41 million in June.
   Single-family construction rose 6.3 percent last month while
apartment starts fell 1.2 percent. Analysts said the multifamily
drop was a natural falloff from an unusually steep 32.9 percent
increase in June.
   The operating rate at the nation's factories remained at 83.6
percent last month after declining 0.3 percentage point in June, the
Fed reported. The rate hit a 10-year high of 84.3 percent last
December. Last month's operating rate was down from 83.7 percent a
year earlier.
   The closer U.S. industry gets to full operating capacity, the
greater difficulty it has producing enough to meet demand, leading
to shortages and price increases. Analysts generally consider an
operating rate of 85 percent or above as an indication of
inflationary pressures.
   The operating rate at manufacturing plants slipped 0.1 percentage
point to 83.9 percent, down from June's 84 percent. That rate had
peaked at 84.7 percent in January.
   The rate at factories producing durable goods, big-ticket items
expected to last more than three years, edged down 0.3 percentage
point from 82.6 percent in June. The rate at factories producing
non-durable goods rose to 86.2 percent, compared with 86.1 percent
in June.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
