<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     08-16 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Accuses North of Using Border for Propaganda</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government accused communist North
Korea on Wednesday of using the border for propaganda purposes by
allowing a student to return to South Korea across the Demilitarized
Zone after an illegal visit.
   Unification Minister Lee Hong-koo said, ``These provocative acts
could endanger a truce on the Korean peninsula.''
   Im Su-kyong, 20, was arrested when she crossed the border Tuesday
at the Panmunjom peace village. She had gone to North Korea six
weeks ago.
   Government officials said Miss Im was being questioned Wednesday
by the Agency for National Security Planning at a hospital. She was
taken there for a medical checkup because she recently went on a
five-day hunger strike.
   Officials said she would be released from the hospital soon into
the intelligence agency's custody. The agency has said it intends to
arrest everyone who participated in sponsoring or financing the trip.
   South Korea forbids unauthorized trips to North Korea and insists
that all dialogue on reunification be conducted through official
channels. The peninsula has been divided since 1945.
   Miss Im went to the North for an international youth festival as
a symbol of reunification and has said she returned across the
heavily guarded border to dramatize the issue. Her supporters call
her ``the flower of unification.''
   She crossed the border with the Rev. Moon Gyu-hyun, a Roman
Catholic priest who traveled to North Korea to escort her home.
   They were arrested immediately. The government has said they
would be charged with violating security laws by making unauthorized
trips to an enemy country and committing other acts against state.
   Dissidents and radical students said they would conduct a
nationwide campaign against any punishment for Miss Im and Moon.
   Newspapers and political columnists predicted the trip and its
aftermath would accelerate the deterioration of relations and lead
to another crackdown on dissent in South Korea.
   Lee, the unification minister, said North Korea ``committed an
intentional provocation'' by permitting the crossing ``through
Panmunjom despite our repeated warnings.''
   The U.S.-led United Nations Command, a signatory to the 1953
armistice agreement that ended the three-year Korean war, said a
formal protest would be filed with North Korea. The U.N. Command and
South Korea say the crossing violated the agreement.
   No peace treaty has been signed, so the nations remain
technically at war. Talks to reduce tensions have been held
sporadically, with little progress.
</TEXT>
