<FIRST>r w AM-AIDS-Protesters 1stLd-Writethru a0580 08-16 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Protesters, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0580,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Demonstrators Take Stage to Protest `Platitudes'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4 grafs new material for last 2 grafs pvs. Diana Diana
in 3rd graf is CQ</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Participants in a government-sponsored
conference on AIDS and minorities disrupted a morning session
Wednesday to demand discussion about women's issues and other topics
they said were getting short shrift.
   About two dozen people attending the National Conference on HIV
Infection and AIDS Among Racial and Ethnic Populations took over the
stage during the main morning event and, when the speaker finished,
commandeered the microphone.
   ``I'm not getting what I need out of this conference,'' Diana
Diana, executive director of the South Carolina AIDS Education
Network Inc., told the audience of several hundred. ``I need
information on drugs. I need information on other people's
programs.''
   Diana and others complained that women's issues _ including low
representation in drug-testing trials _ weren't being adequately
addressed and that there wasn't enough opportunity for people
actually running programs in communities to share their experiences
with each other.
   A man among the demonstrators said people like himself who have
AIDS were being shortchanged by the lack of discussion about
life-prolonging treatments that are becoming available and about
access to clinical trials in which new therapies are being tested.
   ``I'm sorry we had to act up, and I'm sorry that some of you
don't like the fact that we're acting up, but some of us are
fighting for our lives,'' he said.
   ``It's platitudes, empty rhetoric we're hearing,'' Gail Harris of
the Center for Women's Policy Studies in Washington explained after
the demonstration that, with much support from the audience,
disrupted the conference for about half an hour.
   During the interruption, a woman who had been translating into
sign language for the deaf continued signing, and often the audience
broke in with enthusiastic applause for the protesters, some of whom
are members of the activist group AIDS Coalition to Unleash Power,
known as ACT UP.
   At first, some in the audience argued with the action of the
demonstrators, with one person in the audience calling the protest
``an act of incredible disrespect'' because the demonstrators began
mobilizing at the front of the room while a native American was
speaking from the podium.
   But another person in the audience rose to say:
   ``I think what they're doing is encouraging. ... There are too
many of us that have felt a lot of anger and it's about time someone
did something.''
   Another person in the audience drew hearty applause when she said:
   ``We are letting ourselves be divided _ that's not what we're
here about. We need to move on and work together.''
   The moderator of the session agreed to give the protesters five
minutes, which stretched to about 20 minutes, for individuals among
them to state their concerns.
   The four-day conference, which ends Thursday, is being sponsored
by the Department of Health and Human Services.
   Jim Brown, a spokesman for the Public Health Service, which is
part of HHS, defended the agenda for the conference.
   ``In putting together this conference, we worked with all groups
involved in the fight against AIDS ... about what should be
discussed,'' he said.
   ``The list of sessions covers the complete spectrum _ from legal
and discrimination issues to drug abuse, helping people with AIDS,
volunteerism _ the whole spectrum.''
</TEXT>
