<FIRST>r a PM-PopcornCaper     08-16 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Popcorn Caper,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trail Of Popcorn Leads Officers to Young Vandals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CACTUS, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A trail of popcorn led authorities to four
young vandals who broke into a school, trashed several rooms and
tried to take the sting out of any future punishment by stealing the
school's paddles.
   The boys splattered finger paint, tore up a bean bag chair and
scattered its contents and poured bleach, vinegar and cooking oil on
floors.
   They also spilled unpopped popcorn, and that was their undoing,
Sheriff Ted Montgomery said Tuesday.
   Montgomery said a boy at Cactus Elementary School inquired the
day before the burglary last week if there would be paddling during
the upcoming school year.
   ``He was told yes, there would be,'' the sheriff said. ``Part of
the things that were missing were all of the paddles in the school.''
   Authorities later found popcorn kernels around the home of the
boy who had popped the corporal punishment question.
   ``Apparently the youngest one had gotten cooking oil all over
him,'' the sheriff said. ``The popcorn had stuck to the youngest
one's clothes.''
   School officials had no estimate of the damage.
   The boys were turned over to their parents and the case was
referred to juvenile authorities.
   Cactus is about 50 miles north of Amarillo in the Texas Panhandle.
</TEXT>
