<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1339EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CalifPrimary     08-16 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Calif Primary,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Californians Want Earlier Presidential Primary, Poll Finds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Californians want a bigger say in who
becomes president of the United States and strongly support
advancing the date of the state's primary, a poll found.
   A California Poll released Tuesday found that residents favor
moving up the primary, now scheduled in June, unless the move costs
a lot of money.
   Democrats and Republicans alike favor the proposal by 61 percent
to 21 percent, according to the poll.
   But the estimated $40 million added expenses was a definite
turn-off, with only 14 percent backing such a plan when the estimate
was included.
   The last time California voters cast decisive votes in a
presidential bid was in 1972, when George McGovern beat Hubert
Humphrey in the California primary to grab the Demoratic nomination.
   Measures have been introduced in the Legislature to move the
primary to February, March or April.
   ``It would create at the top of the calendar an instant winnowing
device for both parties and establish early on who are credible
national candidates,'' said Michael McCurry, a spokesman for the
Democratic National Committee.
   Those who dislike the current primary system say the state has
virtually no voice in selection of presidential nominees, even
though it sends the largest groups of delegates to party conventions.
   The California Poll was based on interviews with 754 registered
voters and was conducted by telephone from July 12 to July 23. The
results have a margin of error of plus or minus 3.7 percent.
</TEXT>
