<FIRST>r a PM-CellblockInmates     08-16 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cellblock Inmates,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Juveniles and Adults Housed in Same Cellblock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Juveniles held at the city's House of
Correction have been put in the same cellblock as adults, and in at
least one case, in the same cell, The Philadelphia Inquirer reported
today.
   Prison officials disputed the report, which the newspaper said
was based on court records, a retired prison chaplain and a source.
   State and federal law allow juveniles who have been certified to
stand trial as adults to be housed in an institution with adults.
   But the practice may violate a Philadelphia Common Pleas Court
consent decree requiring that juveniles at the House of Correction
be kept separate from adults there, the newspaper said.
   The Inquirer said that according to prison records, one day last
month, three adults were held in a part of the cellblock that prison
officials said is for juveniles.
   The records also showed that an adult was housed in the same cell
as a juvenile who had been at the House of Correction for one day.
That adult had been charged with aggravated assault and endangering
the welfare of children.
   Prison officials said as many as 27 juveniles at a time have been
held in a wing of the adult prison over the past nine months because
of overcrowding at the city's youth detention center.
   But Maj. Thomas Costello, who oversees city juvenile facilities,
and Maj. Wilhelmina Speach, a deputy warden at the House of
Correction, told The Inquirer that adults and juveniles have not
been held in the same area.
</TEXT>
