<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh-Bomb     08-16 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh-Bomb,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes at Opposition Leader's Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded at a public meeting
Wednesday where opposition leader Sheik Hasina had been speaking,
but there were no injuries, police said.
   Two men carrying explosives were arrested, said police offcials
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   On Friday, assailants opened fire on Ms. Hasina's house in Dhaka
and hurled a grenade at it. There were no injuries in that attack.
   Ms. Hasina is a vocal critic of president Hussain Mohammed Ershad
and is the daughter of Bangladesh's first president, the late Sheik
Mujibur Rahman.
   Rahman, his wife, three of his children and three other family
members were killed in a military coup Aug. 15, 1975. Ms. Hasina was
out of the country at the time.
   Farooqur Rahman, one of the leaders of the coup, leads the
Freedom Party. Since the 1975 coup, Bangladesh has had eight
presidents, all of whom were installed through military intervention.
   Ershad, an army general, seized power in 1982. He resigned in
1986 and then won the presidency in elections that Ms. Hasina and
other opposition leaders call fraudulent.
   Wednesday's blast came soon after Ms. Hasina finished speaking at
an outdoor public meeting organized in the capital by her Awami
League party. The explosion occurred about 200 yards from speaker's
podium, witnesses said.
</TEXT>
