<HEAD>Jurors Agree to Resume Deliberations After Panel Member's Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with jury resuming deliberations;
PICKS UP graf pvs, `The alternate ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jury in the 6-month-old ``Night Stalker''
murder trial resumed deliberations today after the foreman reported
that panel had ``put behind them'' the slaying of a juror and the
suicide of her boyfriend.
   The ``Night Stalker'' defendant, Richard Ramirez, a drifter
charged with 13 murders, shouted out an objection and an obscenity
when the judge indicated he would allow the panel to return to its
task with an alternate member.
   Superior Court Judge Michael Tynan ignored Ramirez's comment and
rejected a defense request for at least a week's delay in
deliberations to allow jurors to recover from their grief. There was
no request for mistrial.
   Earlier, the judge called into the courtroom the jury foreman and
asked whether jurors were able to proceed in light of the slaying of
Phyllis Singletary by her boyfriend.
   ``I feel it's somewhat tranquil,'' said the foreman, Felipe
Rodriguez. ``Everyone appears to have put it behind them.''
   The judge then summoned all of the jurors and told them: ``We
must get on with the task that life has given us. No matter how
deepl.
   The alternate who was chosen to replace Ms. Singletary appeared
upset when her name was called and sat trembling in her chair rather
than moving into the jury box.
   Tynan said he understood the jury's emotions: ``I think we have
all been terribly affected.''
   But he said the killing was unrelated to the Ramirez case and
expressed the hope that panelists could complete their job.
   ``I do not mean to be callous,'' he said, ``but we have business
to do.''
   The judge said he would allow jurors to attend Ms. Singletary's
funeral arrangements if the services are in Los Angeles. Ms.
Singletary, a Pacific Bell employee, is originally from El Paso,
Texas, where her family lives.
</TEXT>
