<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Refugees     08-16 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Refugees,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budapest Mayor OKs Tents for East German Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities gave permission Wednesday
for a tent community to shelter hundreds of East Germans seeking to
emigrate to the West, while the international dispute surrounding
them escalated.
   East Germany told a West German official that activities by
Bonn's embassy in Budapest violate international law.
   Bonn government spokesman Herbert Schmuelling said the East
German Foreign Ministry called in Franz Bertele, the head of West
Germany's Permanent Representation, to lodge the protest.
Schmuelling said it was rejected by Bertele.
   The tents approved by Hungarian authorities are intended for use
by some of the hundreds of East Germans who left their makeshift
camp outside the West German consulate Tuesday and moved to a nearby
Roman Catholic Church.
   A crush of passport and asylum requests by East Germans has
overwhelmed West German diplomats in this city and East Berlin. The
embassy and consulate were closed in Budapest Monday, and the West
German mission shut down in East Berlin on Aug. 8.
   Csilla von Boeselager, president of the Hungarian Maltese Caritas
humanitarian group, said about 20 military tents would be set up
Thursday on a campground in a working-class district in the Pest
part of Budapest.
   The tents, sent with cots by the West German Red Cross, can
shelter up to 350 people, the state news agency MTI said.
   Some East Germans began round-the-clock vigils outside the
consulate last month in hopes of getting help to emigrate to West
Germany. Most have now illegally overstayed their visas to visit
Hungary.
   Bonn government officials said Monday that 141 adults and 40
children remained holed up inside the West German Embassy despite
the closure to the public. They have demanded asylum in the compound.
   Hundreds more East Germans are reported to have gone underground
rather than return to their Communist homeland. Some refugees say
they fear persecution if they go home, and others say they seek a
better life in the West.
   East Germany and Hungary are allies in the Soviet-led Warsaw
Pact. Hungarian officials have privately acknowledged that East
German attempts to use Hungary as a springboard to the West are
leading to tensions between their country and East Germany.
   Officially, Hungary insists the affair is strictly between Bonn
and Berlin. But a West German diplomat said Wednesday the Hungarians
are doing what they can to help the East Germans' efforts to
emigrate.
   ``The tent city OK comes officially from the mayor of Budapest,
but it's clear that the (Hungarian) interior and foreign ministries
were consulted,'' said the diplomat, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The estimated 300 East Germans who left the consulate crowded the
lawns of a Roman Catholic church Tuesday evening, but Mrs.
Boeselager said Hungarian families took in two thirds of them
Wednesday.
   On Wednesday, many of those remaining at the church lined up at
folding wooden tables as Hungarian Red Cross volunteers doled out
peas and pork. Some refugees ate sitting on the lawn, while others
filled out questionnaires given them by West German diplomats.
   The refugees say the diplomats have been processing requests and
handing out passports on church grounds.
   Several East Germans say they will stay in Hungary as long as it
takes to gain passage to the West.
   ``People at home are so bitter about the stagnation there,'' said
a 30-year old woman while her two boys, aged 6 and 3, crouched at
her feet eating their food. ``We'll do anything to make it over the
border.''
   The wave of refugees developed in Hungary after its liberal
communist authorities removed border fences with Austria in May.
Hungarian border guards, however, have not let East Germans pass
with papers obtained in Budapest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
