<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marylou Whitney, unofficial hostess
for the social whirl surrounding the annual August thoroughbred
races here, is recovering from injuries suffered in the line of duty.
   Whitney, wife of businessman and horsebreeder C.V. Whitney,
cracked a rib, blackened an eye and opened a gash on her forehead
that required 13 stitches when she fell while dancing Friday during
the annual ``Evening in Old Saratoga'' ball.
   Whitney was taken to Saratoga Hospital, where she seemed more
concerned about the blood on her yellow and turquoise taffeta Arnold
Scaasi gown than with her injuries. Renee Walsh, a friend from
Chicago, was dispatched to a convenience store while still in her
ball gown to buy seltzer water as an aid to removing the blood.
   ``We had our priorities straight,'' Whitney said, back in action
Sunday night at another gala event. ``Take care of the dress first,
then dress my head.''
   Craig Foster, a New York City plastic surgeon and Whitney friend,
will check the gash in three to four months to see if plastic
surgery is necessary. In the meantime, Whitney said she's going on
safari.
   ``It's much more dangerous to go to an evening in Saratoga than
it is to go off on safari and sleep in a tent with wild animals all
around you,'' she said.
</TEXT>
