<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Another bump is in the path of Pete Rose, the
Cincinnati Reds manager already under fire over allegations he
gambled on baseball.
   Rose and umpire Joe West shoved each other after the manager came
to the defense of second baseman Ron Oester, who also exchanged
bumps with West. It was the second time in 13 months that Rose has
bumped an umpire.
   The argument Tuesday night came during the Reds' 5-2 loss to the
Chicago Cubs. It started over a call by the plate umpire.
   Rose is under investigation by Baseball Commissioner A. Bartlett
Giamatti for allegedly betting on Reds game. A federal court order
prevents Giamatti from conducting a disciplinary hearing on the
charges.
   National League President Bill White will review the bumping as a
separate matter and will not take into account the gambling probe,
spokeswoman Katy Feeney said Wednesday.
   White is gathering reports from the umpires and will review any
available videotapes, she said.
   Last season, Rose was suspended for 30 days and fined $10,000 by
then-NL President Giamatti for bumping umpire Dave Pallone.
   ``You saw what they did when I pushed Pallone last year,'' Rose
said. ``Let's see what happens now.''
   ``We have no comment, nothing to say,'' said Jerry Crawford,
chief of the umpire crew.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soul singer Mica Paris says visitors
would be surprised by the diversity of music she plays at home.
   ``I love rock, pop, soul and R&amp;B (rhythm and blues), and because
I like so many types of music, I try to put all types of music in my
material,'' she said in a telephone interview from her apartment in
New York City prior to a scheduled Nashville performance Wednesday
night.
   ``If you came to my house, you'd say, `Like, Mica, what are you
doing with these records?'' she said.
   Paris, 20, became popular in England last year. Her debut album
in the United States was released in April.
   She said she knew at an early age that she wanted to sing.
   ``I'm just one of those people who knew what they wanted to do.
When I was 10 years old, I turned to my grandmother and said I'm
gonna be the first person to buy her a house. And I was.''
