<FIRST>r w AM-NuclearPlant     08-16 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Plant,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Utility Chief Says Nuclear Managers Ignored Warning of Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Managers of a Maryland nuclear plant that has
been called one of the nation's worst ignored warnings as long ago
as three years that complacency was jeopardizing safety, the owner's
chief executive told federal regulators Wednesday.
   George McGowan, chairman of Baltimore Gas &amp; Electric Co., said he
had told supervisors at the Calvert Cliffs plant on Chesapeake Bay
that he saw ``a slippage setting in'' that threatened the plant's
reputation for efficiency and safety.
   ``I'm not so sure they believed what I had to say,'' McGowan told
members of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission, which last December
declared Calvert Cliffs one of the worst-run plants in the country
and stepped up monitoring of its operations.
   The commissioners called in McGowan and the utility's other top
officers to explain how Calvert Cliffs had fallen to the bottom of
the performance pile after long being touted as one of the best-run
and most efficient plants in the nation.
   The plant's sudden fall from grace has raised new questions about
the NRC's ability to detect drops in plant performance levels before
serious accidents occur.
   Both of Calvert Cliffs' nuclear reactors were shut down last May
because of mechanical problems. A series of earlier mishaps at the
plant culminated in the accidental death last September of an
employee who drowned in a water storage tank.
   ``We recognize we have problems _ major problems,'' McGowan told
the commissioners. ``The current state of affairs disturbs me
deeply.''
   He and other utility officials said they were working on a broad
strategy for improving operations, including methods of ensuring
stricter adherence to safety procedures and strengthening plant
management.
</TEXT>
