<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-O'Malley     08-16 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-O'Malley,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Priest Who Inspired Bing Crosby Character in `Going My Way' Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Eugene F. O'Malley, considered the
inspiration for the character of the same name portrayed by Bing
Crosby in the movies ``Going My Way'' and ``The Bells of St.
Mary's,'' has died. He was 87.
   O'Malley, director of the all-male Paulist Choir at Old St.
Mary's Roman Catholic Church for four decades until it was disbanded
in 1967, died Monday of cardiac arrest at the St. Joseph Hospital
and Health Care Center.
   The Chicago-born O'Malley began his lifetime commitment with the
choir in 1912 as a singer. He became director in 1928. Under his
leadership the choir traveled around the country and performed at
the White House.
   It disbanded due to O'Malley's advancing age and retirement, a
decline in applicants and church reform.
   Mass for O'Malley will be sung by the chorale Thursday evening at
Old St. Mary's. He is survived by a sister, Genevieve V. Rudd.
</TEXT>
