<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Israel     08-16 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Israel,0723</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel: No Plans to Intervene, but Cautioning Syria</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel has made clear it does not want to
intervene in Lebanon, but is quietly reminding the Syrians of limits
to how far they can expand their battle with the Christians without
risking retaliation.
   The warnings have been contained in hints by some officials and
repeated public statements calling for worldwide pressure on Syria
to stop the 5-month-old battle
   Uzi Landau, a legislator from Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's
right-wing Likud bloc, said Tuesday the Israelis would warn Syria
``in a quiet way'' about ``red Lines'' that cannot be crossed.
   That same day, Israel's air force sent a warning to Palestinian
guerrillas, some of whom are allied with Syria, by buzzing guerrilla
positions near Sidon in south Lebanon.
   Reporters asked Shamir on Wednesday whether Israel would put
limits on Syrian military action in Lebanon. He replied without
elaboration: ``There are red lines. The red line is the safety of
Israel.''
   Israel has long made clear that its strongest territorial defense
line is drawn at Sidon and the Awali River. The river is 25 miles
north of the border.
   The government also insists the Syrians not threaten Israeli's
freedom to fly reconnaissance over Lebanon or its ability to patrol
the southern Lebanese coast to block guerrilla attacks by sea.
   Most statements by officials have castigated the United Nations
for failing to stop or condemn Syria's bombardment of civilians in
Beirut, which Israel also shelled relentlessly during a 70-day siege
in 1982.
   ``We were sorry to see that the U.N. Security Council was not
ready to do anything of any significance,'' said Foreign Minister
Moshe Arens. ``The Syrians think they can act in this brutal manner
contrary to all the norms and laws of civilized society.''
   At a meeting called by Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar,
the Security Council approved an appeal Tuesday night for a
cease-fire in the Syrian-Christian artillery battle that began five
months ago.
   Analysts say they believe Syria understands how far it can go,
but also pointed to changes in strategy Israel would consider a
threat.
   Mark Heller, a Middle East expert at Tel Aviv University's Jaffee
Center for Strategic Studies, said a Syrian ground buildup could be
dangerous for Israel even if it did not encroach on south Lebanon.
   ``If they bring large formations, air defense systems are part of
these formations,'' he said, and Israel would fear that Syrian
missiles could interfere with its aerial surveillance.
   Syria now has 40,000 soldiers in Lebanon under a 1976
peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League.
   Aharon Levran, a retired brigadier general and independent
military analyst, said Syrian air defense batteries could ``gnaw
away'' at Israel's freedom of action in the air.
   He also said a Syrian victory in Lebanon that upset the balance
of power might force Israel to reconsider its non-intervention
policy.
   ``If Syria ends up with the upper hand, being victorious, this
will be a drastic change in the strategic situation in Lebanon,'' he
said.
   Levran added, however, that he did not believe President Hafez
Assad of Syria would risk possible retaliation from Israel or from
Iraq, which supplies arms to the Christians.
   Assad does not want to ``annihilate'' the Christians, he said,
only to punish the Christian army commander, Gen. Michel Aoun, for
challenging his role as power broker in Lebanon.
   Aoun describes the Syrians as an occupation army and says he is
fighting a ``war of liberation'' to drive them out.
   ``What Assad really wants is Aoun's head,'' Levran said.
   He said involvement in Lebanon has kept Syria too busy to
concentrate on Israeli, and ``it's a blessing for Israel that Syria
will be bogged down deeper and deeper in the Lebanese mud.''
   Israel's unwillingness to intervene stems from its experiences in
the 1982-85 invasion and occupation of Lebanon: 650 soldiers killed,
political disunity at home and harm to Israel's image abroad.
   Finance Minister Shimon Peres, head of the center-left Labor
Party, said on television Wednesday: ``Israel did not get out of
Lebanon in order to return there. ... There is a place for being
worried only if direct Israeli interests are harmed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
