<FIRST>r i AM-Singapore-US     08-16 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Singapore-US,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governing Party's Youth Wing Protests Any U.S. Bases in Singapore</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARI S. MANIAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing party's youth wing on
Wednesday protested Singapore's proposal to allow U.S. military
bases on its territory.
   Singapore's offer, made earlier this month, was seen as a move to
encourage the Philippines to extend the lease on American bases
there. The Philippines asked other countries in the region to share
some of the burden of having U.S. bases.
   Five officials of the youth wing of Malaysia's governing United
Malays National Organization gave their note to the Singapore
diplomats at that country's embassy.
   However, the youth officials and about 20 supporters made no move
to protest at the U.S. Embassy across the street.
   The note accused Singapore of ignoring the concerns of its
neighbors. ``We know it is Singapore's sovereign right to do as she
wants, but how will she like it if Malaysia invites the Soviet Union
to site bases in this country?''
   Some members of the group said they ignored the U.S. Embassy
because the proposal came from Singapore, and Washington has not
said it would accept it.
   Malaysian leaders, including Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad,
also have criticized Singapore for making the proposal. If accepted,
they said, it could destabilize the region.
   Singapore diplomats declined comment on the youth group's
criticism, saying only that the note would be sent to their
government.
   The tensions stem from the opposition of many Filipinos,
including lawmakers, to extend the lease of the six American
installations there. They include the stategically important Clark
Air Base and Subic Bay Naval Base.
   Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., who is touring the Philippines, said
Singapore's offer was helpful and that Washington was also eager to
keep its bases in the Philippines.
   He said, however, if Philippine opponents of the bases win their
battle to block leasing of the bases beyond 1991, Washington will
find other host countries for them.
   ``If they come to the conclusion that it is to the best interest
of the Philippines to permit us to continue using the facilities,
then we will gladly and willingly continue to utilize them,'' he
said.
   He added that the United States would develop ``operative
facilities elsewhere'' in case the Philippines decides to close the
bases.
   Solarz, chairman of the Asian and Pacific affairs subcommittee,
arrived in Manila Wednesday with Rep. Robert Dornan, R-Calif., and
Eni Faleomavaega, a legislator from American Samoa. He met briefly
with President Corazon Aquino but did not say what was discussed.
   Mrs. Aquino has not stated her position on extending the base
agreement.
   The Philippines and United States are expected to begin talks
this year on whether to extend the agreement despite growing
anti-American sentiment. Mrs. Aquino is expected to discuss the
issue during a visit to the United States in November.
   In October 1988, the two countries reached an agreement allowing
the bases to remain until 1991 in return for $962 million in U.S.
military and economic aid over two years. About 40,000 American
troops, civilian workers and military dependents are stationed at
the facilities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
