<DOCNO> AP890816-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1623EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran     08-16 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Revolutionary Hard-liner New Iranian Parliament Speaker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian lawmakers Wednesday elected to the
influential post of parliament speaker a radical anti-Western cleric
who advocates the spread of the Islamic revolution.
   The selection of Hojatoleslam Mehdi Karrubi was seen as a blow to
the new president, Hashemi Rafsanjani, whose so-called pragmatist
faction favors rebuilding relations with the West.
   Parliament has to approve all the president's Cabinet
appointments. As the overseer of the 270-seat parliament, Karrubi
could make or break legislation and curb Rafsanjani's policies.
   State-run Tehran radio monitored in Nicosia said Karrubi won 145
votes among the 243 members of the parliament, called the Majlis,
who attended the session Wednesday.
   Rafsanjani, 54, had been speaker since 1980 but gave up the post
after his election to the presidency July 28. He had pushed for
former Interior Minister Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri to succeed him.
   During his time as speaker, Rafsanjani built the speakership into
a key role.
   Karrubi, a 51-year-old middle-ranking cleric, has been a member
of the Majlis since March 1981 and was elected deputy speaker under
Rafsanjani last year.
   He is a revolutionary hard-liner who frequently was imprisoned
for his clandestine activities during the reign of the late Shah
Mohammad Reza Pahlavi.
   He is allied with Rafsanjani's political rivals, led by the
radical interior minister, Ali Akbar Mohtashemi.
   Karrubi also was close to the late revolutionary leader,
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, who named him head of the Martyrs'
Foundation, a vast conglomerate that controls more than 700
enterprises in Iran.
   As head of Iran's Pilgrimage Bureau, Karrubi was well-placed to
oversee covert operations in the drive to export the Islamic
revolution.
   In 1986, Iranian Revolutionary Guards posing as pilgrims tried to
smuggle explosives and weapons into Saudi Arabia during the annual
pilgrimage to Islam's holiest shrines in Mecca. Most were arrested
and deported.
   The following year, Karrubi led militant Iranian pilgrims to
Mecca, where Saudi troops were called in to quell political rioting
allegedly instigated by the Iranians. More than 400 pilgrims, most
of them Iranians, were killed.
   This year, Karrubi told demonstrators in Tehran the 1987 riots
were ``a calculated plot designed by American and Israeli advisers
to prevent the spread of the Islamic revoution to other parts of the
world.''
   Karrubi's brother, Hassan, was involved with Rafsanjani in secret
arms-for-hostages negotiations in 1985 with then-U.S. National
Security Adviser Robert McFarlane.
   Rafsanjani is expected to take the oath of office Thursday. He
takes over the presidency from Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, who was
elected Iran's religious leader after Khomeini died June 3.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890816-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1624EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SmithPlane     08-16 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smith Plane,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Say Pilot Was Confused Before Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of a plane carrying Rep. Larkin
Smith appeared nervous and even ran the aircraft off a taxiway
shortly before takeoff, officials investigating the fatal crash said
Wednesday.
   The Cessna 177 veered east from its anticipated flight path
before slamming into a 70-foot pine tree in the DeSoto National
Forest Sunday night. Killed were pilot Chuck Vierling, 58, and
Smith, a 45-year-old freshman Republican.
   People who saw Vierling before takeoff ``said he appeared to be
kind of nervous ... like he was concerned about the flight,'' said
Jorge Prellezo, regional director for the National Transportation
Safety Board in Miami.
   ``People at the Hattiesburg airport observed the aircraft taxing
out and said it ran off the paved (taxiway) area and into the grass,
then back onto the paved area, which is kind of strange,'' Prellezo
said in a telephone interview.
   The two were returning from Hattiesburg to their homes in
Gulfport, about 70 miles to the south. The plane wreckage was found
Monday, scattered through tall pines and dense underbrush about 14
miles south of New Augusta.
   William Dowden, an employee of Southeast Aviation, watched
Vierling's single-engine plane both during and after takeoff.
   ``He taxied straight out off the ramp area onto the grass and
when he realized what had happened, he made a 180-degree turn, then
taxied slowly out to the runway,'' Dowden said. ``The taxiways are
lit up with blue lights and what happened struck us as being highly
unusual.''
   Prellezo said there were other questions about the first minutes
of the flight, including why the pilot told controllers that he
would follow the established route along U.S. 49 but instead flew
about nine miles to the east over the DeSoto National Forest.
   ``We will look at every aspect to see why he deviated,'' Prellezo
said.
   While the investigation into the crash continues, residents of
the Mississippi Gulf Coast, where Smith once served as sheriff,
began filing by the congressman's flag-draped casket on Wednesday. A
funeral Mass was scheduled for Thursday.
</TEXT>
