<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-War     08-16 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-War,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Catholic Leader Reminds Germans of Nazi Past</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany's Roman Catholic
leader on Wednesday marked the 50th anniversary of the outbreak of
World War II by reminding his countrymen of the ``heavy burden'' of
their Nazi past.
   Bishop Karl Lehmann, chairman of the West German bishops
conference, also called the Nazi massacre of the Jews
``unparalleled'' in human history.
   On Sept. 1, 1939, Adolf Hitler's troops attacked Poland, touching
off the worldwide conflict that killed more than 50 million people.
During their 12-year dictatorship, the Nazis also killed an
estimated 6 million Jews.
   In his message, Lehmann said later generations are not
responsible for what happened under the Nazis.
   ``But that alone doesn't take care of the question of guilt and
its causes,'' he wrote. ``All in fact are affected by the common
heritage and must carry along this heavy burden in solidarity.''
   ``And what's more, all are responsible for what will become of
our people in the future,'' the 53-year-old bishop wrote in his
message distributed to the news media.
   He blamed the outbreak of the war on the Nazi leaders'
``megalomania,'' third thirst for power, and their ``criminal
contempt of mankind.''
   The bishop also called on West Germans to be on guard against
movements that lead to hatred. The country has been seeing
increasing support for the extreme right, which has blamed
foreigners for many of the nation's troubles.
   Lehmann also singled out the sufferings of the Jews under the
Nazis.
   ``Hitler's profound hatred of Jewish fellow human beings and of
certain minorities determined his actions,'' the bishop said. ``The
genocide of the Jews is unparalleled in human history.''
   West Germany has been the scene of a debate sparked by some
conservative historians who argue that the Nazi killings of the Jews
should be compared to other atrocities in history. Some West Germans
contend those historians are trying to diminish the horror of the
Holocaust.
</TEXT>
