<FIRST>r i AM-Ethiopia-Leland     08-16 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethiopia-Leland,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medics, Equipment Airlifted to Ethiopia to Identify Bodies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Air Force plane carrying
forensic experts, medical equipment and nine coffins arrived
Wednesday to retrieve the bodies of Rep. Mickey Leland and eight
other Americans killed in a plane crash.
   Marine Lt. Col. David Titus said it probably would take five to
seven days to identify the remains. The task was under way in a
makeshift clinic at Addis Ababa's international airport.
   ``Obviously, we wouldn't want to ship an Ethiopian body back to
the states by mistake,'' said one U.S. official, explaining the need
for the medical specialists and their sophisticated equipment.
``Conversely, we wouldn't want to leave an American here.''
   Seven Ethiopians also died in the crash Aug. 7 of the small Twin
Otter plane, which was en route to a refugee camp near the Sudanese
border. The plane slammed into the side of a mountain in bad
weather, killing all aboard.
   Leland, D-Texas, was visiting Ethiopia in his official capacity
as head of the House Select Committee on Hunger.
   As the medical experts arrived, other American military personnel
began leaving.
   On Sunday, when the wreckage of the plane was found, more than
300 U.S. personnel were in Ethiopia taking part in the search.
   Not since 1974, when a military coup brought a Marxist government
to power in Ethiopia, have so many U.S. personnel been in the
country.
   The Ethiopians even permitted an American U-2 reconnaissance
plane, commonly used on spy missions, to participate in the search.
   That cooperation extended into an investigation into the cause of
the crash, being conducted jointly by the Ethiopian Civil Aviation
Authority and U.S. and Canadian experts.
   Members of the National Transportation Safety Board and its
Canadian counterpart and representatives of the Boeing and Pratt &amp;
Whitney companies flew to the crash site Wednesday to begin the
investigation.
   Boeing and Pratt &amp; Whitney provided the aircraft's frame and the
engines for Leland's chartered Twin Otter, which was manufactured in
a Canadian plant.
   A memorial service for Leland was scheduled Saturday in Houston.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Secretary of
Health and Human Services Louis Sullivan and White House personnel
director Chase Untermeyer would represent the president at the
service.
</TEXT>
