<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Strikes 1stLd-Writethru   08-16 0840</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Strikes, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0606,0861</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Government Rules Law that Sparked Strikes Violates Constitution</HEAD>
<HEAD>SUBS 5 grafs for grafs 8-11 pvs, `But the...' to UPDATE with justice
minister's comment, session televised. Pickup 12th pvs, `On Aug....'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and the Kremlin
leadership on Wednesday rejected as unconstitutional a new Estonian
law that denies some Russian residents of the Balitic republic the
right to vote.
   They called it a violation of human rights.
   However, the Supreme Soviet Presidium, the government's top
executive body, has apparently sought to avoid a contest of wills
with Estonian leaders over the law, which has touched off an
8-day-old protest strike by tens of thousands of ethnic Russians who
live in the tiny Baltic republic.
   Instead, the Presidium said that by Oct. 1, Estonia's government
would present the republic's legislature with proposals to bring the
law into line with the Soviet Constitution, the Tass news agency
reported. That seemed to indicate agreement on both sides to avert a
crisis.
   Leaders in the republic of 1.6 million people, which declared its
sovereignty in November, have rejected attempts by Moscow-based
authorities to annul their laws, but both sides have avoided
bringing matters to a head.
   Estonian President Arnold Ruutel met with the Presidium in the
Kremlin Wednesday and explained the reasons that led to adoption of
the election law, Tass said. It was not clear whether he agreed it
should be revised.
   Ethnic Estonians have called the more-restrictive law a necessity
to ensure they maintain political control in their ethnic homeland
and are not overwhelmed by an influx of ethnic Russians and Soviet
outsiders lured by Estonia's higher living standards.
   But the Presidium found that the law's restrictions, which
Justice Minister Veniamin Yakovlev said constitute the Soviet
Union's first residency requirements for voting and holding office,
``violate human rights .. including in the International Covenant on
Human Rights,'' Tass said.
   The law limits the right to vote and hold office to long-term
residents.
   Among diplomatic commitments entered into by the Soviets that are
violated by the law is a Covenent guarantee that ``each citizen
should have the right and possibility to vote without any
discrimination and without groundless restrictions,'' the Presidium
said.
   ``The Soviet Constitution, its demands of equality of rights of
citizens and equality of citizens before the law, must be observed
unconditionally _ there is no other way,'' said Vice President
Anatoly I. Lukyanov, a Gorbachev protege, who chaired the meeting.
   Excerpts of the session were shown by state television.
Gorbachev, the Presidium's chairman, did not take part, but Tass
said he signed the decree at the Kremlin, giving it his personal
stamp of approval. The Soviet leader has been rumored to be on his
customary August vacation.
   The Aug. 8 decision of Estonia's Supreme Soviet parliament to
limit the right of suffrage and office-holding ignited a strike that
continued Wednesday. Strike committee member Vasily Maximov said by
telephone from Estonia's capital, Tallinn, that more than 20,000
workers have walked off the job, shutting down 51 factories and
enterprises.
   Official Soviet media have said the strike in one of the
country's most economically advanced republics has cost the national
economy millions of rubles.
   More than 2,000 loaded freight cars are sitting idle and dock
workers at Tallinn's two ports also have joined the walkout, Tass
reported.
   The government newspaper Izvestia said Wednesday the Estonian
government had annulled its own Aug. 10 decree that had ordered an
immediate end to the strike, but which stiffened strikers'
resistance instead.
   Protest leaders said the decision, which they called an attempt
to appease them, would have no effect.
   ``Our demands are political, not economic,'' said Maximov. ``We
are fighting for our political rights.''
   Leaders of the strike, which began the day after the more
restrictive election law was adopted, say the measure
disenfranchises many ethnic Russians and other recent arrivals in
the republic. Of Estonia's total population, 65 percent are ethnic
Estonians and 28 percent are ethnic Russians.
   While the Presidium was in session, a commission of Soviet
parliamentarians toured Estonian factories hit by the strike and
spoke with workers, said Mikhail Lysenko, another strike committee
member.
   The panel of legislators met Tuesday night with the strike
committee, Lysenko said from Tallinn.
   Under the new election law, residents of Estonia must live in the
same district for at least two years or anywhere in Estonia for a
total of five years to be able to vote. Candidates for elective
office must have lived in the same spot for five years or in Estonia
for 10 years.
   By declaring the law unconstitutional, the Presidium again was
taking issue with the republic's claim of ``sovereignty'' proclaimed
in November by Estonia's Supreme Soviet, which said the
independent-minded republic could set its own policy in all fields
except foreign policy and defense.
   Moscow authorities pronounced that concept invalid, but the
Estonian parliament has stood by its vote. This year, Estonian
lawmakers also declared Estonian the republic's official language
and approved limited private property.
</TEXT>
