<FIRST>r w AM-PhilippinesDebt     08-16 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines Debt,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banks, Philippines Agree on Debt Package</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators for the Philippines and bank
creditors announced tentative agreement Wednesday on a new debt
package, allowing the Bush administration to claim a second victory
for its program to reduce the debt burden being carried by the Third
World.
   The Philippines will receive new money in addition to a partial
reduction in its $28 billion debt burden, about half of which is
owed to commercial banks.
   The Philippines agreement follows an accord reached last month
with Mexico, the developing world's second largest debtor with $108
billion in loans.
   The Bush administration hailed the Philippines pact as evidence
that its initiative to reduce the $1.3 trillion Third World debt
burden was bearing fruit. Private economists, however, were less
enthusiastic, saying the amount of actual debt reduction was likely
to be modest both for the Philippines and Mexico.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady, who was briefed on the details
of the debt plan Wednesday by top Philippine negotiators, predicted
that it would ``promote significant debt reduction while also
providing new money.''
   Brady on March 10 unveiled the administration's new approach to
Third World debt. The effort seeks to get commercial banks to
voluntarily forgive a portion of the loans they hold in return for
guarantees from the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank
that the reduced debt would be repaid.
   In the Mexican agreement, banks were given the choice of reducing
interest or principle on the old debt or lending new money.
   The same option of reducing old debt or supplying new money will
apply for the Philippines, officials said. They stressed that the
exact amounts of new money and debt relief will not be known until
the commercial banks holding the debt make their individual
decisions on which option to take.
   Philippine negotiators, who had been seeking new bank loans of as
much as $1.7 billion, expressed happiness with the outcome of the
discussions, which were held in New York.
   Jose Fernandez, the Philippine central bank governor who led his
country's negotiating team, said that the combined effect of the
debt reduction and an improving economy would eventually ``bring
about the end of the debt problem for the Philippines.''
   Mexico and the Philippines were considered two of the best
candidates for the Brady debt-relief plan. Discussions with two
other leading candidates, Costa Rica and Venezuela, are currently
stalled.
   Private economists said that the Brady initiative was still a
long way from its goal of reducing the pool of commercial bank debt
by 20 percent for the world's 39 most heavily indebted nations.
   ``This is an incremental change rather than an explosive
change,'' said Richard Feinberg, head of the Overseas Development
Council, a research group specializing in developing countries. ``It
would be a mistake to argue that there is great momentum behind debt
relief.''
   Cynthia Latta, an economist with DRI-McGraw Hill, said that the
debt relief in the case of both Mexico and the Philippines was
likely to be modest as long as the packages remained voluntary on
the part of the banks.
   ``You need a coordinated effort and some type of enforcement
mechanism that says everybody has to write off a certain portion of
the debt,'' she said. ``If you are just piling new loans on old
loans with little actual debt relief, all you have bought is more
time.''
   David L. Pflug, senior vice president of Manufacturers Hanover
Trust Co. and the leader of the bank negotiating team, said that the
options of granting debt relief or providing new lending would
appeal to two separate categories of banks: ``those that wish to
exit from the process as opposed to those that have determined to
maintain their credit relationships in the country.''
   Both sides predicted that a final agreement on all outstanding
issues with the Philippines would be reached in September.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
