<FIRST>u i AM-Czechoslovakia 1stLd-Writethru   08-16 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0638,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissident Urges Caution on Prague Spring Invasion Anniversary</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS one grafs to UPDATE with Czechoslovak reaction. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident Czechoslovak playwright Vaclav
Havel urged his countrymen to refrain from street protests marking
the 1968 Soviet-led invasion because such rallies may spur a harsh
crackdown by authorities.
   Monday is the anniversary of the Aug. 21, 1968, invasion that
crushed the ``Prague Spring'' reforms that briefly liberalized Czech
society.
   In a statement dated Aug. 14 and released Wednesday by the
London-based emigre publishers Palach Press, Havel said he could
understand that Czechoslovaks might believe street protests are the
only way to vent frustrations.
   But he added, ``I personally believe there is no point in
resorting predominantly or exclusively to this method of protest now
... when authorities are waiting exactly for this type of action in
order to be able to strike hard to paralyze people's democratization
for a long time to come.''
   Havel instead urged citizens to sign the petition known as ``A
Few Sentences,'' which has garnered an estimated 15,000 signatures
since it was first distributed in late June.
   The petition demands democratic reforms and negotiations with
Communist authorities. It has come under fierce attack in the
state-run media and from party leaders who have rejected the sort of
political reforms occurring in Poland, Hungary and the Soviet Union.
   Protests during last year's anniversary failed to nudge the
government closer to reform but resulted in at least three petitions
for democratic change and an increased activism among dissidents.
   This year, authorities have warned they won't tolerate
disturbances and will do what is necessary to maintain public order.
   Czechslovakia's official Human Rights Committee appealed to
citizens to avert street violence on the anniversary, Prague
newspapers reported Wednesday.
   The committee was established on Dec. 9, 1988, in an apparent
move to offset the rising wave of dissident protest, but activists
say it lacks the courage to speak out against police brutality.
   ``Having the experience of January, we express our anxiety over
the possible manifestations of demagoguery, general nihilism or
violence in the forthcoming days,'' the Human Rights Committee's
appeal warned.
   The statement referred to protests that broke out in January
marking the 20th anniversary of the death of Jan Palach, who set
himself on fire to protest the 1968 invasion.
   Havel was arrested during one such protest and was jailed for
four months. Several dissidents have been harassed in advance of the
anniversary. Dissidents Jan Carnogursky and Miroslav Kusy were
detained in the Slovak capital of Bratislava on Monday, apparently
in connection with the ``Few Sentences'' petition.
   Two weeks ago, Havel was detained twice in two days and warned to
stay out of Prague.
   Last week, six independent Czechoslovak human rights groups
called for two minutes of silence at 5 p.m. on Aug. 21.
   Havel, 52, appeared to encourage his fellow citizens to be
optimistic that change is coming.
   ``I am firmly convinced that a thorough revision of the official
view of the August 1968 invasion of Czechoslovakia is irrevocably
drawing near,'' Havel wrote.
   Havel cited Friday's statement by a Hungarian official that the
invasion was ``essentially wrong,'' and a Polish Senate resolution
condemning the Warsaw Pact invasion.
   On Wednesday, Hungary's ruling communists distanced themselves
even further from the 1968 invasion.
   In a statement carried by the official MTI news agency, the
ruling Politburo of the Hungarian Socialist Workers Party said the
party's ``present leadership ... does not concur with the 1968
military intervention in Czechoslovakia.''
   The Czechoslovak state news agency criticized the Hungarian
statement as helping ``Czechoslovak and foreign anti-socialist
forces. They, incited by reactionary circles of the West, want, in
contradiction with the historic truth, to misuse the events of 1968
against restructuring and democratization inh Czechoslovakia.''
</TEXT>
