<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1858EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BlastedTown     08-16 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Blasted Town,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Mining Company Vows to Leave Tuscarora Alone But Continue Mining</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUSCARORA, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This 1870 mining boomtown that now is home
to just a few people got something of a reprieve from a company
digging an open pit gold mine that was intended to swallow half the
historic community.
   ``Horizon affirms today that it has no desire to mine its way
through a century of history of Tuscarora,'' John Watson, president
of Horizon Gold Shares, told a public hearing Tuesday.
   Watson said the company, which originally wanted to expand its
open pit into part of Tuscarora, will leave the main town alone,
including three sites for which residents are seeking protected
historic status.
   ``I state publicly that Horizon Gold will not invoke Nevada's
eminent domain statute to mine within the original town site area,''
said Watson, adding that trailers outside of town could be moved,
however.
   Watson's statements came during a public hearing held by the Elko
County Commission to discuss giving historic status to an old
rooming house, a Masonic lodge building and the town cemetery in
this flyspeck on the map 250 miles northeast of Reno.
   The designation is sought by some dozen full-time and another
dozen part-time Tuscarora residents trying to block Horizon's
efforts to expand its 2{-year-old mining operation to get at ore
reserves near and below town.
   Dennis Parks, a town leader who has lived in Tuscarora since 1966
when he started a pottery school in the old rooming house, said he
was wary of the Denver-based mining company's promise to leave town
residents alone.
   He questioned why Horizon still plans to go ahead with its
lawsuit to prove that the company through its century-old mining
claims owns the town and that residents only have surface rights.
   Watson said the lawsuit, filed Friday in Elko County, is needed
to settle once and for all the issue of who owns the land in the
historic town built after gold and silver were discovered in the
late 1860s.
   ``There are 125 years of confusing and often conflicting
transactions that have given Horizon concern as well,'' Watson said.
   Some 80 people attended the 1{-hour-long public hearing in
Tuscarora, and 19 spoke in favor of designating the three historic
sites in the town.
   Only Watson opposed the status, saying the law specifically says
that an historic designation shouldn't be declared just ``to hamper
mining.''
   The commissioners took no immediate action on the issue and set
another meeting for Sept. 20 to discuss the proposal.
   Horizon employs about 50 people to work at the open pit mine 52
miles north of Elko. The company has invested $8 million so far in
working the pit, now about 400-by-800 feet and 150 feet deep.
   At its 1870s peak, Tuscarora had 4,000 residents and a
1,000-strong Chinatown, the largest Chinese population in the West
at the time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
