<FIRST>r w AM-US-Nicaragua     08-16 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Nicaragua,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Calls for Release of Nicaraguan Political Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration on Wednesday welcomed
the release of 29 political prisoners by Nicaragua but condemned
that nation's government for continuing to imprison more than 6,000
people for their politics.
   ``This step is long overdue,'' said State Department spokesman
Richard Boucher.
   ``We urge the Sandinistas to release all political prisoners,
including the 6,000 political prisoners they still hold, and the
remaining 39 National Guardsmen who have been imprisoned since 1979
in violation of the Sandinistas' commitments ... to free them,'' he
said.
   Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega on Tuesday announced the
release of 29 peasant farmers jailed for alleged
counter-revolutionary activities and said his government would
decide the fates of an additional 1,200 political prisoners by early
September.
   The gesture appeared designed to encourage anti-government
guerrillas to lay down their arms in the wake of an agreement among
Central American presidents to disband U.S.-backed Contra rebels
based in Honduras. The agreement calls for the demobilization this
fall so long as Managua moves toward democratic reform.
   The State Department spokesman said ``the release of political
prisoners is always a welcome development.'' But he said Nicaragua,
by continuing to hold political prisoners, was violating an
agreement reached two years ago among Central American presidents.
   ``The continuing imprisonment of political prisioners in
Nicaragua is a violation of the Esquipulas Agreement, which required
signatories to issue decrees of amnesty, which I quote, `shall
establish all the provisions to guarantee the inviolability of life,
freedom in all its forms, property and the security of the persons
to whom such decrees apply,''' said Boucher.
</TEXT>
