<FIRST>r w AM-Crash-Compensation     08-16 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crash-Compensation,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skinner Asks Action on Air Accident Treaty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner called
Wednesday for the Senate to move quickly to to ratify a 14-year-old
treaty that would increase compensation for victims of international
air accidents, saying action is long overdue.
   In a letter to the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, Skinner
said the bombing last December of Pan American World Airways Flight
103 ``serves to highlight the gross injustices that exist'' because
current treaty provisions limit compensation to $75,000.
   The Senate has wrestled with the compensation question for more
than a decade.
   In 1975, the United States signed the so-called Montreal
Protocols to the Warsaw Convention which would allow an increase in
compensation for international air accidents by establishing
supplemental compensation plans.
   While the Foreign Relations Committee twice has recommended the
Montreal Protocols be ratified, the Senate has failed to do so
because critics objected that proposed plans still did not provide
for enough compensation to international air travelers.
   Last year the Transportation Department offered a revised
supplemental compensation plan. It cast aside the proposed maximum
compensation of $317,000 and proposed an essentially unlimited
recovery plan per passenger which would be subject only to an
overall limit of $500 million per accident.
   The awards would come from a special fund established through a
$5 per passenger fee on roundtrip tickets for international air
travel.
   But the Senate never held hearings on the proposal before
adjourning.
   In a letter to Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the
Foreign Relations Committee, Skinner asked that hearings be
scheduled as soon as possible on the revised compensation package
and that the full Senate act swiftly after that to ratify the
protocols.
   ``I urge that your committee take the necessary action to bring
an end to this longstanding inequity for international air
passengers,'' wrote Skinner.
   Congress has recessed until after Labor Day and a secretary in
Pell's office said the senator was not in Washington. Staff aides to
Pell and on the committee could not be reached Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
