<FIRST>r a AM-NightStalker     08-16 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Night Stalker,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disrupted Deliberations Resume After Juror's Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The disrupted deliberations in the ``Night
Stalker'' murder trial resumed Wednesday after the foreman said
jurors had ``put behind them'' the murder of a juror.
   Richard Ramirez, the drifter charged with 13 murders and 30 other
felonies, shouted out an objection when the judge indicated he would
allow the panel to return to its task with an alternate replacing
the dead juror.
   ``I have an objection,'' shouted Ramirez, using an obscenity.
   Defense attorney Ray G. Clark told the judge: ``I believe a cloud
hangs over the jury now, a cloud of sadness.'' He asked that
deliberations be suspended for a week.
   Defense attorneys said outside court they feared that the jurors,
grief-stricken over the killing of Phyllis Singletary by her
boyfriend, who then committed suicide, might vent their anger on
Ramirez.
   ``He's the only target they have,'' Clark said.
   Superior Court Judge Michael Tynan, ignoring Ramirez's outburst,
overruled Clark's motions after interviewing the jury foreman.
   Asked about the atmosphere in the jury room a day after panelists
learned of their colleague's violent death, foreman Felipe Rodriguez
said, ``I feel it's somewhat tranquil. ... Everyone appears to have
put it behind them.''
   The judge then summoned all the jurors and told them to remember
that the killing of Ms. Singletary, found shot on Monday, had no
relation to the trial.
   ``Please understand that none of this had anything to do with
whether Mr. Ramirez is guilty or innocent of these charges,'' he
told the jurors.
   ``We must get on with the task that life has given us,'' he told
them.``No matter how deeply you feel about her death, it is in no
way connected to the case of Richard Ramirez.''
   Ramirez, 29, is charged with 13 counts of murder and 30 other
felonies. Prosecutors allege that Ramirez is the devil-worshipping
``Night Stalker'' who raped, robbed and murdered victims in a 1985
rampage that terrorized Southern California.
   Some jurors wept Tuesday when they were told about the death of
Ms. Singletary, 30, who had sat beside them in the trial for the
past year and had deliberated with them for 13 days.
   The alternate who was chosen to replace the dead juror was
distraught at first. But by Wednesday she appeared calm as she sat
in Ms. Singletary's seat in the jury box.
   Tynan informed jurors that Ms. Singletary's live-in boyfriend,
James Cecil Melton, 51, had committed suicide on Tuesday, leaving a
note admitting he had killed her over a domestic dispute.
   The deliberations have been troubled since last week when another
juror had to be replaced by an alternate for sleeping during
deliberations. That meant the jurors who had been deliberating for
13 days had to start their talks all over again. On Wednesday, they
began for a third time.
   The prosecutor, Deputy District Attorney P. Philip Halpin, told
reporters: ``I'm relieved. I am grateful that we followed the
correct path.''
   No mistrial motion was made, and Clark said he was uncertain
whether there would be one in the future.
   ``I like the jury,'' he said, ``so personally I'm not crazy about
a mistrial.''
   In another development, the judge said he was issuing a bench
warrant for the arrest of a defense attorney in the case, Arturo
Hernandez, who has failed to appear at recent court hearings. Daniel
Hernandez, no relation, said his colleague was recently married and
has been in Europe on his honeymoon.
</TEXT>
