<SECOND>AM-US-Cubans,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Declines To Say Why It Barred Cubans From Baseball
Tourney</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Wednesday it had
invoked a 1985 presidential proclamation to bar seven Cubans from
attending a baseball tournament in Puerto Rico.
   In San Juan, the president of Puerto Rico's Olympic committee,
German Rieckeoff Sampayo, protested the decision as an ``abuse'' and
unsportsmanlike.
   The seven, one of whom was listed as a technician, applied as
journalists. Five Cubans who had been granted visas to cover a
boxing tournament in Puerto Rico were permitted to remain. And
another Cuban journalist was approved.
   Cuba's national baseball team is participating in the amateur
tournament known as the Interncontinental Cup along with teams from
the United States, Japan, South Korea, Italy and Taiwan.
   The 1985 proclamation declared all Cubans except diplomats
ineligible for visas. But, a press office statement said, ``as a
matter of practice, the department often grants exceptions to this
prohibition to Cuban sports delegations.''
   Forty-two members of the Cuban national baseball team were
granted visas. No explanation was given for singling out the seven
Cubans who were barred.
   ``After reviewing the applications, the department granted
exceptions to only five of the journalists,'' the statement said.
   A U.S. official said the decision was based on ``facts,'' but he
declined to elaborate.
