<FIRST>u i AM-Cambodia     08-16 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khmer Rouge Balk at Mention of Genocide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Khmer Rouge are demanding that references to
genocide be struck from texts in what rivals said Wednesday was a
``semantic battle'' stalling progress at a Cambodian peace
conference.
   Less than two weeks before the close of the international forum,
the Cambodian guerrilla faction has balked over the word
``genocide'' and is insisting that Vietnamese civilians in Cambodia
be viewed as colonizers.
   The subjects are dominating discussions, diplomats say.
   ``Around these two themes they have launched an absurd and
indecent semantic battle,'' Cambodian vice minister of foreign
affairs, Sok An, said. ``They are blocking the work of the
commissions.''
   Working committees, which resumed closed-door negotiations
Wednesday after a four-day break, are to submit conclusions to a
session of foreign ministers that convenes for three days starting
Aug. 28.
   Ministers from 19 nations and U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez
de Cuellar opened the conference on July 30 in the first concerted
effort to lay the groundwork for peace in Cambodia.
   Vietnam will pull its troops out of Cambodia in late September,
leaving the Vietnamese-installed government in Phnom Penh fighting
the guerrilla coalition, unless the peace talks find a solution.
   Pressing conference tasks include setting up an international
control mechanism to monitor vietnam's troop withdrawal, an eventual
cease-fire and an end to foreign aid to the various factions.
   Progress is ``very 50-50,'' said one Western delegate. ``But the
mood, I think, is still fairly optimistic. ... It is a tremendous
task to be accomplished in a month.''
   Discussions are heated and insults have been exchanged between
the four Cambodian parties, said one participant.
   Prime Minister Hun Sen and the resistance, headed by Prince
Norodom Sihanouk, remain opposed on all major points.
   The center of the conflict lies in whether the Khmer Rouge should
be allowed a part in a coalition government. Hun Sen argues they
should not, but Sihanouk maintains the Khmer Rouge are less
dangerous as allies than enemies.
   ``The priority now is to liberate Cambodia,'' said Keo Puth
Rasmey, a member of Sihanouk's delegation. ``We know that the Khmer
Rouge is the problem, but let the Cambodian people reject them ...
in general elections.''
   During nearly four years of Khmer Rouge rule, hundreds of
thousands of people were killed. Vietnam invaded in late 1978,
driving out the Khmer Rouge and installing another communist
government.
   Both Hun Sen's government and its Vietnamese sponsors refer to
the Khmer Rouge reign of terror as ``genocide.'' A Khmer Rouge
delegate, speaking on condition of anonymity, said using the word
``genocide'' in conference texts allows Vietnam to justify its
invasion.
   The resistance claims there also are Vietnamese soldiers
``disguised'' in the Cambodian military and up to 1 million
Vietnamese ``colonizers'' who have settled in Cambodia since Hanoi's
invasion and should be expelled. Hun Sen's regime says there are
less than 100,000.
   Sihanouk is prepared to settle the issue outside the conference,
according to members of his delegation, but the Khmer Rouge want to
deal with it now.
   The issue is ``a bigger problem than it would have appeared a
month ago,'' said the Western delegate, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
</TEXT>
