<FIRST>u a AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0632 08-16 0896</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0632,890</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Campaigns for Cuban-American, Raps Castro</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf 12: ``He landed,'' to put Bush in Kennbunport</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, campaigning for a Cuban-born
congressional candidate, Wednesday declared that U.S. relations with
Cuba cannot be normalized as long as Fidel Castro ``swims against
the tide'' of political reform in closed societies.
   Making a 2,000-mile political detour on the way to Maine for a
three-week vacation, Bush criticized the communist leader at a
fund-raising luncheon for Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, who is seeking to win
the seat held for 27 years by the late Rep. Claude Pepper.
   ``As president, I will look for signs that Castro wants to move
away from subverting his neighbors, move toward more openness, more
freedom for his own people. But until I see demonstrable change
there will be no improvement in relations with Cuba,'' Bush
declared, to warm applause. ``It simply cannot be.''
   In a city where anti-Castro sentiment runs high among Cuban
exiles, Bush avoided any mention of a recent Justice Department
action ordering the deportation of a popular Cuban-born pediatrician
accused of involvement in terrorist activities.
   Many local GOP officeholders and politicians, including Ms.
Ros-Lehtinen, have called Orlando Bosch a hero in a war against
Castro.
   Bosch, 62, in custody here as an illegal alien since February
1988, has been linked to terrorist acts aimed at Castro's
government, and to the 1976 bombing of a Cuban jetliner that killed
73 people. However, his supporters argue that he was acquitted of
the plane bombing in Venezuela.
   Ms. Ros-Lehtinen told reporters she and Bush discussed the Bosch
case on the way to Miami from Washington and he was ``very
well-versed on it.''
   ``It's not really a presidential matter, it's in the hands of
...the federal system,'' she said. However, she added that if a
mid-September court hearing on Bosch's appeal doesn't go his way,
she planned to renew her appeal to Bush to intervene.
   Presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Bush would not
comment on the matter because Bosch's case was under an appeal in
federal court.
   The case puts the White House in an awkward position, given GOP
efforts to bring more Cuban-Americans into the Republican fold and
the administration's strong condemnation of terrorism.
   Bush stopped here to campaign for Ms. Ros-Lehtinen _ whose
campaign manager is Bush's son, Jeb Bush _ on a roundabout route to
Maine, where he will spend most of the next three weeks at his
seaside compound in the resort town of Kennebunkport. ``It was right
on the way,'' Bush joked.
   He landed in Maine late in the afternoon and went straight to the
compound.
   The Republican state senator will face Democratic lawyer Gerald
Richman in a special Aug. 29 election to replace the late Rep.
Claude Pepper.
   Bush was warmly received by the predominantly Cuban-American
audience of about 600 people, who paid $1,000-a-couple for the
luncheon.
   Fitzwater, meanwhile, said that Bush, returning to Washington on
Sept. 4, will address the nation on Sept. 5 on his new drug policy.
   It will be the president's first national address and will
probably be an evening speech from the White House, Fitzwater said,
although he said time and location had not been nailed down.
   Bush is scheduled to unveil his plan for fighting drugs earlier
the same day.
   ``The president felt it was a national strategy, an issue of
concern for all Americans and it will call for sacrifices and hard
work and he wanted to discuss it directly with the American
people,'' Fitzwater said.
   Bush also discussed the war on drugs in Wednesday's political
speech, saying ``the No. 1 issue in Miami, the No. 1 issue indeed
across America, is drugs and the violent crime they spawn.''
   But Bush saved his sharpest comments for Castro.
   ``With Castro's Cuba just 90 miles away, she (Ms. Ros-Lehtinen)
understands the horrors of totalitarianism,'' Bush said.
   Bush's comments about Castro contrasted with his recent overtures
to leaders in Communist-led countries in Eastern Europe.
   In fact, he told his audience, ``We've seen how democracy is
surging forward around the world and taking roots in outposts like
Poland and Hungary.''
   ``Someday I'd like to see improved _ yes, normalized _ relations
with Cuba,'' Bush said. ``But that cannot and it will not be as long
as Castro violates the human rights of his own people; as long as
he, almost alone in the entire world now, swims against the tide
that is bringing sweeping change, democracy and freedom to closed
societies around the world.''
   Fitzwater said the Republican National Committee picked up the
tab for the political leg of Bush's trip from Washington to Miami
and then to Pease Air Force Base in Portsmouth, N.H., from where he
was to take a helicopter to his vacation home on the Atlantic coast
   Bush told his audience that ``with any luck and if the weather
holds'' he planned to watch the lunar eclipse Wednesday night with
family members in Kennebunkport.
   Fitzwater, briefing reporters on Air Force One on the way to
Miami, dismissed a new Washington Post-ABC poll showing that 52
percent of those surveyed did not think Vice President Dan Quayle
was qualified to take over as president.
   ``We think the public does have confidence'' in Quayle, the White
House spokesman said. ``We think the vice president is doing a
splendid job.''
</TEXT>
