<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Extend From The Ohio Valley to The Ozarks</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms spread from southern Ohio to southeast Kansas and
eastern Oklahoma and were scattered across the East and Gulf coasts,
dampening the hopes of many Americans for a glimpse of Wednesday
night's lunar eclipse.
   In Oklahoma, the storms dumped up to 3{ inches of rain near
Sasakwa, and flooded many rural roads across Seminole and Pontotoc
counties. Street flooding was reported at Ada.
   Heavy rain also fell in the Wichita, Kan., area, and St. Louis,
Mo., got its first rain of the month. A thunderstorm produced strong
winds and small hail at Falmouth in northern Kentucky.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered across the East Coast
and Gulf Coast states. A thunderstorm brought .69 inches of rain in
17 minutes at Port Arthur, Texas.
   A tropical storm warning was issued for islands in the eastern
Caribbean as a depression moved westward from the Atlantic.
   The depression, with maximum sustained winds of 35 mph, was
moving at about 20 mph and some strengthening was expected by
Thursday afternoon, according to the National Hurricane Center in
Coral Gables, Fla.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included 1.06 inches at Chanute, Kan.; .74 inches at Wichita, Kan.;
.94 inches at Beaumont and Port Arthur, Texas; .67 inches at Mineral
Wells, Texas; and .59 inches at St. Louis, Mo.
   Widely scattered showers and thunderstorms also developed in the
afternoon across the Rockies, and were expected over the northern
High Plains.
   Those parts of the nation with a clear eastern sky were expected
to be able to view Wednesday night's lunar eclipse.
   Temperatures were in the 70s and 80s across most of the nation in
the afternoon. Much of the northwestern states from Montana to the
Pacific Northwest had readings in the 60s. Temperatures were in the
lower 90s over portions of the Eastern seaboard, the central Gulf
Coast and Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Coeur d'Alene, Idaho, to 104 degrees at Needles, Calif.
The low in the nation Wednesday morning was 31 degrees at Truckee,
Calif.
   Thursday's forecast called for numerous showers and thunderstorms
over the central Gulf Coast region, southern Florida, and portions
of Virginia and West Virginia; and scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the middle and south Atlantic Coast states across
the Tennessee Valley and Gulf Coast states to the southern Plains.
Showers and thunderstorms were also expected across the Rockies and
Dakotas to western Minnesota.
   High temperatures were expected in the 70s from the Great Lakes
region and upper Ohio Valley to northern New England, and from
northwest Montana to the Pacific Northwest and along the California
coast; and in the 80s to lower 90s over most of the rest of the
nation. Temperatures were expected to reach near 100 degrees in the
Rio Grande Valley of Texas and over portions of Utah and the
interior valleys of California.
</TEXT>
