<SECOND>AM-Poland, 4th Ld-Writethru,a0691,0996</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Approves Resolution with Walesa as Prime Minister</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs with Walesa saying he doesn't want job but
it's not his final decision; pickup 10th pvs, ``We came...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos WAR52,53</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity members of Parliament
overwhelmingly endorsed a resolution Wednesday night calling for the
first non-Communist government in the Soviet bloc, with Lech Walesa
as prime minister.
   Walesa, however, said early Thursday that ``I will not be prime
minister. There are better people than Walesa'' for the job. But he
added it was not his final decision.
   ``The final decision is will be when they nail up my coffin,'' he
told reporters.
   Walesa, who won the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize, was applauded loudly
at the caucus of lawmakers from his independent Solidarity movement,
United Peasant Party and the Democratic Party before the vote.
   ``I never assumed that Lech Walesa could be prime minister and I
don't assume so now,'' said the shipyard electrician from Gdansk,
who led the strike that created the independent union in August
1980. The post must be offered by President Wojciech Jaruzelski.
   The two small parties were non-voting guests at the caucus. They
have had a long alliance with the Communists, but agreed earlier in
the day to form a coalition with Solidarity.
   In a show of hands from the Solidarity caucus, the indepedent
movement's 161 Sejm deputies and 98 senators endorsed a government
formed by a coalition under Walesa's leadership. Only the five
negative votes and 17 abstentions were counted.
   In a last-minute amendment, they altered the wording to leave
open the possibility that Walesa could designate someone else to be
prime minister.
   Asked who the coalition will propose for prime minister,
Solidarity parliamentary leader Bronislaw Geremek said, ``Walesa
will decide.'' He said it should be known by the end of the week.
   Before the vote, Walesa asked ``for a new coalition which will
counteract monopoly.''
   ``We came here to change Poland. ... I am very grateful to our
elder friends from the Peasant Party and the Democratic Party for
understanding my game. Together we will teach the (Communist Party)
pluralism, freedom and listening to others.''
   The three parties represent 264 parliament votes, a majority in
the 460-member Sejm, and theoretically enough to form a
non-Communist government. Walesa is not a member of Parliament.
   Whether the Communist Party would turn over control of the
government remained a question. In a separate meeting, Communist
lawmakers appointed a group to formulate a stand on the Solidarity
resolution.
   On Tuesday, Jaruzelski proposed a meeting of all the country's
main political leaders to find ``rational solutions'' to the
governing crisis.
   The resolution said, in part:
   ``We think that the parliamentary coalition of the Peasant Party,
the Democratic Party and Solidarity is capable of forming a
government of national responsibility under the leadership of Lech
Walesa in which all political forces of our country could be
represented, all forces which are determined to act in favor of
political and economic reform.''
   Earlier Wednesday, the Peasant Party lawmakers met with their
chairman, Roman Malinowski, and said afterward that they ``fully
support'' the proposal Walesa originally made Aug. 7 for a
Solidarity-led coalition with the Democrats and Peasants.
   The 27-member Democratic Party caucus also met and voted for the
Solidarity-led coalition, said its leader Jan Jankowski.
   Prime Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak on Monday announced in the face
of opposition from Solidarity he was ready to step down and turn
over his unsuccessful attempt to form a government to Malinowski.
Malinowski has not accepted the proposal, and his party's
legislators said they preferred joining with Solidarity.
   The Communist Party chief described his party's situation as
``dangerous.''
   ``We have entered a period of an open fight for power,'' party
First Secretary Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski told a closed meeting of
Communist Party lawmakers earlier in the day, according to the
state's PAP news service.
   ``The situation is dangerous, but it is not time to put up our
hands'' in surrender, said Rakowski. He alleged that Walesa's power
bid violated the ``round-table'' agreement reached in the spring
between communist authorities and the opposition.
   Addressing the caucus on behalf of Solidarity lawmakers, Deputy
Aleksander Paczynski called for intense reforms and a renegotiation
of the round-table accords to bring about fully free elections in
Poland in two years, instead of the promised four.
   A government headed by Walesa and ``spectacular quick decisions''
such as giving parliament control of state radio and television
would help quell social impatience, Paczynski said.
   In a climate of economic deterioration and public discontent with
the communist leadership, Solidarity has said only an opposition-led
government will have enough support to carry out difficult decisions.
   The proposal has alarmed the Polish Communist Party and the
government of the neighboring Soviet Union, which has said the
attempt to form the government could lead to the destabilization of
Europe and endanger the Warsaw Pact alliance.
   To ease Soviet fears, Walesa promised Tuesday that in a
Solidarity-led government, the Communist Party would retain control
of the ``sensitive'' ministries of defense and interior.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Yuri Gremitskikh said in Moscow
the Kremlin is ``very concerned'' about events in Poland, but he
lauded as ``sensible'' Walesa's promise not to upset the Warsaw Pact
military alliance.
   Gremitskikh added: ``We don't interfere in the internal affairs
of that country. The Polish people should decide themselves.''
   Polish Communist Party Secretary Slawomir Wiatr told a Warsaw
newspaper, however, the the Communists ``will not take
responsibility for the result'' if Solidarity forms a non-communist
coalition government.
   More than four decades of government leadership by the Communist
Party appeared shaky because of the governing crisis that stems from
its crushing losses in the most democratic elections in the country
since World War II.
</TEXT>
