<FIRST>u i AM-Obit-Fuller     08-16 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Fuller,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Horace Fuller, Retired Marine General, Dies At 81</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPETSAI, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Horace Fuller, a retired U.S. Marine
Reserve brigadier general and a veteran of the Guadacanal campaign
in World War II, has died after a battle with cancer, a doctor said
Wednesday. He was 81.
   Fuller, a resident of the Spetsai for the past 10 years, died
late Tuesday at the Greek island's health center, according to Dr.
Christos Ressos.
   Fuller had recently traveled to the United States, where he
underwent several operations for cancer, Ressos said. It was not
immediately clear what type of cancer he suffered from.
   Fuller was born in 1908 and was a 1930 graduate of Harvard
University.
   He was one of the few survivors when his regiment hit the beach
at Guadacanal in the South Pacific during World War II. He was
wounded there and evacuated to the United States.
   When he returned to duty, Fuller was assigned to the Office of
Strategic Services, the forerunner to the CIA.
   He served in southern France and was one of three men who
parachuted into the Pyrenees to assist French resistance fighters
against the Nazis in May 1944.
   After the war, Fuller went to Greece to help with the Marshall
Plan and later entered the shipping business there. He retired from
the Marine Corps reserve while in Greece.
   His wife, a Greek, died in 1981.
   He was buried Wednesday on the island.

</TEXT>
