<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Soviets     08-16 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Soviets,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sharon Invited To Visit Soviet Georgia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ariel Sharon, Israel's trade and industry
minister, got an official invitation Wednesday to visit Soviet
Georgia, the national news agency Itim and Israel radio reported.
   The radio said Sharon would travel to the southern Soviet
republic in September or October, becoming the first Israeli
minister to visit the Soviet Union since Moscow broke relations in
1967 over the Arab-Israeli war.
   Itim said the invitation was extended by members of a Soviet
Georgian trade delegation who arrived Tuesday for a 21-day visit
aimed at promoting trade links between the Black Sea republic and
Israel.
   There was no indication whether the Kremlin had a hand in the
invitation, but it presumably has Moscow's approval.
   Sharon's spokesman could not be reached for comment despite
repeated telephone calls.
   Itim said the Georgian delegation included Vazha Gingihadze, the
republic's foreign trade minister, and the head of the Georgian
Chamber of Commerce. It said the delegates were investigating
possibilities of trade in the medical, agriculture and food
processing areas.
   A delegation from Soviet Georgia that visited in April signed a
cultural exchange agreement with Israel.
   There has been widespread speculation that the first minister to
visit the Soviet Union would be Ezer Weizman of the center-leaning
Labor Party, now a Cabinet minister without portfolio.
   Sharon is considered a hawk even in Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc. He was a hero of the 1973 war and,
as defense minister, directed Israel's invasion of Lebanon in 1982.
   Weizman is known for dovish views on the Israeli-Palestinian
conflict, and agrees with the Soviet position that Israel should
talk with the Palestine Liberation Organization and trade territory
for peace.
   The Soviet Union severed diplomatic ties in 1967 to protest
Israel's occupation of territories belonging to Moscow's Arab
allies. The two nations established interest offices in 1987-88,
however, and cultural and tourism exchanges have expanded since.
   Analysts say Soviet republics appear to have greater flexibility
in contacts with Israel than does the central government in Moscow.
   Israel and the Soviet Union have no direct air links, for
example, but an Israeli jetliner landed in Yerevan, capital of
Soviet Armenia, in June to pick up 61 survivors of the December
earthquake for treatment in Israel. An El Al aircraft landed in
Yerevan again Tuesday, taking them home.
   Finance Minister Shimon Peres, head of the Labor Party, said
recently that Israel should develop relations with each republic
separately.
   Last week, Israel and the Soviet Union agreed on their first
joint venture, to manufacture medical equipment.
   Israel's Agriculture Ministry and the Soviet Academy of Sciences
signed an agreement Saturday to create a joint agricultural company.
A five-member academy delegation had spent 12 days in Israel
studying Israeli agricultural techniques.
</TEXT>
