<FIRST>u i AM-Vatican-Jews     08-16 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vatican-Jews,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Group Applauds Pope's Statement on Covenant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jewish group applauded Pope John Paul II's weekly
talk on religious matters Wednesday, saying it had a different tone
than two speeches earlier this month that the group had condemned.
   Rabbi David Rosen, a Vatican representative of the
Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith, said the pope addressed the
question of ancient Jews and their covenant with God ``in a manner
that is consonant with post-conciliar documents and that is to be
welcomed.''
   His statement was released by the league office in Rome.
   The group had protested following two general audiences in which
John Paul said the Old Testament showed ``many instances of Israel's
infidelity to God.'' The pope also said that God sent messengers to
convert people and tell them of a new covenant to come.
   The Anti-Defamation League had said those remarks suggested the
new covenant with Christianity had superseded the alliance with
Jews. The organization had said it hoped the ``clock of
Catholic-Jewish relations had not been tragically set back.''
   But Rosen said Wednesday's remarks were in line with the Second
Vatican Council's 1965 document Nostra Aetate (In Our Times), which
officially dropped the accusation that Jews killed Christ.
   Following Wednesday's general audience, Rosen said, ``It would
seem that the pope is trying to clarify classical Christian theology
in a manner that is consonant with post-conciliar documents and that
is to be welcomed.''
   He expressed hope that ``such clarifications may be the
expression of an ongoing dialogue which is only to the advantage of
the church, Jewish people and humankind as a whole.''
   The pope spoke Wednesday about God's choice of Israel as his
people, as expressed in the Old Testament, and the role of the Holy
Spirit in the creation of the Roman Catholic Church.
   The controversy over the pope's remarks came at a time of tense
relations between Catholics and Jews.
   A Polish cardinal recently suspended an agreement to move a
Catholic convent at the Auschwitz death camp, prompting protests
from Jewish officials.
   Jewish groups said the convent and its Christian symbols offend
the memory of the 2.5 million Jews who died there.
</TEXT>
