<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0631 08-16 0872</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0631,0891</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christian Accepts Cease-fire Call; No Word From Syrians</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 7th pvs, `Syria made...' to ADD earlier
Syrian comment; picks up 8th pvs, `In Washington...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BEI1,2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Christian commander welcomed a U.N.
call to halt fighting that has cost more than 700 lives, but there
was no word Wednesday from the Syrians, who have ringed Christian
territory with guns and armor.
   Shelling that has ravaged Beirut became intermittent after the
U.N. Security Council issued its cease-fire appeal Tuesday night in
New York, but Syria and allied Moslem militias brought up men, tanks
and artillery to reinforce their siege of the Christian enclave
north and east of Beirut.
   An independent observer said privately the warring factions
appeared to be observing a ``cease-fire of convenience. They are
quietly bolstering their forces.''
   Five months of artillery duels between the Syrians and Gen.
Michel Aoun's force of about 20,000 Christian army troops have
killed 772 people and wounded more than 2,051, nearly all of them
civilians.
   A spokesman for Aoun said Wednesday: ``The general
unconditionally welcomes the U.N. Security Council resolution. The
resolution as we understand it is a package deal that involves not
just a cease-fire, but also lifting of blockades and programming the
Syrian military pullout from Lebanon.''
   Aoun calls Syrian troops an occupation army and has declared a
``war of liberation'' to drive them out. Syria has 40,000 soldiers
in Lebanon under an Arab League mandate granted in 1976, the year
after the sectarian civil war began.
   Syria made no immediate response to the truce resolution, which
the Security Council approved during a meeting called by U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   Earlier, Syrian President Hafez Assad told Italian Premier Giulio
Andreotti he will try to ``silence the guns'' in Lebanon and promote
a settlement among all factions in the country. Assad did not
elaborate in his reply to a recent message from Andreotti asking the
Syrian leader to act ``in a decisive manner'' to end the fighting,
the premier's officer said in Rome.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Richard Boucher read a
statement that said, in part: ``The senseless bloodshed ... has gone
on for far too long and it must cease. We urge in the strongest
terms that all parties abide by the council's call for a total and
immediate cease-fire.''
   Syrian gunners shelled the Christian enclave Wednesday and the
Christians responded by firing on residential areas of Moslem west
Beirut. Several apartment houses in the Moslem sector were set
ablaze.
   Six people were wounded in Christian territory, police reported,
but they said west Beirut suffered no casualties because ``most of
the targeted apartments were evacuated'' during earlier shelling.
   Moslem security sources said the Moslem allies moved more tanks,
troops and ammunition up to their positions along the 65-mile
confrontation line with Aoun's outnumbered forces.
   One said the Syrians deployed Soviet-designed T-62 tanks on the
northern and eastern flanks of the 310-square-mile Christian zone
and Druse chieftain Walid Jumblatt positioned scores of T-54 and
T-55 tanks in the mountains to the south. The Christian area faces
the Mediterranean on the west.
   Israel has informed Syria of ``red lines'' it cannot cross during
any military action, particularly in south Lebanon, without inviting
Israeli retaliation.
   Druse fighters, seen manning jeep-mounted machine guns and
recoilless cannons, were seen in west Beirut for the first time
since Syrian troops moved into the Moslem sector in February 1987 to
stop factional war among militias.
   ``It seems we are heading for a new confrontation despite this
cease-fire call; the militias are back,'' said Talal Hosseini,
watching his janitor fill plastic bags with sand to fortify the
entrance of his apartment house.
   The Lebanese capital, divided into Moslem and Christian sectors,
has taken the brunt of battle. All but 150,000 of its 1.5 million
people have left since the shelling began March 8.
   Adnan Bader, a salesman, left more than a month ago for Shehim
village southeast of the capital. He drove to west Beirut on
Wednesday to check his apartment in the Bourj Abu Haidar district
and found it shattered by a 155mm howitzer shell.
   ``The radio reported that our street was shelled. I came to find
by apartment torn apart,'' Bader said, his eyes brimming with tears.
The shell pierced a bedroom wall, blowing away his children's room
and part of the living room.
   ``I'll move the fridge, the stove, the washing machine and the
rest of the kitchen equipment to Shehim,'' he said. ``It costs
plenty of money to buy these things.''
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, and Sunni
religious leaders also embraced the U.N. truce appeal, which was
broadcast by Beirut radio stations.
   Hoss and Aoun lead competing Moslem and Christian cabinets formed
during a government crisis in September 1988 that also led to a
split of the army into Christian and Moslem commands. The 22,000
poorly equipped Moslem soldiers, under Maj. Gen. Sami Khatib, have
stayed out of the current fighting.
   The artillery war began two days after Aoun's forces blockaded
illegal ports run by Moslem militias that deprived the government of
about $100 million a year in customs revenue.
</TEXT>
