<FIRST>r a AM-SectWeapons     08-16 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sect Weapons,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sect Leader Denies Urging Flock To Arm, Stockpile Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN K. WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a Montana-based religious
sect that is preparing for nuclear war said Wednesday she never
urged members to purchase weapons, and denied that the church had
been stockpiling assault rifles.
   Elizabeth Clare Prophet, leader of the Church Universal and
Triumphant, told reporters after her 90-minute grand jury appearance
that it is not the sect's policy to purchase or stockpile weapons.
   Mrs. Prophet, her husband, Ed Francis, and two other church
employees appeared before a federal grand jury investigating alleged
illegal weapons purchases by Vernon D. Hamilton, a 15-year staff
member who handled security for the church.
   Mrs. Prophet, known as ``Guru Ma'' or ``mother'' to followers of
her Christian-New Age church, used the occasion to criticize the
lack of a national civil defense policy.
   The church is building a large bomb shelter to house 754 people
at its Corwin Springs, Mont., headquarters and members are required
to build individual shelters beneath or near their homes, said Erin
Lynn Prophet, a church spokeswoman and the sect leader's daughter.
   The shelters are being built on the 12,000-acre Royal Teton Ranch
near Yellowstone National Park in preparation for a possible nuclear
confrontation between the superpowers, Mrs. Prophet said. She
contended the Soviet Union is better prepared than the United States
to defend its citizens and military personnel in the event of a
nuclear attack.
   Even some members disagree with her prophecy predicting the start
of a new period of nuclear tension beginning Oct. 2, the sect leader
said. Church members are praying that such a confrontation will be
avoided, she said.
   Mrs. Prophet declined to discuss her testimony or Hamilton's
case, saying the proceedings were confidential and Hamilton's
attorneys had asked her not to comment on the criminal case.
   ``I trust the legal process,'' she said. ``I want to give it an
opportunity to work.''
   Federal prosecutors said they cannot discuss matters relating to
the grand jury.
   Hamilton, 42, was arrested in Spokane July 7 with documents
concerning the purchases of $100,000 worth of weapons and
ammunition. He was indicted July 25 on four counts of making false
statements in the acquisition of a firearm.
   Church officials Wednesday continued to deny knowledge of the
weapons purchases, which are legal, or Hamilton's alleged use of
fake names to buy them, which would be illegal.
   Documents found in the church-owned car driven by Hamilton
indicated he was the church's chief of security and planned to buy
enough weapons to outfit 200 people, federal authorities have said.
   Hamilton is staying at his parents' Spokane home pending a Sept.
25 trial. A conviction carries a maximum five-year prison sentence
and $250,000 fine.
   Among weapons confiscated by police were seven .50-caliber
Barrett semi-automatic rifles that assistant U.S. Attorney Thomas
Rice characterized as ``capable of taking out an armored personnel
carrier.''
   Other weapons included Korean assault rifles and Austrian sniper
rifles and more than 120,000 rounds of armor-piercing and tracer
ammunition.
</TEXT>
