<DOCNO> AP890816-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 2050EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-StealthBomber 2ndLd-Writethru a0664 08-16 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stealth Bomber, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0664,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Low Oil Pressure Reading Cuts Short Second Flight of B-2 Bomber</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, `The B-2 ..., with 2 grafs to show Pentagon
now saying plane flew to same speed and altitude as during first flight,
not faster and higher; picks up 8th graf pvs: The four-engine....</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The B-2 stealth bomber's
second flight ended prematurely Wednesday when a low oil-pressure
reading forced pilots to land the $530 million plane an hour after
takeoff.
   ``We don't even know if it's a problem yet. We're concerned with
it and will have to check it out,'' said 1st Lt. Anu Sjaardema, an
Air Force spokeswoman.
   The radar-evading aircraft lifted off over the Mojave Desert at
7:29 a.m. for a three- to four-hour flight but returned at 8:36 a.m.
because ``there were some minor concerns with the oil pressure
indicators,'' she said.
   The two men aboard, Air Force Col. Richard S. Couch and Northrop
Corp. chief test pilot Bruce J. Hinds, were never in any danger, but
they ``obviously would have liked to accomplish more,'' she said.
   ``We did achieve some of the things we set out to do, so we can't
say it wasn't a successful flight,'' Sjaardema said.
   The B-2, a tailless flying wing, flew with its landing gear
retracted for the first time, she said.
   Sjaardema also said the plane flew ``a little bit faster and a
little bit higher'' than on the first B-2 flight in July. But Air
Force Maj. Dick Cole at the Pentagon later said the plane ``was
flown to a maximum altitude of 10,000 feet and a maximum air speed
of 180 knots.'' That is the same elevation and speed as during the
July flight.
   The four-engine bomber, built with composite materials, is
intended to carry nuclear bombs and, along with the conventional
B-1, replace the Air Force's aging B-52 fleet. It is under fire in
Congress because of its cost.
   Each of the B-2's four engines has an accessory drive. ``One out
of the four drives indicated low oil pressure,'' Sjaardema said.
   Each accessory drive is like a transmission, connected to each
engine by a shaft. The drives power air turbine starters and
hydraulic systems, Sjaardema said.
   Air turbine starters are used to restart engines. The B-2's
hydraulics apparently control its landing gear, but it isn't known
if they are used to move flaps and other control surfaces, as is the
case on many planes. Tech. Sgt. Donn Clarius said there was no
failure of the hydraulic system.
   The Air Force had planned to fly the plane shortly after dawn
Tuesday, but the test was rescheduled for Wednesday because of
delays caused by wind and a long list of preflight checks, officials
said.
   The Air Force tried to fly the B-2 for the first time on July 15,
but the attempt was aborted by a low fuel pressure reading while the
bomber revved its engines awaiting clearance for takeoff. After the
flight was cancelled, workers checked the aircraft and discovered a
problem in a device called the heat exchanger in the bomber's fuel
system. The problem was fixed, but no details were available.
   During the plane's July 17 maiden flight, Hinds and Couch flew
the B-2 for nearly two hours and reached an altitude of 10,000 feet.
   The government has already invested about $22.4 billion in the
B-2 program, which is 18 months behind schedule, and Congress has
balked at the thought of paying more than $500 million apiece for
the 132 bombers the military wants.
   Congress imposed limits on the B-2 bomber despite fierce lobbying
efforts by the Bush administration to keep the program intact. House
and Senate members are scheduled to meet in conference in early
September to craft a final version of the defense authorization bill
and settle their differences over B-2 funding.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
