<FIRST>u a AM-Bush-Drugs 2ndLd-Writethru a0689 08-16 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Drugs, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0689,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Plans Big Drug Speech Sept. 5</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS grafs 12-13 bgng: ``Nonetheless, there,'' with report
of $6.5 billion cost</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush intends to rally support for his
battle plan against drug abuse on Sept. 5 in his first nationally
televised speech as president, his spokesman said Wednesday.
   Bush, who has said he will announce a broad drug-fighting
strategy on that date, ``wanted to discuss it directly with the
American people,'' said White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater.
   The White House has not yet approached the television networks
and thus has not set a time for the speech, he said.
   ``The president felt it was a national strategy, an issue of
concern for all Americans and it will call for sacrifices and hard
work for all Americans,'' Fitzwater said aboard Air Force One as the
president flew to Miami.
   Fitzwater said the president, in a meeting Tuesday with his
Domestic Policy Council of Cabinet and senior advisers, signed off
on the broad planks of the strategy. But the spokesman added,
without elaborating, ``There's still some outstanding specifics'' to
be decided.
   Bush has made up his mind on the controversial issue that had
divided his advisers _ whether to withhold federal highway funds,
criminal justice assistance and other aid from states that do not
take steps such as revoking drug offenders' drivers' licenses and
putting in place adequate drug prevention and education programs at
schools, it was learned.
   However, it was not known which way the president had decided on
that point.
   Bush was to make the final decisions during his three-week
vacation in Kennebunkport, Maine, where he headed after leaving
Miami Wednesday.
   The official said the anti-drug strategy envisions expanded use
of the U.S. military to help combat drugs at the source in foreign
countries, when those countries request assistance.
   He said that the price tag for what has been touted as a major
cross-agency program is being closely held by the Office of
Management and Budget.
   Bush said Tuesday that he would not reveal the cost before Sept.
5 and that decisions were still being made on what programs
elsewhere in government would have to be tightened to pay for an
expanded war on drugs. He said his plan would require ``commitment
and sacrifice and understanding '' by Americans.
   Nonetheless, there have been various reports of what the cost
would be. An administation official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Wednesday night the cost would be ``roughly a
billion'' dollars more than what Bush set down in his February
budget proposal.
   The Bush budget called for $5.5 billion for anti-drug spending
during the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1, which would be a 21 percent
increase from this year's spending. The administration official's
report would imply spending of $6.5 billion, an increase of about 41
percent.
   On Wednesday, at a Miami fund-raising lunch for congressional
candidate Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, Bush said, ``The No. 1 issue in
Miami, and the No. 1 issue across America, is drugs and the violent
crime they spawn.''
   ``A strong foreign policy, hopes and plans for our children and
our elderly, all our dreams and best intentions will be for naught
if we cannot win the war against the thunder in the streets and the
evil that men do,'' he said.
   Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, a Republican state senator, will face
Democratic lawyer Gerald Richman in a special Aug. 29 election to
replace the late Rep. Claude Pepper.
   Drug policy coordinator William J. Bennett, has called for a
dramatic increase in drug treatment funds for 1990, according to a
draft of his national drug strategy.
   The draft obtained by The Associated Press revealed that Bennett
wanted $925 million for drug treatment next year, a 49 percent
increase over the $621 million in the current budget and a 26
percent increase over the $735 million that Bush had sought in his
budget request earlier this year.
   The draft also called for $1.2 billion for new prisons and the
expansion of federal prison capacity by 85 percent, and for
increases in most law enforcement efforts, including an additional
$200 million for a total of $350 million for state and local
enforcement efforts.
   In addition, Bennett sought $1.2 billion for prevention efforts,
a 28 percent over current spending.
   The draft strategy also called for spending $50 million for the
Department of Housing and Urban Development, $45 million of which
would be used for security improvements.
</TEXT>
