<FIRST>u a AM-MonroeSpared 1stLd-Writethru a0724 08-16 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Monroe Spared, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0724,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roemer Spares Life Of Monroe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd, `Monroe, labeled ..., to CLARIFY that
commutation means life without parole.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Buddy Roemer decided Wednesday to
spare the life of condemned murderer Ronald Monroe although ``the
evidence is persuasive to me that he is guilty.''
   Monroe, 34, was to have died in the electric chair on Aug. 30 for
the 1977 death of his landlady, Lenora Collins, who was stabbed
repeatedly while her two children watched. They later testified that
Monroe was the killer.
   Monroe, labeled by his attorneys as borderline mentally retarded,
had exhausted all appeals. He has insisted he is innocent for more
than a decade.
   The commutation means that Monroe must serve the rest of his life
in prison without a chance for parole, Roemer said.
   Roemer's decision came after private meetings with defense
attorneys, prosecutors and with one of the victim's children,
Theodise Collins, 24.
   Defense attorneys contended that Lenora Collins was killed by an
ex-boyfriend, George Stinson. They say Stinson admitted the murder
in 1980 to a cellmate in a Michigan prison. Stinson has a history of
stabbing women and of intimidating witnesses, the defense said.
   Defense attorney Douglas Morris said that Stinson intimidated the
Collins children so they would identify Monroe as the killer.
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, considering the defense
claims last year, said there was no evidence to back up the
allegations.
   The panel noted that Stinson was given immunity and testified
that while serving time in Michigan for fatally stabbing his
common-law wife he told a cellmate that Lenora Collins died in a
similar fashion ``but he did not say or imply that he personally had
any guilt in her (Collins') death.''
   Roemer talked at length to Theodise Collins Wednesday about
Stinson.
   ``He asked me whether I was positive about the person who killed
my mother,'' she told reporters later. ``My response was, of course,
Ronald Monroe. He asked if I had been mentally, physically or
sexually abused by anyone (in connection with the case), especially
George Stinson. My reply, of course, was no.''
   Roemer said he felt the two juries that tried Monroe were wrong
to give him the death sentence.
   ``The developments in this case have been several, which say that
Ronald Monroe had no evidence of criminal activities, zero,'' Roemer
said. ``Ronald Monroe had lived in that house next door for years
with no violence. ...
   ``While there is guilt for Monroe, in an execution in this
country, the test ought not be reasonable doubt. The test ought to
be is there any doubt. ... He met the test for guilty but not
execution.''
   Collins said if Roemer decided to stop the execution, she would
not be angry, although she felt Monroe should die.
   ``He (Roemer) has a job he has to do,'' she said. ``I don't think
the question is whether Ronald Monroe is guilty or not. I think it's
exactly what are we supposed to do with him now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890816-0169 </DOCNO>
