<HEAD>Foreign Photographer Held Under Anti-Terrorist Law</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with photographer charged; picks
up 11th pvs, `The spokesman...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Wednesday said a West
German free-lance photographer arrested under anti-terrorism laws
has been charged with a weapons offense.
   A spokesman at Belfast police headquarters said the photographer
was charged Wednesday, but the spokesman would not specify the
firearms offense or identify him by name.
   Sporadic rioting broke out in Roman Catholic areas of west
Belfast Wednesday night, police reported. They said supporters of
the Irish Republican Army in isolated attacks threw gasoline bombs
and rocks at security forces but that no injuries or arrests were
reported.
   In Armagh, near the border with the Irish Republic, the IRA blew
up a Protestant-owned gas station with a car packed with explosives
on Tuesday night. It said the bombing was punishment for supplying
police vehicles. No one was injured.
   Earlier Wednesday, Britain deported Martin Galvin, a leading
American supporter of the outlawed Irish Republican Army, who was
arrested in Northern Ireland on Tuesday for defying an order banning
him from British territory.
   Galvin, publicity director for the New York-based Irish Northern
Aid Commiteee, or Noraid, was flown to the United States from a
Royal Air Force base near London.
   News of the photographer's arrest broke amid complaints by
officials that some foreign cameramen are provoking riots.
   Dozens of foreign television crews are in Northern Ireland to
cover this week's 20th anniversiary of the deployment in British
troops in the province, which is torn by Roman Catholic-Protestant
strife.
   A police spokesman said the West German photographer was arrested
early Tuesday in Catholic West Belfast and is being held under
Britain's Prevention of Terrorism Act. A British Broadcasting Corp.
television report identified the photographer as Dick Vogel.
   Police refused to comment on British news reports that police
found smoke bombs and other missiles in the trunk of his car.
   The spokesman said a French photographer was also arrested
Tuesday but later released.
   Local news photographers supported charged the presence of
foreign photographers has prolonged relatively routine
stone-throwing in Roman Catholic areas. The British Broadcasting
Corp. said that in some cases cameramen actively encouraging
youngsters to riot for the pictures.
   The Belfast Press Photographers Association said in a statement
that in Northern Ireland, ``news does not need to be manufacturued.''
   The mainly Catholic IRA is fighting British rule in Northern
Ireland. It wants to unite the predominantly Protestant province
with the 95 percent Catholic Irish Republic under socialist rule.
</TEXT>
