<FIRST>u i AM-Begin     08-16 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Begin,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Prime Minister Begin Hospitalized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Prime Minister Menachem Begin was
hospitalized for medical tests on Wednesday after complaining of
fatigue, doctors said.
   Begin, who turned 76 on Saturday, was admitted to Shaarei Tzedek
Hospital and will stay for ``a day or two,'' said Dr. Jonathan
Halevy, the hospital's director.
   ``He complained for the last few days about some fatigue, but
nothing specific,'' Halevy said.
   Halevy said initial tests ``were negative, meaning nothing was
found.''
   ``I expect him to be released within a day or two,'' he said.
   Reports of Begin's hospitalization were carried on state
television and radio newscasts. Army radio described him as
``walking around'' and ``in a good mood.''
   Begin was admitted to the same hospital in April 1987 after
complaining of weakness. He was discharged after 10 days of medical
tests.
   Begin, the former leader of Israel's right-wing Likud bloc, came
to power in 1977. He resigned without warning in September 1983 and
since has lived in seclusion in Jerusalem.
   At the time, aides said Begin was depressed about the death of
his wife and about Israel's protracted involvement in Lebanon after
its 1982 invasion of that country.
   Israel was widely criticized for the invasion and three-year
occupation of southern Lebanon.
   Begin suffered several heart attacks while prime minister and
underwent prostate surgery in 1986.
   Begin seldom speaks in public. His last public statement was on
July 9, when he condemned a Palestinian attack on an Israeli
passenger bus that killed 16 people and injured 25. Most victims
were Israelis.
</TEXT>
