<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 2250EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PhoneStrikes     08-16 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Phone Strikes,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Phone Talks End With No Progress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the nation's four strikebound Baby Bell companies held
informal talks with telephone workers Wednesday, but both meetings
ended with no progress reported in the 11-day-old walkout.
   The Communications Workers of America and NYNEX met at an
undisclosed location in the New York area for the first time since
picket lines went up Aug. 5in the dispute over wages and company
plans to cut back health benefits.
   Wednesday's meeting ended in part because neither side would
shift its position on whether workers should pay for part of their
health insurance, officials said.
   In Washington, CWA spokesman Bill Bickers said informal talks
occurred between union officials and another regional telephone
company, Philadelphia-based Bell Atlantic, but there was no progress
to report.
   ``There's a lot of concern that the company has not moved yet,''
Bill Bickers said. ``The union would really like to see some
movement from the company so we can get on with negotiations.''
   Bickers said no further talks were planned.
   The companies affected by the strikes are:
   _NYNEX, which serves about 50 percent of New York state, a small
part of Connecticut and the five other New England states. Its
companies have 60,000 workers on strike. Some 10.3 million customers
are affected.
   _Bell Atlantic, which has subsidiaries serving 12.7 million
customers in Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Maryland, Delaware, Virginia,
West Virginia and the District of Columbia. It has 52,000 workers on
strike.
   _San Francisco-based Pacific Telesis, whose two subsidiaries
serve 13.2 million customers in parts of California and all of
Nevada. More than 40,000 CWA members are striking.
   _Chicago-based Ameritech, which owns companies serving 12 million
customers in Illinois, Indiana, Ohio, Wisconsin and Michigan. It has
35,000 employees belonging to the CWA on strike. Ameritech
subsidiaries in each state are negotiating separately with the
union. An additional 12,500 employees, members of the IBEW, have
ratified agreements with the companies.
   No talks were scheduled in the Ameritech and Pacific Telesis
strikes.
   Three other so-called Baby Bells _ the regional phone companies
formed out of the breakup of American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.'s
Bell System _ have reached settlements with the CWA and the IBEW.
They are Atlanta-based Bell South, Denver-based US West and St.
Louis-based Southwestern Bell.
   NYNEX said in the statement that the company was prepared to
bargain on ``the entire package of wages, benefits and pension and
all other issues.''
   But NYNEX spokesman John Bonomo said NYNEX will not change its
position that the workers must share the cost of their health
insurance.
   Clara Allen, a CWA spokeswoman, said the union was adamantly
against workers sharing the cost of their health benefits.
</TEXT>
