<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 2156EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SiberianRadiation     08-16 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Siberian Radiation,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reindeer Herders in Soviet Nuclear Test Area Ravaged by Radiation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cancer and lung disease, the legacies of Soviet
nuclear tests carried out decades ago, are ravaging the reindeer
herders who live across the Bering Strait from Alaska, a Moscow
weekly reported Wednesday.
   The cancer rate among natives of the Chukotka peninsula is 2-3
times higher than the national average, virtually the entire
population suffers from tuberculosis and 90 percent from chronic
lung disease, Moscow News said.
   It said the general radiation level on the peninsula was at least
twice as high as normal and equal to the average dose received by
people living in areas around the Chernobyl nuclear power plant.
   In part because of their drastically reduced immunity, the
average lifespan of the natives, known as the Chukchi, is only 45
years, Moscow News reported.
   The article attributed the unusual radiation to nuclear tests
carried out in the 1950s and 1960s.
   ``Peaceful hunters and reindeer herders who in no way
participated in the conflict of the superpowers are now paying the
most for big politics,'' Moscow News said.
   The authors of the article, Dr. Vladimir Lupandin and historian
Yevdokia Gayer, said they visited one village on Chukotka where they
were told virtually every resident had cancer.
   Scientists measured up to 100 times the normal amount of some
radioactive elements in some deer hunters, the article said.
   Infant mortality is also especially high among the natives, with
up to 100 deaths per 1,000 infants, the Moscow News said.
   The Chukchi, a Mongoloid people inhabiting the northeastern-most
portion of Siberia, traditionally settle in small groups and live
off hunting and fishing.
   The article in the Moscow News was one of many to appear in the
Soviet media recently denouncing the conditions in which the peoples
of the Soviet Far North live.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
