<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 2257EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SpillRecords     08-16 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spill Records,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects State's Request For Testimony on Spill Records</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state's request for testimony on the
destruction of Exxon oil-spill records has been denied again, and
the attorney general said Wednesday he will not pursue the dispute
further.
   The dispute began in July when Kenneth Davis, a fired computer
operator for Exxon Co. USA in Houston, admitted he had accidentally
destroyed the computerized records. He said his superiors were
negligent in protecting them.
   Attorney General Douglas Baily said then the destruction was
``potentially a loss of devastating proportions'' to the state's
investigation of the nation's worst oil spill.
   A judge last month granted the state a hearing to question Exxon
employees involved in the records destruction, but two days later he
canceled the hearing and ordered Exxon to explain what happened in
affidavits instead.
   Exxon officials said the destroyed records were on obsolete
backup tapes and that other copies existed in computer archives. In
court documents, Exxon said the backup tapes were routinely
``recycled.''
   Davis disputed Exxon's version of the incident in an affidavit.
The state also obtained an affidavit from a contract employee who
had worked on Exxon's computer system. The employee termed Exxon's
affidavits misleading, said Fred Boness, an attorney for the state.
   Baily, dissatisfied with Exxon's explanation, asked the court
again to let the state take testimony from Exxon employees. Superior
Court Judge Brian Shortell denied the request without comment in an
order signed Friday.
   Shortell and Exxon attorneys did not return phone calls for
comment Wednesday.
   Baily said the state could have gained a more thorough
understanding of the records incident if it had been allowed to
question Exxon employees under oath.
   ``I'm still reluctant to accept the representations of Exxon,''
he said.
   The judge's decision effectively ends the dispute for now. The
issue remains alive, however, in a lawsuit Davis filed last month
against Exxon, alleging the oil company wrongfully fired and
slandered him.
   Baily said a pretrial hearing will be held within the next few
weeks in the state's negligence lawsuit filed Tuesday against Exxon
Corp., and about 140 other lawsuits related to the March 24 oil
spill in Prince William Sound.
   With the many lawyers involved, a large degree of cooperation
will be necessary to prevent the process from getting bogged down,
he said. The state's lawsuit, which also names the six other oil
companies that own Alyeska Pipeline Service Co., is expected to
bring in more attorneys.
   The state has had up to 25 lawyers working on its case, Baily
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
