<HEAD>Zia Supporters, Opponents Clash On Eve Of His Death Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fired tear gas Wednesday to
disperse supporters and opponents of Gen. Mohammed Zia ul-Haq who
battled on the eve of the first anniversary of the president's death
in a plane crash.
   Police said no one was injured in the clash at a shopping area of
Rawalpindi, 12 miles south of Islamabad.
   The clash was between supporters of the governing Pakistan
Peoples Party of Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto and members of the
opposition Islamic Democratic Alliance, which supported Zia, police
said.
   Zia and his top military officials died on Aug. 17, 1988 in an
unexplained air crash that also killed U.S. Ambassador Arnold
Raphel. Investigators blamed the crash on sabotage but never
assigned responsibility.
   Zia's family and the political opposition will mark the
anniversary Thursday with a memorial service at Islamabad's Faisal
Mosque, where Zia is buried. Organizers have said they expect
thousands will attend.
   Hundreds of people were camped near the mosque on Wednesday.
   Faisal Avenue, which leads to the mosque, has been decorated with
large portraits of Zia and banners praising his services to Islam,
Pakistan and the anti-communist war in Afghanistan.
   Portraits of political opposition leader Nawaz Sharif, chief
minister of Punjab, are also displayed along the route.
   Hundreds of policemen and guards have been called to Islamabad
and many parts of the capital have been closed to visiting mourners.
   The government has asked its supporters not to mourn, but rather
to commemorate Aug. 17 as the end of Zia's 11-year military rule.
   Zia overthrew former Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, Benazir
Bhutto's father, in a 1977 military coup. Bhutto was hanged two
years later after a show trial convicted him of ordering the
assassination of a political rival.
