<SECOND>AM-Deaths, SUB, a0736,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS the TOKYO-dated item to CLARIFY that Pearl Harbor attack
took place on Dec. 7, 1941; due to international date line, attack occurred
on Dec. 8 by Tokyo reckoning.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Minoru Genda</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minoru Genda, one of the planners of Japan's
surprise attack on Pearl Harbor and a former member of Parliament,
died Tuesday of heart failure. He was 84.
   Genda was a graduate of Japan's naval academy, He was a young
aviation staff officer who was called in to plan for the attack on
the U.S. Pacific fleet in Hawaii that brought the United States into
the war.
   Genda directed much of the secret training in Japanese waters
before the attack and, on Dec. 7, 1941, he was aboard one of the
Japanese carriers that launched the raid on Pearl Harbor.
   In June 1942, Genda was involved with the unsuccessful Japanese
attack on Midway Island.
   After the war, he joined Japan's revived air force in 1954 and
became its chief of staff in 1959. After retiring from the military,
Genda was elected in 1962 to the upper house of Parliament for the
governing Liberal Democratic Party, and was re-elected three times
before he retired in 1986.
