<FIRST>r a AM-GreenRiver     08-16 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Green River,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Green River Suspect's Brother Says He Can Prove Innocence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The brother of a man identified by police as a
suspect in the Green River serial murder investigation said
Wednesday he has proof that his brother was on the East Coast when
the first victims disappeared.
   Robert Stevens said his brother, William Jay Stevens II, is
``more a scapegoat than he is a suspect'' in the ``reckless''
investigation by the Green River Task Force.
   ``I believe in my brother's innocence,'' Stevens said at a news
conference he held at a Spokane parish hall one block from his
ailing father's home. He gave reporters a list of credit card
charges and four photographs he said are from a month-long vacation
when William Stevens and his parents visited him and his family in
Connecticut in July 1982, during the time the first Green River
victims disappeared.
   Robert Stevens said he has given the information and photographs
to Green River Task Force investigators, who interviewed him at his
father's home Tuesday.
   William Stevens, 38, has not been charged in any of the 48 deaths
or disappearances of women between 1982 and 1984 linked to the Green
River serial killer. Stevens is completing a jail sentence in
Seattle for a 1979 burglary and 1981 escape from a work release
center.
   ``The task force has been reckless in their investigation and
have done nothing but harass my brother, family and friends,''
Robert Stevens said, complaining that investigators waited more than
seven months after William Stevens' arrest in January to contact him
for information about his brother's whereabouts during 1981-85.
   Task force officials did not return numerous phone calls
Wednesday.
   Police last month searched two Spokane residences where William
Stevens lived while attending Gonzaga University Law School.
Investigators carted away truckloads of materials, including a
collection of police badges, videotapes and other paraphernalia.
   In a lengthy affidavit used to obtain a search warrant,
authorities labeled Stevens ``a viable suspect in the Green River
homicides, and possibly others in the Pacific Northwest.''
   Robert Stevens said he only recently obtained a copy of the
affidavit and spent two weeks compiling the information that he said
clears his brother in the Green River investigation.
   Stevens said his family had decided to hold a news conference
before he was contacted by the task force Tuesday. He said he is
researching more information that will prove his brother was not in
the areas where other Green River victims disappeared at the time of
those crimes.
   His brother also accompanied his parents on a trip to Vancouver,
British Columbia, in late April 1984 around the time of another
Green River disappearance, Stevens said.
   Stevens, 37, a senior chief petty officer at the U.S. Navy's
submarine base at Bangor, is on temporary humanitarian leave to care
for his father, who is recovering from surgery.
   William Stevens walked away from a Seattle work release facility
where he was completing a one-year sentence in 1981 for burglary of
a police equipment store. Since then, Stevens used several aliases
while living at Vancouver, British Columbia, Portland, Ore., and
Spokane, where he was in the fourth and final year of law school
when re-arrested in January.
   His name was one of several that surfaced after the nationally
syndicated show ``Manhunt'' television program aired Dec. 8 on the
Green River slayings.
   Robert Stevens said he knew his brother had been in jail but was
unaware he was a fugitive when he drove his parents to New England
in 1982.
   The Green River investigation takes its name from the river south
of Seattle where the bodies of the first five victims were found in
1982. The killer is believed responsible for the deaths of at least
40 women and is suspected in the disappearances of eight others in
Washington and Oregon from 1982 to 1985.
</TEXT>
