   Students said they blocked Bolivar Street to protest the
indefinite closing of two high schools in Chiriqui, in the western
part of the country, and one in Colon, 50 miles north of Panama
City, after anti-government demonstrations last week.
   The Education Ministry has warned that it will close any school
where there are disturbances in the weeks before the scheduled
change of government Sept. 1.
   One student died and several others were injured at the
university Aug. 3 when police fired birdshot to break up a
demonstration.
   Acting President Manuel Solis Palma's term expires Sept. 1, but
the lack of a successor threatens to create a vacuum in the
government.
   International observers say the opposition defeated the
government presidential candidate by a landslide in May 7 elections,
which the government annulled.
   The opposition is demanding its victory be recognized so it can
take power and that Noriega step down as chief of the Defense
Forces, a post that makes him the country's de facto leader.
   Government and military representatives have refused both
demands, but continued talks with the opposition on Wednesday.
   An Organization of American States mission that has been
mediating the talks is to report on progress on Aug. 23.
   Noriega was indicted in Florida on U.S. drug trafficking and
money laundering charges. He denies the charges.
