<FIRST>r a AM-Flight255 1stLd-Writethru a0594 08-16 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 255, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0594,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relatives of Victims of 1987 Northwest Crash Fear Trial Will Revive
Pain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `The second ..., with 4 grafs to UPDATE with
evening ceremony; picks up 6th graf pvs: ``I would ...; Cecelia in 3rd
graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEOFFREY HAYNES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many who lost loved ones in the nation's
second-worst air disaster fear they'll relive the tragedy when
liability suits come to trial in October, said a member of a support
group for relatives of crash victims.
   Northwest Flight 255 crashed at Detroit Metropolitan Airport in
suburban Romulus on the hot, humid night of Aug. 16, 1987, killing
154 people on board and two people on the ground.
   The jet failed to gain altitude during takeoff and slammed into
an overpass on Interstate 94. The sole survivor was Cecelia Cichan,
then 4.
   The little girl is living with her aunt and uncle, Rita and Frank
Lumpkin, in Birmingham, Ala., shielded from media inquiries. She
lost her mother, father and 6-year-old brother in the crash.
   About 300 people, family and friends of the dead, met on a grassy
hillside overlooking Middlebelt Road at Interstate 94, where the
jetliner broke apart in flames moments after takeoff.
   ``As long as some of us can manage to walk up that hill, we will
be here,'' said the Rev. Ron Lund, who heads a survivors' support
group.
   The site has been decorated with wooden carvings of white-painted
doves, each bearing a victim's name and arranged to form the number
``255.'' For a second consecutive year, survivors who met at the
hillside held small flashlights to illuminate the flight number at
8:46 p.m. EDT _ the time of the crash.
   ``All the people here _ they know what you've experienced. They
know how you feel,'' said Nancy Engelhart of Bay City, whose sister,
brother-in-law and two nephews died in the crash.
   The two years haven't erased the pain, she said. ``It's hard to
get used to. You still expect to see them walk through the door,''
she said of Sue Byelich, 48, Don Byelich, 46, and their sons Mike,
16, and Brad, 14.
   ``I would say the first year was a breeze compared to the second
year. It's like reality has set in,'' said Betty Polec, an organizer
of Flight 255: Their Spirit Lives On, a support group for those who
lost relatives and friends in the crash.
   ``We have the memories of our loved ones, but they are so
painful,'' she said. ``And it's getting closer to the trial and
that's going to open up the wounds again.''
   The liability trial is set for Oct. 2 in U.S. District Court in
Detroit. Northwest attorney Carroll Dubuc says it could take four to
five months to settle the 102 suits pending against Northwest and
McDonnell Douglas, which built the MD-80 plane that crashed.
   Forty-six suits have been settled, Dubuc said.
   Officials for Northwest, the nation's fourth-largest airline, say
the company has rebounded from the disaster. A record number of
passengers are expected to fly Northwest this year. Record profits
of $35.5 million were reported in 1988.
   ``The passage of time tends to make an event like that less vivid
in the minds of traveler,'' Northwest spokesman Bob Gibbons said.
``Most airlines that experience this sort of tragedy note a decline
in passengers immediately after the accident, but normal levels
return shortly thereafter.''
   In May, the nation's fourth-largest airline launched a new
corporate identity program, complete with a new logo, repainted jets
and new uniforms for flight attendants. Gibbons says the changes
were made to spruce up the image of the expanding company and
unrelated to the crash.
   At Detroit Metropolitan Airport, emergency plans have been
altered and fine-tuned as a result of the tragedy.
   Some of the lessons learned two years ago will be used during a
mock disaster drill in September, said Mark Sparks, director of the
Emergency Management Division for the Wayne County Sheriff's
Department.
   The sheriff's department has arranged for a hotel to house
families of passengers in the event of a plane crash, and a corps of
multilingual chaplains of all denominations has been established to
console families.
</TEXT>
