<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0810EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:CountryMusic Adv21   08-16 0918</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Country Music, Adv 21,0941</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs, Aug 21 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Las Vegas of Country Music</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY NACHTIGAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRANSON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Roy Clark first visited this community
nestled in a lush Ozark Mountain valley eight years ago, the country
music entertainer couldn't believe his eyes.
   Vehicles bearing license plates from nearly every state stretched
bumper-to-bumper for miles on the winding main strip, creeping past
miniature golf courses, go-cart rides, water slides and arts and
crafts shops swarming with tourists.
   Clark also noticed long lines of people waiting to get into
country music theaters where local performers sang, put on skits and
told corny jokes in a wholesome, family atmosphere.
   ``I was amazed. I said, `What is this doing here in the middle of
nowhere?''' Clark says.
   The Grammy-winning guitarist and co-host of television's ``Hee
Haw'' had stumbled on what local promoters call the country music
show capital of the world.
   With about 20 glittery theaters lining Missouri 76, better known
as 76 Country Music Boulevard, Branson is also billed as the Las
Vegas of country music _ but with an emphasis on family.
   ``You can see more Nashville stars in Branson than you can in
Nashville or anywhere else,'' boasts Bill Jones, executive manager
of the local chamber of commerce.
   The list of performers appearing in Branson this summer reads
like a Who's Who of country music: Barbara and Louise Mandrell, Mel
Tillis, Ray Stevens, Dolly Parton, Mickey Gilley, Tammy Wynette,
Janie Fricke, Pat Boone, Conway Twitty, Ricky Skaggs, Rodney
Crowell, the Gatlin Brothers, Sweethearts of the Rodeo, Highway 101,
Ronnie Milsap, Tom T. Hall, Porter Waggoner and Moe Bandy.
   City officials estimate that at least 3.25 million people saw
country music shows in Branson last year during the peak June-August
tourist season. Several theater owners say business is even better
this year, and Clark is considering staying open year-round instead
of closing in the winter months.
   ``I found out after I became acquainted with Branson that
everyone else in life knew about it but me,'' Clark said. ``I run
into people in almost every state who say they plan Branson every
year as part of their vacation.''
   Branson has a population of 2,500, but on a typical summer day
tourists swell the southwest Missouri town to 30,000 or more.
   Jones predicts that 5 million people will visit Branson this
year, up 1 million from 1988. That's more people than annually visit
Yellowstone Park or the Grand Canyon.
   Vacationers are drawn by the breathtaking mountain scenery, the
camping, fishing and boating available at several huge lakes nearby,
and two old-time theme parks, Silver Dollar City and Shepherd of the
Hills.
   And, of course, they come to hear country music. From theaters
seating a few hundred people to an outdoor ampitheater with a
capacity of 15,000, Branson offers more than 40,000 seats for
country music shows.
   Clark liked what he saw in Branson and spent $12 million to build
a 1,200-seat theater and a 191-room hotel and convention center
featuring a smaller Las Vegas-style showroom.
   He was the first to regularly feature top-name entertainers. Soon
Freddy Fender, Boxcar Willie and Danny Davis and the Nashville Brass
opened theaters along the heavily developed strip, where land is
scarce and commands more than $2,000 a square foot.
   ``It's no longer possible for anyone to come in and start a
theater on a shoestring,'' Jones says. ``It's now become big
business and big money.''
   Clark, who plays about 30 dates a year in his own club, compares
Branson to the atmosphere that existed in Nashville, the recording
capital of country music, 50 years ago.
   ``Not to take away from Nashville, but Nashville is commercial,''
said Clark, relaxing in his plush travel bus after a matinee
performance at his Roy Clark Celebrity Theatre.
   ``Here, the music industry is treated in its true art form. I've
often said the most fun I've ever had in my life was when I played
for free. You're not performing, you're just playing country music.
That's sort of the attitude of country music in Branson.''
   Several of the shows are family operations. The Mabe family has
run and starred in their Baldknobbers Hillbilly Jamboree for 30
years, initially starting with 25 folding chairs. Today the
Baldknobbers play to packed audiences in a 1,700-seat theater.
   ``There was a lot of worry about the future of these family run
theaters when the big-name stars came to the area,'' said Tommy
Bilyeu, a member of the Baldknobbers' show for the last 20 years.
``But the more shows that come in, the more our business grows.''
   Branson's country music success can be partly attributed to its
central location.
   ``Our major market is the haven of country music, the Midwest and
Southwest,'' Jones said. ``People from Texas, Iowa, Oklahoma and
Louisiana through the ages have been our big drawing cards.''
   In addition, country and bluegrass music have flourished in these
rugged Ozark hills for years. Many country stars got their start on
``Ozarks Jubilee,'' a live nationally televised show in the 1950s
that originated in Springfield.
   If Pat Boone has his way, Branson will step further into the
national country spotlight. Boone says he's working to develop a
television show such as ``Ozark Jubilee'' that would be based in
Branson. His wife, Shirley, was the daughter of ``Jubilee'' host Red
Foley.
   ``I think the time is right for it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Mon Aug. 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
