<FIRST>a a PM-ReligionintheNews Adv18   08-16 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Religion in the News, Adv 18,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Fri PMs Aug. 18, or thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Student Rabbis Serve Isolated Congregations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH J. HARPAZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When rabbinical student Amy Schwartzman began
serving a small Massachusetts congregation at age 23, she felt
handicapped by her youth and inexperience.
   ``A woman came to me for counseling about a career change,'' she
recalled. ``I've never even had a full-time job! And this women is
asking me for advice.''
   But after two years of handling Sabbath services, funerals, bar
mitzvahs and assorted life crises, Schwartzman is accustomed to her
role as spiritual _ albeit youthful _ leader of her Great Barrington
flock.
   She is one of 90 rabbis-in-training from Hebrew Union
College-Jewish Institute of Religion who spend one or two weekends a
month serving small Jewish communities around the nation.
   The only U.S. school for rabbis from the Reform branch of
Judaism, Hebrew Union has campuses in Manhattan, Cincinnati, Los
Angeles and Jerusalem.
   Aside from on-the-job training, the student pulpit program gives
the novice rabbis ``a sense of service to the Reform Judaism
movement. In some of these places, our students are keeping these
congregations alive,'' said Rabbi Norman Cohen, dean of the New York
campus.
   The 35-family Congregation Gates of Prayer in New Iberia, La.,
has been using Hebrew Union students since the 1940s.
   ``It's good for us and it's good for them,'' said Steve Lahasky,
congregation president. ``We give them all the consideration of a
fully ordained rabbi. If we need counseling, a bar or bat mitzvah or
the naming of a new baby, they're our rabbi.''
   Many of the congregations that use student rabbis are too remote
or too poor to attract full-time rabbis, who can earn $45,000 and
up. The students are a bargain at $9,000, plus transportation and
lodging. Some congregations even save on hotels by putting students
up in private homes, an arrangement that lacks privacy but creates
strong bonds.
   ``They want to talk to me about everything Jewish that they've
ever heard of, and I want to be there for them,'' said Schwartzman,
whose stays in congregants' homes have also included non-spiritual
pursuits like helping out with gardening and teaching kids to play
knock-hockey.
   ``The old people think of me almost as a granddaughter,'' she
said. ``The other side of it is I have a great connection with all
the kids.''
   Working in areas away from cities where Yiddish expressions and
Jewish food are part of mainstream culture also gives the students
``a different perspective on Jewish communities and their needs,''
said Cohen.
   Eric Weiss, who was ordained as a rabbi in June after serving the
Louisiana congregation, said ``getting to know Jews of the South''
was one of the best aspects of his Louisiana stint.
   ``They're not a part of a majority Jewish culture at all,'' he
said. ``It's not like being in New York or Los Angeles. They put a
lot of effort into their community because they can't rely on big
Jewish organizations'' to keep the religion alive.
   Peter Shaktman, 27, who served a Jupiter, Fla., congregation,
agreed.
   ``One of the frustrations of the rabbinate in general is working
with people who are apathetic and jaded,'' he said. ``One of the
ironies of these pulpits is that even though they're often small,
they really feel a certain mission about maintaining their
religion.''
   Assisting that mission can seem like an awesome responsibility.
   ``I'm the rabbi for a 25-mile radius and I'm not even a rabbi,''
said Stephen Weisman, 28, who served a 72-family congregation in
Fredericksburg, Va. ``They're coming to me, expecting me to be the
voice of knowledge and wisdom, when I have to learn from them and
all of their traditions.''
   Weisman says he ``fudged'' his first funeral, ``probably very
badly. The blessing of never having a death in my family, probably
was a curse.''
   He added, grinning: ``Then I had to do four funerals in one
month. Now I know how to do it inside out.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Aug. 18.</NOTE>
