<DOCNO> AP890816-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1335EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:ExorcistSequel Adv24   08-16 1036</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Exorcist Sequel, Adv 24,1066</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thu AMs, Aug 24 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Demons, Deaths and Exorcists Romp Through Georgetown</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifteen years ago, an adolescent's spinning
head terrified movie audiences throughout the world, as the ghastly
specter of possession chillingly chiseled its way through ``The
Exorcist.''
   Well brace yourselves, horror movie fans, ``The Exorcist: 1990''
is on its way.
   William Peter Blatty, who wrote the original from his novel of
the same name, has written this third sequel, based on his 1983
novel, ``Legion,'' and is directing. Although ``Legion'' does not
concern possession, Blatty has added an exorcism to his script.
   William Kinderman, the rumpled police detective who had a role in
``The Exorcist,'' investigates a series of ritualistic murders in
``The Exorcist: 1990.''
   Blatty shot on location this summer in the Georgetown University
area, where he once went to school and where much of the original
1974 film was also made.
   ``I would like it to be thought as the one and only sequel to
`The Exorcist,''' he said.
   Blatty held all sequel rights to the original but allowed Warner
Bros., which released the first movie starring Linda Blair, Ellen
Burstyn and Max Von Sydow, to do ``Exorcist II: The Heretic.'' The
sequel was written by William Goodhart and directed by John Boorman
and was both a critical and commercial failure.
   Blatty won an Academy Award for ``The Exorcist,'' which also
received six Oscar nominations including best picture and director
(William Friedkin).
   Locations for the new movie have included Holy Trinity Church and
the original Georgetown General Hospital, which will again be a
hospital in the movie, although it is now a dormitory for male and
female Georgetown students.
   Blatty says there will also be a scene on the long stairway where
Father Damien Karras tumbled to his death in one of the most
hair-raising scenes of the original.
   Members of the cast include George C. Scott and Viveca Lindfors,
as well as Georgetown students making their debut as extras and
former Surgeon General C. Everett Koop in a cameo appearance as
himself.
   ``I think the occult is playing a larger and larger role in
American society,'' Koop told publicists for the film in a video
interview. ``I think there are some things about it that are hokey,
but there is a very real satanic worshiping group of people in this
country, and I have been involved in public health issues that deal
with that three times in eight years.
   ``I think Shakespeare was right when he said that we don't know
everything in earth and heaven. I'd say we only have a very small
smattering of what's really yet to be known.''
   In the movie, Koop, who left office in July, has coffee with a
priest in The Tombs, a restaurant near the campus.
   The bearded pediatrician said his literary agent called him and
said the filmmakers were ``looking for someone recognizable because
they wanted to authenticate a shot to make it look like Washington
with real people.''
   The shooting came during the break between spring and summer
terms, so disruption on the university campus was held to a minimum,
said Betsy Wittleder of the school's public information office.
   ``Basically, other than when they have some filming going on and
people are requested not to go into that area because of the
filming, life continues as usual,'' she said.
   On one recent afternoon, Blatty, wearing jeans, sneakers and a
Georgetown baseball cap, filmed a scene in which Lindfors, in a
nurse's uniform, walks down the front steps of the hospital with a
worn carpetbag in her hand.
   ``We want it to be an extaordinarily good film, and we want to
scare the pants off the audience,'' he said.
   Blatty thought the debacle of ``Exorcist II'' put a stigma on the
current project. ``But if the film is good, it (the stigma) will
vanish overnight,'' he said.
   The original ``Exorcist'' also received its share of brickbats
from critics.
   Michael Billington of the Illustrated London News said, ``It
exploits the subject of diabolic possession without telling you
anything about it.'' Stanley Kauffmann, said, ```The Exorcist' makes
no sense,'' although he conceded that ``if you want to be shaken, it
will scare the hell out of you.''
   Despite the mixed reviews, the film grossed a reported $160
million worldwide, a record at the time.
   The film told the story of a girl, played in both 1974 and 1977
by Linda Blair, who is possessed by the devil and causes several
violent deaths. Blair, whose career plunged after the ``Exorcist''
movies, is not in the third film. Besides Scott and Lindfors, the
cast also includes Ed Flanders (``St. Elsewhere'') and Sylvia Sidney.
   ``The story that I had constructed just didn't have any place for
her,'' Blatty said. ``Rather than taking a character I had to use
and then trying to build a story around her, I thought the faithful
thing to do was to create a great story and see who fits into it.
Linda did not, unfortunately.''
   Blatty said the sequel will begin where ``The Exorcist'' ended
and will follow the story of ``Legion'' except for ``a totally
different ending.'' The story involves a friendship between a police
lieutenant, played by Scott, and a priest, played by Flanders.
   ``There will be one, I hope breathaking moment at the end of the
film, an effect that has never been seen before,'' the director
said. ``I hope we can do it.''
   But the film will not emphasize the spectacular special effects
that helped make ``The Exorcist'' such a hit.
   ``This one does not rely upon spinning heads for shock,'' he
said. ``The terror is in the shadows in the mind.''
   ``There is almost no act of violence,'' said Scott. ``I think it
goes to a different level than your normal spooky picture.''
   But don't worry. It's going to be scary anyway, said Blatty. ``It
is pure entertainment that uses theology only as it contributes to
the excitement.
   ``I have independently counted 30 shocks, or little jumps out of
the seat, some much higher than others.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, Aug. 24</NOTE>
