<DOCNO> AP890816-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0214EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   08-16 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Are 1990 Prices Scaring Buyers?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A surge in early-August car and truck sales may be
an indication that consumers are shying away from waiting for this
fall's 1990 model cars and the higher prices they will be carrying.
   Figures released Tuesday by the eight major automakers with U.S.
assembly plants showed that car and truck sales during the Aug. 1-10
period rose 8.2 percent over the same period last year. Car sales
were up 7.4 percent and truck sales rose 9.4 percent.
   Late 1989 model cars may be looking more attractive to consumers
who have heard recent news of tentative price increases by the Big
Three automakers ranging from 3.4 percent to 5 percent for 1990
models.
   The increased sales also may have been fueled by manufacturers'
incentives, which have been around in some form since early April.
   When asked if he thought some consumers planning to buy a 1990
car had decided to beat the price increases by purchasing a late
1989 model, analyst Ron Glantz said flatly, ``I hope so.
   ``I think in all probability there are people buying a little
earlier than usual, but not many,'' said Glantz of Montgomery
Securities Inc. in San Francisco.
   He said that later this month and next month, as the 1989 model
year draws to a close, more people may decide to buy now rather than
wait for later.
   ``We haven't had any dealer advertisements yet saying `Beat the
price increase.' They should start soon,'' he said.
   General Motors Corp. said its tentative prices will be about 3.4
percent above 1898 levels, Ford Motor Co. said its prices will jump
about 4.8 percent and Chrysler Corp.'s 1990 prices will be about 5
percent more than in 1989.
   The companies said some of the increases are due to governmental
requirements that they install passive restraint systems _ air bags
or automatic seat belts _ in 1990 model cars.
   ``Let's face it, the consumer won't pay for safety,'' Glantz said.
   The wild card in late 1989 and early 1990 model year sales
promises to be incentives. Automakers and some dealers would like to
get rid of them, but consumers are used to being told how big a
rebate they'll get if they drive away in a new car now.
   ``They (manufacturers) are filing for pretty big price
increases,'' said analyst David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
in New York. ``But whether they will be real-world (prices) or just
on paper to be superseded with rebates is a good question.
   ``I think they will wait for about 15 minutes, see that sales are
slow and come out with rebates.''
   The incentives are designed to give sales a boost, but they
haven't done the kind of job this year as they have in the past.
   From Jan. 1 through Aug. 10, car and truck sales were 3.6 percent
behind last year's pace, falling to an average daily rate of 38,063
from a rate of 39,500 in the year-ago period. Car sales were off 4.8
percent and truck sales were down 1.5 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
