<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0224EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-HomeShopping-GTE Bjt   08-16 0722</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Home Shopping-GTE, Bjt,0745</SECOND>
<HEAD>Video Retailer Challenges $100 Million Libel Award</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Home Shopping Network Inc. pitches
cookware and jewelry to millions of TV viewers, but the video
retailer's more important audience is a judge who will rule on its
appeal of a $100 million libel award.
   The financially ailing company, which could be devastated by such
a large forfeiture, is seeking to reverse or reduce the jury award
granted GTE Corp. earlier this month.
   In an earlier lawsuit of its own, HSN had accused GTE of
installing an inadequate telephone system at the retailer's
Clearwater headquarters, which it blamed for missed calls from
viewers and the loss of millions of dollars worth of sales.
   But the case boomeranged on HSN when GTE successfully
countersued, claiming that its reputation was smeared by HSN's
accusations, which it called false.
   The HSN appeal awaiting state Circuit Judge Howard Rives when he
returns from vacation later this month alleges 336 faults in the
six-week case, ranging from improper evidence to Rives' demeanor,
described as grumpy.
   The Aug. 2 verdict ``was grossly excessive and was the product of
prejudice, passion and gross confusion,'' said HSN in its appeal
motions filed Monday.
   Much of the appeal focuses on Rives' decision to permit GTE's
libel counterclaim to be heard in the same trial as the $1.5 billion
HSN suit. Rives also is accused of prejudicing jurors against HSN
and its attorneys.
   GTE spokeswoman Jan Morris declined to comment on the motions,
but said the Stamford, Conn.-based telecommunications giant would
answer the challenges in court.
   A hearing on the appeal before Rives has been set for Nov. 28.
   ``This promises to go on for months,'' said HSN spokewoman Kathy
Jurado. ``We said all along we'll try to get this overturned.''
   Nonetheless, some people familiar with the case speculate that
GTE may be interested in settling the matter by working out a lower
settlement with HSN, which claimed it lost $500 million in sales
when GTE's telephone system could not handle an increasing volume of
calls in 1986 and 1987.
   GTE executives also were accused of trying to hide the problem
from HSN, which now uses MCI Communications Corp. telephones.
   ``GTE is in a very strong bargaining position,'' said James
Stork, an analyst with the Chicago investment firm Duff &amp; Phelps
Inc. ``This is really not a large amount of money for a company like
GTE. They might just make some sort of deal to end it.''
   In closing trial arguments, GTE attorney Roy Reardon said the
company only wanted to clear its name and did not want to devastate
HSN with a huge award. ``I didn't come down here to look for
money,'' he told the jury.
   The judgement, one of the highest ever awarded in a libel case,
struck the 7-year-old video retail pioneer at a bad time.
   HSN reported slumping sales and a $5.9 million loss for the
quarter ended May 31. For all of 1988, the company reported a profit
of $18 million on sales of $730 million. Its stock, which surged to
$47 a share in mid-1987, bottomed out at $3 a share hours after the
jury verdict.
   Meanwhile, two of HSN's principal competitors plan to merge next
month. CVN Cos. of Minneapolis and QVC Network of West Chester, Pa.,
say their combined sales will knock HSN from the top spot in video
retailing for the first time.
   Some legal experts said HSN's best option is to aggressively
appeal the libel ruling. Floyd Abrams, a libel-law specialist, said
he believed the facts of the case did not support the huge award.
   ``If there is no evidence that GTE suffered damages as the result
of the libel, it will be difficult for the damage verdict to be
sustained because of its elephantine nature,'' he said.
   However, Abrams noted that the award _ even if knocked down _
could encourge more companies to file libel suits in cases of rumors
or common corporate bad-mouthing in the hope that other juries are
equally generous.
   Earlier this month, American Express Co. admitted its
representatives circulated false stories claiming that international
banker Edmond Safra, an Amex competitor, was tied to money
laundering. American Express opted for an $8 million settlement
rather that risk a possible libel battle in court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
