<FIRST>u f BC-LorenoPay     08-16 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Loreno Pay,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Frank Lorenzo Paid $1.25 Million Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp. suffered a $719 million loss last
year, the most of any U.S. airline company. But Chairman Frank
Lorenzo's $1.25 million cash compensation made him one of the
nation's highest-paid airline chief executives.
   Texas Air's annual proxy statement, which is being mailed to
stockholders this week, says Lorenzo received salary and bonuses of
$977,225 and ``relocation'' compensation of $275,000.
   Houston-based Texas Air is the parent company of Eastern
Airlines, which is in bankruptcy reorganization because of a
5-month-old strike by the pilots, Machinists and flight attendants
unions. Texas Air also owns Continental Airlines, which went through
bankruptcy reorganization in 1983 during similar labor strife.
   Texas Air spokesman Art Kent declined to discuss Lorenzo's salary.
   But Eastern's unions called it is outrageous, especially since he
has constantly demanded concessions from them.
   ``Given the fact that he's put two airlines in bankruptcy and
hasn't done anything for the common stockholders, I think it's
atrocious,'' pilots union spokesman Ron Cole told The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
   By comparison, AMR Corp., parent of industry profit leader
American Airlines, paid its chairman, Robert Crandall, salary and
bonuses of $1 million last year. Highly profitable Delta Air Lines
will not publish its new proxy until next month. But in fiscal 1988,
Delta Chairman Ronald W. Allen earned cash compensation of $456,683.
</TEXT>
