<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     08-16 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Off, Stocks Up 273 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar declined against the Japanese yen
today after a four-day climb, while stock prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange rose for the second day.
   The dollar closed at 141.80, down 0.40 yen from Tuesday's close
of 142.20 yen. It opened at 141.70 yen and moved between 141.40 yen
and 141.90 yen. The dollar had risen 3.35 yen in four trading days
before today's decline.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which gained 139.07 points
Tuesday, rose 273.46 points, or 0.79 percent, closing at 35,084.15.
   Dealers said the U.S. currency started lower following
dollar-selling on the Singapore and Sydney foreign exchange markets,
but rose in afternoon trading, which remained light.
   ``Japanese trust banks bought dollars aggressively toward the
close,'' said Minori Takeuchi, a trader at Chemical Bank.
   Minoru Ozawa, a foreign exchange dealer with the Taiyo Kobe Bank,
said dealers were positioning themselves before announcements of
U.S. housing starts and investment utilization rates today.
   The stock market today ``was quite strong, with the advance quite
broad-based,'' said a trader at Kleinwort Benson International, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Trading was light at 550 million shares. Traders said there was a
fair amount of index buying, with people returning from summer
holidays contributing to the advance.
   Yoshio Shimoyama of Nikko Securities said stock traders, too,
were awaiting the U.S. announcements, but were optimistic.
</TEXT>
