<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was lower in early European trading
today as market participants took profits ahead of a series of U.S.
economic figures to be released later this week, currency dealers
said.
   Gold prices rose.
   Dealers said many in the market chose to cut out before
Washington today releases industrial activity and housing starts
figures for July, the June trade report on Thursday and the consumer
price index on Friday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.40 yen to a closing 141.80 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 142.20 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday's
prices, included: 1.9435 West German marks, down from 1.9500; 1.6749
Swiss francs, down from 1.6790; 6.5650 French francs, down from
6.5835; 2.1847 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1905; 1,395.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,397.50; and 1.1785 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1822.
   In London, the dollar fell slightly against the British pound. It
cost $1.5751 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5735 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at $368.25 a troy ounce, compared with late
Tuesday's $365.75. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $367.60.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $367.90, up from $366.25 late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $3.12 to close at $368.84.
   Silver was quoted in London at $5.24 a troy ounce, unchanged from
late Tuesday.
