<FIRST>u f PM-ArcoGasoline 1stLd-Writethru   08-16 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arco Gasoline, 1st Ld-Writethru,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arco Marketing Low-Pollution Fuel in Southern California</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to ADD details of air cleanup plan. NO pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL MONTE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlantic Richfield Co. plans to market a
lead-free gasoline for older cars and trucks that use leaded gas and
said the new fuel could cut pollution from such vehicles by up to 15
percent.
   The gasoline will go on sale next month at 750 Arco stations in
Southern California for about the same price as leaded regular
gasoline, Arco said Tuesday.
   The announcement came the same day the California Air Resources
Board unanimously adopted a sweeping 20-year plan to clean Southern
California's air, the nation's dirtiest. It will transform the way
Californians work and play.
   Arco's new gasoline was created to reduce pollution caused by the
estimated 1.2 million worst-polluting vehicles in the region _ cars
made before 1975 and trucks built before 1980.
   Arco's refinery in Carson will produce the gasoline, which is
called EC-1 for Emission Control-1 and cost about $20 million to
develop.
   ``We're making this heavy investment because we believe the
dominant fuel of the future will be gasoline, rather than the
alternatives you've been hearing about,'' said Lodwrick M. Cook,
Arco chairman and chief executive officer. Those alternatives
include methanol and natural gas.
   ``What we hope to demonstrate today is that we can clean up
gasoline,'' Cook said.
   The fuel has an octane level of 88 and contains methyl tertiary
butyl ether, which Arco spokesman Al Greenstein described as an
oxygenated additive.
   ``The MTBE is what makes up for the loss of octane by eliminating
the lead,'' he said. ``It's something that's on the market that
wasn't available a few years ago.''
   Arco officials said the fuel reduces chemical components that
cause smog by about one-third, and benzene, a cancer-causing
pollutant, by half. The fuel-sulfur content was reduced by 80
percent.
   ``We're pleased that Arco has taken the initiative in developing
a new gasoline that is more environmentally acceptable and which
reflects the direction of the Air Resources Board's future
regulation,'' said board Chairwoman Jananne Sharpless.
   The board Tuesday voted 8-0 to adopt the smog-control plan
despite industry objections the plan will strangle the region's
economy. It will target emissions from everything from motor
vehicles, factories and auto paint to dry cleaners, bakeries,
aerosol cans and backyard grills.
   The plan embraces land-use planning, transportation programs and
stricter industry standards. It was completed in March by the South
Coast Air Quality Management District and the Southern California
Association of Governments.
   Regional air quality officials estimate that the plan will cost
$2.6 billion a year. Business interests say annual costs will reach
$12 billion.
   Enactment was hailed as a ``leap into a `Brave New World''' by
Harriet Wieder, an Orange County supervisor on the nine-member air
resources board.
   The plan was branded ``Texas justice'' by William T. Huston, a
developer leading a coalition of business and labor interests
fighting to revise the plane. ``They're acting as their own judge,
jury and executioner,'' he said.
   Arco is working on another blend that will be sold elsewhere in
the West, the company said. Arco stations are in five Western
states: California, Washington, Oregon, Arizona and Nevada.
   When asked if Arco was pushed, or jumped, to develop the
alternative to leaded fuel, Cook said, ``A little of both ... but if
there are cleaner fuels to be burned, we'll be producing those too.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890816-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0911EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-UAL     08-16 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAL, Pilots' Union, Consider Employee-Ownership Option</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Line Pilots Association has told its
United Airlines members they have difficult choices ahead amid
reports the union and the carrier are considering plans including an
employee-owned stake in the company.
   ALPA Chairman Rick Dubinsky said in a letter to union members
Tuesday that United's parent, UAL Corp. _ which has received a $5.4
billion, $240-a-share takeover proposal from investor Marvin Davis _
undoubtedly will be bought out by somebody.
   ``In fact, whether you like it or not, you and all the other
employees are going to help pay for it,'' Dubinsky said. ``The only
choice is whether we buy it for someone else or ourselves.''
   He said United pilots may have to ``act rapidly, decisively and
conclusively to assure our survival and prosperity,'' noting
acquisition by an outsider likely would mean a leveraged buyout that
could saddle the company with loads of new debt.
   ``We must watch this situation very closely, insuring that we
have all the information we need to make the difficult choices that
are inevitable,'' Dubinsky said.
   UAL stock closed $4.25 lower at $254.25 a share on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   Several news reports indicated ALPA and UAL officials met during
the weekend to discuss a plans for either a management-employee
buyout or recapitalization that would put a big enough block of UAL
stock in an employee stock ownership plan to help block any hostile
takeover attempt.
   Spokesmen for UAL and ALPA refused to comment Tuesday on whether
meetings were held during the weekend or on reports of the purported
plans.
   ``There's nothing out there to make me feel tremendously
uncomfortable,'' said John Peterpaul, vice president of the
International Association of Machinists, referring to the reported
discussions on a buyout plan. ``We're sitting here watching it.''
   The Machinists union represents mechanics at United and other
airlines. The third union representing United employees, the
Association of Flight Attendants, did not return phone calls seeking
comment.
   Dubinsky said in his letter that the level of contribution to any
ESOP plan by the pilots would depend on the number of employees and
employee groups participating.
   ``Depending on the declared interest of the other employees, we
may need a great level of participation or a slight level,'' his
letter read. ``It would make good sense for you to be financially
prepared for the worst.''
   United's pilots in the past have expressed an interest in buying
the company, and in 1987 proposed a $4.5 billion plan to buy the
airline from its then-parent Allegis Corp. Last week ALPA officials
said its advisers were being consulted about the Davis bid.
   In addition to Davis, New York-based Pan Am Corp. has expressed
interest in a possible merger with UAL.
   Louis Marckesano, an analyst with Janney Montgomery Scott Inc.,
said a deal involving UAL management and its employees would
eliminate fears in Congress and the Department of Transportation
that the airline would be stripped of valuable assets, as might
happen with a leveraged buyout.
   A leveraged buyout is an acquisition financed mainly by borrowed
funds that are repaid with the target company's cash flow or the
sale of its assets.
   ``With that kind of plan, you would assure continuation of UAL as
a strong airline,'' he said, referring to a management-labor buyout.
``It would create labor peace, which would be pretty important in
the future.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890816-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0916EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-DiGiorgio     08-16 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DiGiorgio,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Food Distributor May Be Sold To Prevent Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All or part of the Di Giorgio Corp. food
distributor may be sold to prevent a hostile $165 million takeover
by New Jersey investor Arthur Goldberg, the company said.
   Di Giorgio Chairman Peter Scott said Tuesday the company's board
does not believe the $32-per-share offer by Goldberg's DIG
Acquisition Corp. reflects the true value of the firm.
   At a meeting Monday, the company's directors unanimously rejected
Goldberg's offer as inadequate.
   The board said Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. had been hired to
explore the possible sale of part or all of the company, which
distributes fresh and frozen foods and manufactures building
materials.
   Goldberg, who owns 14.1 percent of the company's stock, has
hinted that if he succeeded in his bid, he would keep Di Giorgio's
White Rose food distribution subsidiary but sell off the building
materials business.
   The Di Giorgio board in June rejected a Goldberg bid of $30 a
share, or $153 million.
   Other investors expressing interest in Di Giorgio in recent years
have included New York investor Mario Gabelli, London-based MIM
Ltd., and the Belzberg family of Canada.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890816-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 0953EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f ResortsInternationalReportsMassiveLoss     08-16 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>Resorts International Reports Massive Loss</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gaming analysts believe Resorts
International Inc. will have to make a dramatic move to pull out of
its financial slump.
   On Tuesday, one day after Resorts posted a large second-quarter
loss, the conclusions were near unanimous:
   ``They have got to recapitalize in some way, shape or form,''
said Saul Leonard, a Los Angeles-based analyst with Laventhol &amp;
Horwath.
   With two gaming halls, ``selling one might be a very viable
alternative,'' he said.
   Resorts blamed its second-quarter losses on slower casino
business, but analysts said the company must go beyond simply
finding more gamblers.
   At stake in the financial crunch is the casino license of owner
Merv Griffin, the entertainer who purchased the company last year
from developer Donald Trump.
   State gaming regulators will hold hearings next month to consider
whether Resorts has enough financial stability to change Griffin's
interim authorization into a license.
   Resorts, based here, will have to pay more than $130 million in
interest and principal this year, but its operations likely will not
generate enough money to cover that. In 1988, the company's cash
flow was only $60.2 million.
   According to figures issued Monday, Resorts posted a $27.9
million net loss for the second quarter of 1989, compared to a $13.8
million net loss for the same period in 1988.
   For the first six months of 1989, the company reported a net loss
of $46.6 million, compared to a $17.6 million net loss for last
year's first half.
   Resorts' earnings from operations for the second quarter were
reported at $411,000, compared to $8.9 million for the same period
last year. Earnings from operations for the first six months were
$6.1 million, compared to $12.9 million for the 1988 first half.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, Resorts
blamed shrinking revenue at its Atlantic City casino on fewer bets
wagered by patrons.
   ``The transitional state of the company's marketing efforts
contributed to this, as did the fact that during the second quarter,
portions of the casino were out of service due to renovations,''
said a statement by a public relations firm for the gaming and real
estate company.
   Resorts also cited lower revenues at its Paradise Island casino
because of a ``significant decrease in the table game hold
percentage'' _ the ratio of casino win to the total amount of chips
purchased.
   Some news about Resorts' future plans will come at a bondholders'
meeting here set for Sept. 19. Company executives said they will
outline a revised business plan, including a possible capital
restructuring.
   In reviewing the Resorts crisis in recent weeks, analysts have
said one option is an exchange offer in which holders of some or all
of the company's $930 million in junk bonds would be offered equity
in return for relinquishing debt.
   Griffin, however, ``is going to have a very hard time
renegotiating his debt simply because he has already taken the
bondholders to the cleaners,'' said Marvin B. Roffman, a gaming
analyst with the Philadelphia investment house of Janney Montgomery
Scott Inc.
   The bondholders, he said, ``could take Merv to court and stick it
to him for misstatements in the offering prospectus.''
   Griffin faces further woes, Roffman said, including ``a declining
market, higher operating costs, eroding market shares caused by
woefully inadequate facilities and potential labor problems with
upcoming union talks.''
   ``And in the middle of all this, that interest rate meter just
doesn't stop ticking,'' he said.
   Griffin will likely have to add more of his own money into
Resorts, Roffman said.
   Leonard was a bit more optimistic. ``There are always options.
The question is whether they are options that Merv Griffin would
prefer,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890816-0219 </DOCNO>
