<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1014EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     08-16 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0317</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market opened broadly higher today,
shaking off its latest doldrums.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 13.28 points to
2,701.06 after a half-hour of trading at 10 a.m. EDT.
   Advancing issues outpaced declines by nearly 2 to 1 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 647 issues up, 308 down and 500 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 24.89 million shares.
   Analysts said the market could break out of its recent sluggish
mood after having digested interest-rate worries that helped depress
bond prices lately.
   Wall Street analysts said earlier this week that the markets were
adjusting to the likelihood that the Federal Reserve might not lower
interest rates after government statistics in recent weeks showed a
moderately expanding economy.
   ``The market looks like it wants to move ahead on a fairly broad
front,'' said Lewis Smith, analyst with Bear Stearns Cos.
   A Commerce Department report this morning that new housing starts
rose 0.8 percent last month had little impact on the market so far,
traders said.
   New homes and apartments were built in July at a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 1.43 million units, up from 1.42 million
units in June, the government said.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was up
0.65 to 192.73.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index had gained
1.06 to 380.88.
   On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 9.86 points to
finish at 2,687.78 in sluggish trading.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 7 to 6 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
809 issues up, 689 down and 501 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 148.77 million shares, up from 142.01
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
