<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1033EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-K-H-Varity     08-16 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-K-H-Varity,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>K-H Fails To Meet Terms of Varity Merger Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROMULUS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   K-H Corp. said it failed to meet the terms
of the merger agreement it expected to complete next month with
Toronto-based Varity Corp.
   K-H, formerly known as Fruehauf Corp., said Tuesday it notified
Varity a day earlier that it had not realized enough money from the
July 14 sale of its trailer and maritime operations to Terex Corp.
to meet the agreement with Varity. Fruehauf agreed in March to sell
the operations to Terex for about $233 million.
   Varity has 15 days to decide whether to go ahead with the merger,
K-H spokesman David Hladik said.
   Varity Chairman Victor Rice wrote Tuesday to K-H, estimating that
K-H's shortfall was $25 million to $30 million and questioning how
its earlier figure ``could be regarded even as a reasonable or good
faith estimate.''
   Rice said Varity would continue studying the matter. ``That's
really all we're going to say, what's in the letter,'' Varity
spokesman J.R. Nowling said today.
   Fruehauf Corp. changed its name Aug. 4 to K-H Corp., after the
sale to Terex. K-H Corp. President Robert Siefert said then the
acquisition of K-H by Varity should be completed next month.
   K-H said Tuesday the sale to Terex contributed to a $18.2 million
loss in the second quarter. The company lost $10.8 million in the
second quarter of 1988.
   The company said its revenue was $333.8 million for the quarter,
up from $286.5 million in the year-earlier period.
   For the first six months of the year, K-H reported a loss of
$259.9 million on revenue of $669.1 million, compared with a loss of
$27.1 million on revenue of $549.4 million in the first half of 1988.
   K-H said $13.5 million of its $18.2 million second-quarter loss
was attributable to sales of the trailer and maritime operations to
Terex Corp.
   Fruehauf had battled heavy indebtedness and weak earnings since
1986 when its managers avoided a hostile takeover by acquiring
control in a debt-financed buyout.
   The sale of the truck-trailer and maritime operations to Terex
left Kelsey-Hayes Co., maker of aluminum wheels and anti-lock
braking systems, as Fruehauf Corp.'s major business.
   The trailer business continues as Fruehauf Trailer Corp., a Terex
subsidiary, while Fruehauf Corp. changed its name to K-H.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
