<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1109EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Northwest-Japan     08-16 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Northwest-Japan,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transport Ministry Asks Northwest to Improve Plane Maintenance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's Ministry of Transport asked Northwest
Airlines Wednesday to improve its servicing of planes at Tokyo's
Narita airport, a ministry official said.
   The ministry urged Northwest to improve its maintenance because
the airline's planes have been involved in many of the flight
irregularities at Narita in recent months, the official said.
   ``A large number of Northwest flights have had to return to the
airport or be diverted because of technical problems, including
engine malfunctions,'' the official said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Northwest officials in Tokyo could not be reached for comment
immediately. At the airline's Eagan, Minn., headquarters, spokesman
Kevin Whalen said officials there had not heard anything of the
reported request and therefore could not comment in detail.
   Whalen said he was trying to reach Northwest officials in Japan,
but had been unsuccessful because it was late at night there.
   Japan's Kyodo News Service quoted Narita officials as saying
Northwest planes were involved in 16 of the 43 cases, or 38 percent,
of flight irregularities at the airport so far this year.
   Kyodo said the 16 Northwest irregularities this year included 12
in which planes were forced to return to Narita after takeoff and
four in which planes were diverted, mainly because of engine
problems.
   Whalen said he could not say if those numbers were correct.
   ``But we do have 22 departures a day from Narita, so we're
talking nearly 5,300 departures so far this year and it would be a
fraction of a percentage (involving problems), if those numbers are
right,'' he said.
   United Airlines had five flight irregularities, the second
largest number, Kyodo quoted the officials as saying.
   United spokesman Rob Doughty said he could not immediately
confirm that United had five flight irregularities this year at
Narita. He said that to his knowledge, Japanese transportation
officials had not asked United to improve its servicing of planes at
the airport.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
