<DOCNO> AP890816-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1113EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-PhilippinesDebt1stLd-Writethru     08-16 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines Debt 1st Ld-Writethru,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Debt Relief for Philippines Agreed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates, edits throughout; adds byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new agreement has been reached between the
Philippines and its creditor banks, the second under the
debt-reduction proposals of Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady, an
international monetary source said today.
   The source said the accord would both reduce the country's $28
billion debt and add new loans to it.
   In last month's agreement on the $108 billion debt of Mexico, a
choice was given to creditor banks: loan reductions, interest
reductions or new loans. Whether Mexico's total debt will be larger
or smaller remains to be worked out.
   The source said the new agreement was reached in New York between
representatives of the Philippine government and a committee of
banks led by Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.
   The source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
International Monetary Fund last May offered the Philippines about
$206 million in loans that the government of President Corazon
Aquino could use for debt relief. In the present state of the
market, the government can settle old loans for about 50 cents on
the dollar.
   The Washington Post, which first reported the debt agreement,
cited Treasury officials and bankers saying they don't consider the
accord a break with the Brady plan because it envisions that the
Philippines will try to reduce its indebtedness.
   Additional money for debt relief is expected from the World Bank,
the fund's sister organization in Washington.
   The money could also be used to reduce interest rates on the old
loans. The burden of interest payments is the heaviest part of the
Third World's $1.3 trillion debt.
   Recent reports have said that the Philippines was less interested
in reduction of its debts to the commercial banks, than in new loans
from them. Jose Fernandez, head of the Philippines central bank, has
been reported seeking $1.8 to $4 billion.
   Of the $28 billion the Philippines already owes, the bulk is held
by governments and intergovernment bodies like the fund and World
Bank, which have not permitted any reductions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890816-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1115EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru   08-16 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, 1st Ld - Writethru,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebuilding Carrier Boosts Schedule; Cuts Fares</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, Eastern also... to provide fare examples.
Picks up 6th graf, George Brennan...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines, trying to recover from a crippling
strike and emerge from bankruptcy proceedings, hopes to win back
passengers by expanding its schedule and cutting fares.
   But a union leader said Tuesday the newly announced fare
reductions by Eastern's competitors, including Trans World Airlines,
Pan American World Airways, United Airlines, American Airlines and
USAir, would hurt Eastern's efforts to rebuild.
   The carrier on Tuesday increased from 350 to 390 its daily
flights by adding 40 flights connecting Atlanta and destinations
mostly in the South and said it would fly 600 daily flights as of
Sept. 7.
   Eastern's rebuilding plan calls for 800 daily flights by year's
end, leaving the airline at about two-thirds its size before its
machinists, pilots and flight attendants walked off the job and the
carrier entered bankruptcy court proceedings in March.
   Eastern also announced discounted fares beginning Sept. 7,
including fares of $79 one-way between New York and Florida and $129
one-way between Atlanta and the West Coast. The airline said the
fares have fewer restrictions than the reduced fares announced this
week by other major carriers and allow full refunds on unused
tickets.
   George Brennan, Eastern's vice president for marketing, said the
airline already planned new discounts before the other carriers and
that Eastern's fall promotion offers tickets that ``are much easier
to use and a much better value in most cases.''
   Eastern will require three- to-seven-day advance purchase and its
rates are available nearly every day and carry no restrictive
penalties.
   The fares are available to all domestic markets, Eastern said.
   While Eastern says it has hired enough pilots and is keeping up
with maintenance despite its strike, it has been leasing five planes
and crews from its affiliated carrier, Continental Airlines. Brennan
said more planes and crews will be temporarily leased from
Continental.
   Eastern and Continental are both subsidiaries of Texas Air Corp.
   Eastern union leaders said the airline's claims to be coming back
are misleading because their low fares make it impossible to make
money.
   Machinists District 100 President Charles E. Bryan said Tuesday
passengers are going to fly on other airlines because ``they are
very reliable, first-line carriers. They're not having phantom
flights and people don't have to worry about losing their money.
   ``If Eastern tries to go even lower than the rest of the
carriers, that's just going to compound their problems. It's going
to doom the rebuilding plan, which was already doomed,'' Bryan said.
   Eastern before the March 4 strike usually had $1 billion in
revenue per quarter. In the second quarter, Eastern reported revenue
of $89.6 million.
   Management hurdled a major barrier to its rebuilding efforts last
week when a split in pilots union ranks resulted in at least 250
more pilots returning to work, boosting to 650 the number of union
members that have crossed picket lines.
   Eastern said that with its own recruitment and training program
it now has the 1,700 pilots needed for its rebuilding plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890816-0226 </DOCNO>
