<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weather Forecasts Cause Market Uncertainty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain futures opened lower and soybean futures
were mixed in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   The weak opening caught analysts by surprise because of
expectations that yesterday's rebound in prices would carry over
into today's trading.
   The buying of soybean futures could be restricted because of the
uncertain weather outlook, said Steve Freed, an analyst with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago. Earlier this week, forecasts called
for a relatively dry weekend in major crop producing states. Now
more rain is being forecast.
   Wheat futures are expected to be pressured by reports that
Algeria's bid for 250,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat under the export
bonus program has been rejected.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 1} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.98\ a bushel; corn was \
cent lower to \ cent higher with September at $3.34{ a bushel; oats
were { cent to 1 cent lower with September at $1.39 a bushel;
soybeans were \ cent lower to 6{ cents higher with August at $6.29 a
bushel.
   Livestock futures were mixed and pork futures higher in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .08 cent lower to .30 cent higher with August at
73.77 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .35 cent lower to .25 cent
higher with August at 84.55 cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent
lower to .20 cent higher with August at 46.97 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .65 cent to .85 cent higher with August at 25.60
cents a pound.
   Livestock futures settled lower and pork futures were mixed in
Tuesday's trading.
</TEXT>
