<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1221EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-PhilippinesDebt 2ndLd-Writethru   08-16 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines Debt, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Debt Relief for Philippines Agreed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: TOPS with 9 new grafs to UPDATE agreement announced; SUBS penultimate
graf to edit for second reference to Fernandez.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators representing the Philippines and
the country's major bank creditors today announced a tentative
agreement on a package of debt reduction, the second pact to be
reached under the Bush administration's to new initiative.
   Philippine Central Bank Governor Jose B. Fernandez Jr., who led
his country's negotiating team, said the tentative deal met the
guidelines established by U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady in
March.
   ``There is no question that we must reduce the country's existing
stock of commercial bank debt if we are to sustain the country's
economic growth,'' he said. ``At the same time new commerical bank
financing is critical for our program as the combined effect of our
debt reduction initiatives and our improving economy work to bring
about the end of the debt problem for the Philippines.''
   Officials said the new accord would reduce the Philippines' $28
billion debt and also provide new loans, the two elements the
country's negotiators had considered critical to keeping the
Philippine economy expanding.
   The new debt package was the second agreement achieved under the
Brady debt plan, which is seeking to get commercial banks to forgive
a portion of their Third World loans in exchange for guarantees of
repayment of the remaining debt.
   Last month, Mexico, the developing world's second largest debtor
with $108 billion owed, reach an accord following the Brady plan's
guidelines.
   In the Mexican agreement, creditor banks were given a choice of
loan reductions, interest reductions or providing new money.
   The Philippine agreement was reached in New York between
representatives of the Philippine government and a committee of
banks led by Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.
   A source in Washington, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the International Monetary Fund last May offered the Philippines
about $206 million in loans that the government of President Corazon
Aquino could use for debt relief. In the present state of the
market, the government can settle old loans for about 50 cents on
the dollar.
   The Washington Post, which first reported the debt agreement,
cited Treasury officials and bankers saying they don't consider the
accord a break with the Brady plan because it envisions that the
Philippines will try to reduce its indebtedness.
   Additional money for debt relief is expected from the World Bank,
the fund's sister organization in Washington.
   The money could also be used to reduce interest rates on the old
loans. The burden of interest payments is the heaviest part of the
Third World's $1.3 trillion debt.
   Recent reports have said that the Philippines was less interested
in reduction of its debts to the commercial banks, than in new loans
from them. Fernandez has been reported seeking $1.8 to $4 billion.
   Of the $28 billion the Philippines already owes, the bulk is held
by governments and intergovernment bodies like the fund and World
Bank, which have not permitted any reductions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
