<DOCNO> AP890816-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1252EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-CBOTEthics     08-16 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-CBOT Ethics,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board of Trade Names Ethics Panel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board of Trade, stung by the
indictment of 46 futures traders in the city, has created a
permanent panel to monitor trading practices at the exchange.
   The Committee on Ethics and Integrity will examine all aspects of
exchange trading practices ``to ensure the utmost of integrity and
ethical conduct,'' the Board of Trade said Tuesday in a statement.
   It said the committee was created by the unanimous vote of the
exchange's board of directors.
   In addition to creating the committee, the board also added its
fourth outside director who is not a member of the exchange. This
will bring the board's membership to 25.
   ``Integrity is the No. 1 priority of this exchange,'' said CBOT
Chairman Karsten Mahlmann. ``We feel that the addition of another
non-member director and the establishment of the Committee on Ethics
and Integrity is a natural outgrowth of this commitment.''
   A federal grand jury has indicted 46 traders at the Board of
Trade and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, accusing them of cheating
their customers.
</TEXT>
