<FIRST>r f BC-Toronto-Trading     08-16 0131</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Toronto-Trading,0139</SECOND>
<HEAD>Computer Failure Stops Most Stock Trading For Three Hours</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The biggest computer failure in at least 12 years
delayed most trading on the Toronto Stock Exchange for three hours
Wednesday.
   Exchange officials said they suspected the problem originated in
the cables feeding the system rather than a software failure.
   ``All we know at the moment is that right at opening there was no
information on the screens to work with,'' exchange president Pearce
Bunting said in a telephone interview shortly after the failure.
   Trading resumed shortly after 12:30 p.m. EDT.
   Because of a lack of stock price information no floor trading
could take place. Trading was not interrupted on a computerized
system for smaller-company stocks, which account for about 20
percent of the exchange's volume.
</TEXT>
