<FIRST>r f AM-IBMSoftware     08-16 0140</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IBM Software,0145</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Announces Unix-Based Software For Big Mainframes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. said
Wednesday it would have Unix-based operating software available for
its most powerful computers early next year, fulfilling a pledge
made early last year.
   IBM had said in March 1988 that within two years it would have
Unix-based software for its full range of computers.
   Unix is a base layer of software developed by American Telephone
&amp; Telegraph Co. that theoretically enables many kinds of computers
to run the same programs with little or no modification. That is not
actually possible because Unix has become fragmented into many
versions, but efforts are under way to unify it.
   IBM's version of Unix is called AIX. IBM said its AIX for
mainframe System 370 computers is already installed in 13 customer
test sites.
</TEXT>
