<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     08-16 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed; Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was mixed against other major
currencies in European trading on Wednesday. Gold prices rose $3 an
ounce in London and $2 in Zurich.
   Bullion traders in Zurich said gold was restrained from even
higher rises because of uncertainty ahead of the release Thursday of
U.S. trade data for June.
   A narrower-than-expected trade gap would likely boost the dollar
and depress gold prices by diverting investors from the bullion
market.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $368.75 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $365.75.
   In Zurich, gold closed at a bid $368.50, compared with $366.25
late Tuesday. Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $3.12 to close at a
bid $368.84.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5725 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.5735 late Tuesday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.40 yen to a closing 141.80 yen. Its late price in
London was 142.45 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe late Wednesday, compared with
late Tuesday: 1.9470 West German marks, down from 1.9500; 1.6775
Swiss francs, down from 1.6790; 6.5700 French francs, down from
6.5835; 2.1925 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1905; 1,397.75 Italian
lire, up from 1,397.50; 1.1785 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1822.
   Silver bullion traded in London at a late bid price of $5.24 a
troy ounce, unchanged from late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
