<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1426EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-HousingStarts Bjt   08-16 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing Starts, Bjt,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Falling Mortgage Rates Boost Housing Starts for Second Month</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing starts, driven down for four months by
high mortgage rates, rose for the second straight month in July, the
government reported Wednesday, and analysts said single-family
construction should continue at a moderate pace the rest of the year.
   ``The interest rate drops in June definitely have begun to hit
the market,'' said John A. Tuccillo, chief economist for the
National Association of Realtors, who predicted further interest
rate declines will keep housing activity strong in the months ahead.
   ``The consumer is coming off the sidelines'' as mortgage rates
fall, commented Thomas Holloway, senior economist for the Mortgage
Bankers Association of America.
   The Commerce Department said housing starts were up 0.8 percent
last month, following an 8.5 percent hike in June. New homes and
apartments were started in July at a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 1.43 million, up from 1.42 million in June.
   Starts had fallen for four consecutive months through May as the
Federal Reserve drove up interest rates to slow the economy and curb
inflation. That was the longest string of declines since housing
activity slowed for five months in February-June 1987.
   But as economic growth moderated, the Fed began nudging rates
downward. Fixed-rate 30-year mortgages fell from 11.22 percent in
March to 9.96 percent last Friday, according to a survey by the
Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
   Despite the overall rebound, analysts saw problems in the
multi-family component of the housing starts report.
   While the single-family sector posted a 6.3 percent increase to
1.04 million units annually in July, apartment starts were off 1.2
percent to 389,000 units.
   Part of the decline in apartment starts was attributed to a heady
32.9 percent increase in June, which chief economist David Berson of
the Federal National Mortgage Association said ``was unsustainable
in view of the high vacancy rates.''
   Michael Carliner, an economist at the National Association of
Home Builders, said high rents and the elimination of tax incentives
by the 1986 tax reform added to the weak multi-family pace.
   And housing economist Michael Sumichrast said the 15.4 percent
drop in apartment building-permit applications ``tells me that
starts are going to decline sharply in the fall.'' Building permits
are seen as a barometer of future multi-family housing activity.
   Single-family starts had risen 0.2 percent in June after falling
5.1 percent in May and 4.7 percent in April. Apartment starts had
increased 5.4 percent in May after falling 26.6 percent in April.
   The Northeast paced overall housing construction with a 16
percent jump last month as starts rose to a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 196,000 units.
   Starts were up 11 percent to 272,000 units in the Midwest but
fell 4.3 percent to 530,000 units in the South and fell 4.2 percent
to 432,000 units in the West.
   Applications for building permits for both single-family houses
and apartments were down 3.1 percent in July, following a drop of
2.9 percent in June. They had risen 1 percent in May and 8.5 percent
in April after three consecutive monthly declines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
