<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1442EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-OilSpill 1stLd-Writethru   08-16 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spill, 1st Ld-Writethru,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Captain, Shipping Company Plead Guilty in Oil Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs to fix typo in `Greek.' Also moved on general
news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shipping company and a tanker captain
pleaded guilty today to federal charges of causing a 300,000-gallon
oil spill off Rhode Island on June 23 and agreed to pay fines
totaling $510,000.
   Ballard Shipping Co., a Liberian-registered company operating in
Piraeus, Greece, agreed to pay $500,000 to the state for
environmental research. The captain, Iakovos Georgudis, a
43-year-old Greek citizen, agreed to a $10,000 fine.
   Each pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor violation of the federal
Clean Water Act.
   Nearly 300,000 gallons of heating oil spilled into the mouth of
Narragansett Bay off Newport when the tanker World Prodigy ran
aground.
   If convicted, the captain could have received a year in jail and
a penalty equal to twice the amount of damage. The Coast Guard has
estimated the cleanup cost alone at $2 million. The shipping company
was also liable for twice the damage.
   The captain also is under indictment on state charges carrying up
to a year and a month in jail and fines of $20,000.
   U.S. Attorney Lincoln Almond said he did not press for harsher
penalties because the spill resulted from simple negligence.
   ``The captain became distracted and was also doing computations
to double check'' estimates involving the unloading of the oil,
Almond said.
   ``We believe it was about a six- or seven-minute lapse and there
was nothing in advance of that that was not done properly.''
   ``He was simply trying to handle more than one person could
handle at one time,'' said Peter DiBiase, Georgudis' attorney.
   Georgudis, who had no comment after today's federal court
hearing, previously told the governor and Coast Guard officials that
he failed to turn the vessel in time to avoid the reef.
   He also admitted no harbor pilot was on board to take the tanker
into port. Officials are investigating whether the vessel had passed
the point at which one was required.
   Almond said he felt it was more appropriate to give the money to
the state, rather than to the federal government, because state
beaches and wildlife sustained the most damage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
