<DOCNO> AP890816-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 2106EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-SellingGasoline Adv20   08-16 1082</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Selling Gasoline, Adv 20,1122</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>Customers Lose In Profit Struggle Between Dealers And Wholesalers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The sultry summer is especially sweaty this year for Texaco
station operator Sam Rodar, and it's not from the heat. Because his
supplier is his chief competitor, Rodar says he walks a pricing
tightrope.
   Wholesale gasoline prices have been falling, but Rodar says he
can't pass along the savings to customers because his supplier could
get mad and drive him out of business.
   His predicament illustrates what gasoline market experts call a
nationwide problem that is hurting retail gasoline sellers and
motorists alike. While wholesale prices have dropped as much as 28
cents since mid-May because of an oversupply and sluggish demand,
retail prices have fallen only about 6 cents.
   ``It's a wholesaler's market right now,'' says Tom Kloza, editor
of Oil Price Information Service, an industry newsletter.
``Distributors are wallowing like pigs in slop.''
   Service station dealers blame oil companies and suppliers for
keeping gasoline prices high when they should be lower. Suppliers
claim tighter government regulations and higher insurance rates have
raised costs. Oil companies are reluctant to talk about prices but
say they're set by the market.
   Nonetheless, the market laws of supply and demand don't
necessarily hold in what dealers call the dog-eat-dog world of
peddling gasoline.
   ``The problem here is that some of the dogs are much bigger than
others and some can't bite back,'' says Rodar, who operates a
station outside Sante Fe, N.M.
   In rural areas like that, the distributor _ or middleman between
the refiner and dealer _ often controls prices. In big cities,
dealers often buy directly from the refiner.
   In both situations, dealers claim they don't get the benefit of
cheaper prices because they have little influence over the supply,
controlled by oil companies, their refiners and distribution
networks.
   ``In some cases, they do have a lock on the market,'' concedes
David Morehead, spokesman for the Petroleum Marketers Association,
which represents 10,000 wholesalers and retailers nationwide.
   But Morehead says this year's erratic price shifts are unusual
and don't reflect the broader forces shaping the price of gasoline.
   ``A lot of what they have in inventory they bought at higher
prices and they want to go through that inventory first before they
pass on the prices,'' he says. ``Ultimately competition will
return.''
   Gasoline prices soared after the March 24 Exxon Valdez oil spill
in Alaska due partly to concerns that there wouldn't be enough fuel
to meet the predicted strong summer demand. Refiners rushed to
produce more gasoline and by May wholesale prices were falling
rapidly, but motorists didn't see much change.
   Glenn Nilsson, director of the Lone Star Service Station
Association in Houston, says his dealers face a problem similar to
Rodar's, but in their case the bad guys are the big oil refineries.
   ``The majors have created an artificial profit by keeping prices
high to the dealer,'' Nilsson says. ``They got prices up there and
they left them up there.''
   Most major oil companies decline to comment on pricing practices.
Exxon Corp. spokesman Les Rogers said, ``We monitor our markets
daily closely and we set our prices to be competitive. So it's
purely and simply a response to market conditions.''
   Rodar says his biggest complaint is that his supplier can control
prices and make big profits at the same time.
   The supplier, for example, buys unleaded gasoline for 93.5 cents
a gallon from the refiner, sells it to Rodar for $1.05 and charges
$1.21 at his own pump, the same as Rodar. That means the supplier
makes 27.5 cents a gallon in profit vs. 16 cents for Rodar.
   ``I hate to lead the market in any direction because he has the
ability to price discipline me,'' says Rodar. ``He could sell it for
what I pay for it and literally drive me out of the market.''
   Rodar's supplier, Chester Berridge, president of Berridge
Distributing Co. Inc. of Santa Fe, says he is ``not in business as a
charitable organization.''
   Berridge defends his prices by saying the costs of business have
rocketed because of new pollution regulations requiring station
owners to upgrade equipment and increase insurance coverage.
   Berridge, who supplies 17 New Mexico dealers including himself,
says his insurance premiums have soared to $204,000 a year from
$12,000 and his cost of installing new equipment is about $135,000
per station.
   ``If you think we can stay in this business and make a profit
then you don't know this business,'' Berridge says.
   Prices elsewhere show the evident disadvantage dealers face in
competing with oil company refiners and suppliers that also sell
directly to the public.
   In Houston, for example, the gap between what refiners charge
suppliers and what they charge dealers was 16.35 cents as of early
this month, the biggest gap this year, Nilsson says. The normal gap
is 1{ to 4 cents.
   In San Francisco, the average cost to wholesalers was 59.6 cents
a gallon vs. 77.6 cents to dealers in late July, and in Atlanta it
was 56 cents to wholesalers vs. 69.5 cents to dealers, Oil Price
Information Service figures show.
   Rodar claims he can't go elsewhere to get gasoline because other
Texaco distributors won't sell to him.
   ``We have people who want to go to these (suppliers) and buy for
less but the refiner in most cases has put pressure on the
wholesaler to not sell to so-called captive customers,'' says
Nilsson.
   A few states, including Maryland and Connecticut, have attempted
to deal with the problem by banning oil companies from selling
gasoline at the retail level, says Wayne Konitshek, a Denver-based
dealer lobbyist.
   Konitshek says he believes pricing practices by refiners and
distributors have helped drive dealers out of business. The number
of dealers has fallen from 330,000 in 1972 to 108,000 today, he says.
   Houston dealers several years ago sued major oil companies under
antitrust laws, Nilsson says.
   ``Prices dropped dramatically practically overnight'' and the
dealers dropped the suit, he says.
   A lawsuit filed in state district court in Houston last April
against Exxon by 19 Exxon dealers accuses the oil company of 15
violations of Texas anti-trust and deceptive trade practice laws.
The counts include profiteering from dealers, saddling consumers
with high fuel costs and interfering with their ability to buy
cheaper gasoline elsewhere.
   The suit, which seeks more than $5 million in damages, is pending.
   Five similar suits are pending in other states, Konitshek says.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, Aug. 20</NOTE>
