<FIRST>u f AM-Nicaragua-Devaluation 1stLd-Writethru   08-16 0148</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Devaluation, 1st Ld-Writethru,0153</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Devalues Curency 21st Time This Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>CORRECTS new value of cordoba to 20,600 sted as sent.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced Wednesday it
was devaluating its curency for the 21st time this year. The
cordoba's new value will be 20,600 per dollar after the 3 percent
devaluation, down from 20,000.
   In announcing the move, Vice President Sergio Ramirez said it was
to ``avoid distortions in prices and stimulate exports.''
   The unofficial parallel rate is 25,500 cordobas per dollar in the
exchange houses.
   After consumer price increases of 36,000 percent last year, the
government began in January a rigorous anti-inflation plan that
includes regular devaluations and a severe cut in public spending.
   Ramirez said the government's goal was to bring inflation down to
the 900-1,000 percent range this year. Monthly inflation last month
was registered at 8.5 percent, the government reported.
</TEXT>
