<FIRST>r f AM-Pillsbury-BumbleBee     08-16 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pillsbury-Bumble Bee,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pillsbury to Sell Bumble Bee to Thai Company Affiliate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. moved to drop another subsidiary
as it announced plans Wednesday to sell Bumble Bee Seafoods Inc. to
an affiliate of Unicord Co. Ltd. of Thailand for $269 million in
cash.
   The deal is unusual in that the buyer is from Thailand, a poor
Southeast Asian nation that is trying to catch up with the surging
Four Tigers of South Korea, Taiwan, Singapore and Hong Kong.
   ``The acquisition of Bumble Bee marks the first time that a Thai
company has purchased an American concern of this magnitude,'' said
Dumri Konuntakiet, Unicord's chief executive officer and controlling
shareholder.
   ``We are particularly pleased to be acquiring a company as
well-managed as Bumble Bee, with a strong brand name in the
important U.S. market,'' he said. ``We plan to continue to expand
our company's food-related activities on a global scale.''
   Pillsbury bought Bumble Bee, then privately held, for $242
million in July 1988. But officials said Wednesday that holding on
to Bumble Bee doesn't fit with the long-term strategies of
Pillsbury, which has been streamlining since its $5.7 billion
acquisition by Grand Metropolitan PLC of Great Britain in January.
   Just last week, Pillsbury announced that it will sell its Van de
Kamp's frozen seafoods division to Chicago-based Whitman Corp. for
about $140 million in cash.
   ``Bumble Bee, like Van de Kamp's, is an exceptionally strong
company. However, it does not fit with Pillsbury's long-range
strategy for its core businesses,'' Ian A. Martin, chairman and
chief executive officer of Pillsbury, said in a statement.
   The sale of Bumble Bee and its Santa Fe Springs, Calif.,
manufacturing facility to the newly formed Uni Group Inc., a
U.S.-based affiliate of Unicord, is expected to be completed in
September, the companies said.
   Unicord is a leading Thai seafood processing and exporting
company.
   The San Diego, Calif.-based Bumble Bee markets products including
white meat and light meat tuna, salmon, oysters, and Figaro pet
food. It had annual sales of about $284 million last year.
   Pillsbury had fiscal 1988 sales of $6.2 billion. Its leading
brands include Green Giant Vegetables, Haagen Dazs ice cream and
Totino's pizza, and it owns Burger King.
   Since the Grand Met acquisition, Pillsbury has also sold or made
plans to sell units including five food processing facilities in
Latin America; the Azteca Mexican Foods business and the S&amp;A
Restaurant Corp., as well as Bumble Bee and Van de Kamps.
   In addition, Grand Met has shut down a pizza plant in Joplin,
Mo., a sweet potato plant in Turkey, N.C., and a potato side dish
plant in Grand Forks, N.D. More than 500 employees at Pillsbury's
Minneapolis headquarters and an equal number of non-restaurant
workers in the company's Burger King system have been laid off since
January.
</TEXT>
