<FIRST>u f PM-PartsPlea 1stLd-Writethru   08-16 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Parts Plea, 1st Ld-Writethru,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pleads Guilty To Selling Aerospace Industry Counterfeit Parts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with possible penalties; PICKS
UP graf pvs, 6th graf pvs, `The guilty ...' CORRECTS to distributor sted
manufacturer in lede. Moved on general news wires as 2nd Ld.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RORY MARSHALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An airplane parts distributor and its president
pleaded guilty today to selling thousands of used nuts and bolts as
new to several airlines and aerospace contractors.
   Rice Aircraft Inc. of Hauppauge, N.Y. and its president, Bruce J.
Rice, 42, pleaded guilty to conspiracy and mail fraud.
   The fasteners hold together everything from wings to engines and
were distributed widely in the aerospace industry from 1977 through
1988, mostly in the early 1980s, authorities said.
   U.S. Attorney Gene Wilson said federal investigators have not
directly linked the parts to any aircraft crashes.
   Wilson said Rice Aircraft had the parts secretly stripped and
replated or relubricated, and then sold them as new.
   Rice could receive up to five years in prison, fines of $500,000
and court costs of $250,000 at sentencing Feb. 16. The company faces
fines up to $50,000 and will share with Rice in possible restitution
up to $1 million.
   The guilty pleas came as the government charged three more
defendants with paying kickbacks and conspiring to underbid on
airplane parts contracts.
   Court documents indicate the recycled parts were sold to the U.S.
government, the Israeli government, Airbus, British Aerospace,
Grumman, Sikorsky, Martin Marietta, Boeing Helicopters, Air France,
United Airlines, the Brazilian airline Varig, TWA, American Airlines
and Pan Am.
   Some parts were purchased for military aircraft, including the
F-111, the B-1B bomber and F-14 fighters, Wilson said.
   The U.S. Attorney's also office filed charges against Richard K.
Ohlman, 70, of Mission Viejo, Calif., accusing him of acting as a
middleman who conspired with Rice and Rice Aircraft to pay kickbacks
in 1982 to Boeing Surplus personnel.
   The kickbacks were paid to help Rice Aircraft sell the recycled
parts to Boeing Surplus, a unit of the Boeing Co., authorities said.
In exchange for the kickbacks, Wilson said, Ohlman was given the
``last look'' at competitors' secret bids.
   Unrelated charges also were filed against former Boeing Surplus
employees John J. Rockwood, 49, of Bellevue, Wash., and Richard K.
Watson, 66, of Los Angeles.
   They were accused of conspiring with Southeast Connectors Inc. of
Miami, Fla., to provide Southeast with the ``last look'' at
competitors' bids submitted to Boeing Surplus.
</TEXT>
