<FIRST>r f BC-Embezzle     08-16 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Embezzle,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>S&amp;L Manager Charged With Stealing $3.47 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former San Francisco savings and loan
branch manager has been charged with embezzling $3.47 million from
customers' deposits over more than four years, authorities said
Wednesday.
   Richard A. Mariucci, 30, was arrested by the FBI Tuesday at his
home in the Riverside County community of Rancho, said U.S. Attorney
Joseph Russoniello. He released a 29-count indictment against
Mariucci that was returned Friday by a federal grand jury.
   Mariucci managed a San Francisco branch of Gibraltar Savings and
Loan from 1985 to April 1989, when he was fired for reasons
unrelated to the embezzlement investigation, the FBI said.
   He could be sentenced to 145 years in prison and fined $7.25
million if convicted of all charges, Russoniello said.
   The problem came to light two days after Mariucci was fired, when
a customer asked about the $100,000 certificate of deposit she had
taken out with Gibraltar the previous September and was told there
was no record of her account, said FBI Agent Kathryn Reeve in a
sworn statement.
   She said an investigation showed that Mariucci took certificate
of deposit checks that were placed with him and put much of the
money in a personal account, while setting aside the rest to repay
earlier depositors and avoid discovery.
   Reeve's statement listed eight customers who were verified as
having deposited money that was not in their accounts and another
six who had been identified by Gibraltar, and said the list may
grow. The indictment states 29 instances of embezzlement, of amounts
ranging up to $400,000, between February 1985 and April 1989.
   Agents seized over $639,000 from accounts controlled by Mariucci
at seven institutions on May 9, Reeve said.
   Court documents did not mention the recovery of any of the other
allegedly embezzled funds. Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark Zanides said
Mariucci may have put some of the money into real estate.
</TEXT>
