<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1737EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PhonyLawyer     08-16 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Phony Lawyer,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Phony Lawyer Pleads Guilty in Multiple Frauds, Avoids Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who posed as a financial consultant and
immigration lawyer avoided prison Wednesday by agreeing to a plea
deal to repay more than $80,000 he admitted stealing from clients.
   Ira Ratner, 44, of Easton, Conn., pleaded guilty to 19 counts of
an indictment that charged him with grand larceny, forgery, scheme
to defraud and criminal possession of stolen property.
   Assistant District Attorney Edward Hamlin said Ratner bilked at
least 13 people between December 1985 and July 1988 by promising
services such as getting mortgages and loans, buying and leasing
office space, and investing.
   Hamlin said Ratner also posed as an immigration lawyer and told
illegal aliens he could help them get ``green cards'' _ permanent
residency cards. He admitted in court that he is not a lawyer.
   When he was arrested in January, Manhattan District Atorney
Robert Morgenthau said a two-year investigation ``showed that Mr.
Ratner never performed a legitimate business transaction for any of
these clients, and the only investment made was in his own personal
bank account.''
   In one case, Hamlin said, Ratner took $140,000 in checks and
negotiable bonds from a woman who requested his help after her
husband had a stroke.
   According to the plea deal, if Ratner repays the $80,950.75 that
he kept, he will not go jail. There was no mention of probation or
community service. Ratner could have gotten up to 15 years in prison
on the top count, second-degree grand larceny.
</TEXT>
