<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1655EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-FarmCredit     08-16 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Farm Credit,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farm Credit Second-Quarter Earnings Drop 6.5 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Farm Credit System on Wednesday reported its
second-quarter net income was down 6.5 percent from the same period
last year and warned that .
   The system, the nation's biggest lender to agriculture, said it
earned $159 million for the quarter ended June 30 compared with $170
million in the 1988 period.
   For the first six months of the year, the system showed profits
of $317 million, down 5.7 percent from $336 million in the first
half of 1988.
   Although overall net income declined during the quarter, net
interest income rose by $42 million to $256 million. The improvement
stemmed from continued improvement in the system's loan credit
quality and its interest margin, the difference between its
borrowing costs and interest on loans it makes, said Alan D. Fass,
president and chief executive officer of the Federal Farm Credit
Banks Funding Corp., the credit system's financing arm.
   ``The system's second-quarter results indicate a continued
strengthening of the system's overall financial condition,'' said
Fass.
   For the first half, net interest income was $496 million, up from
$360 million in 1988.
   Fass also said the system was aided by repurchases by some system
banks of portions of their higher-cost debt and retirement of some
other higher-cost debt that matured in the last year.
   But the system said in a statement that ``certain system banks
remain in a weakened financial condition'' and that drought
conditions persist in scattered regions. It said it believes
adequate allowances for loan losses are being maintained to cover
credit risks from possible drought-related losses.
   Fass said Department of Agriculture projections for the system's
net cash income for 1989 remain just slightly under last year's
levels.
   ``This should mean stronger financial positions for system
borrowers, resulting in continued improvement in the credit quality
of the system's loan portfolio,'' he said.
   Nonaccrual loans declined to $2.87 billion as of June 30 from
$3.3 billion on Dec. 31, 1988. Loans considered ``high-risk,''
excluding non-accruing loans, rose to $4.58 billion as of June 30
from $4.56 billion six months earlier, mainly due to a $194 million
increase in the amount of restructured loans.
   The allowance for loan losses was $1.72 billion as of June 30, up
from $1.86 billion at year-end 1988. During the second quarter, the
system took an $80 million negative provision for loan losses,
compared with $181 million in the 1988 quarter.
   The Farm Credit System is a nationwide system of federally
chartered agricultural lending institutions serving the rural
economy and cooperatively owned by their borrowers.
   The system took several steps last year to streamline its
structure following 1987 bailout legislation that included the
issuance of up to $4 billion in government-backed, low-interest
loans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
