<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-16 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted mostly lower Wednesday against
major foreign currencies after a mixed performance overseas.
   Gold prices also fell in domestic trading but made strong gains
in Europe and Asia.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed off $2.50 at $368.20 a troy ounce. Republic National
Bank of New York quoted a late bid for gold at $366.50 an ounce,
down from $368.50 Monday.
   Currency traders said the dollar started out strong but slipped
on rumors of dollar-selling by the Federal Reserve and on internal
market influences.
   ``A lot of people were squaring their positions ahead of
Thursday's trade report,'' said Gary Lutnick, a trader for Banco di
Sicilia in New York.
   The Commerce Department is scheduled to release figures on the
merchandise trade deficit for June, and some traders are predicting
a shortfall of around $9.5 billion. They said the dollar is likely
to rally if the gap falls below $9 billion but decline should it
exceed $10 billion.
   A low trade deficit is seen as positive for the dollar because it
means the currency probably won't have to decline any further to
help improve the U.S. trade picture. A weak dollar makes U.S.
exports more attractive.
   Meanwhile, Lutnick said the currency market largely ignored the
economic figures released Wednesday, showing industrial production
rising for the first time in three months during July and housing
starts continuing to rebound that month.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.40 yen to a closing 141.80 yen. It traded at
142.45 yen late in London, and at 142.185 yen in New York, up from
142.15 yen Tuesday.
   The dollar rose against the British pound in Europe and fell in
New York. It cost $1.5725 to buy one pound in London, cheaper than
$1.5735 late Tuesday. Sterling fetched $1.5805 in New York, up from
$1.5768.
   Other dollar rates at Wednesday's close compared with late
Tuesday, included: 1.9420 West German marks, up from 1.9437; 1.67155
Swiss francs, down from 1.6748; 1.17775 Canadian dollars, down from
1.18025; 6.5615 French francs, down from 6.5780; and 1,395.00
Italian lire, down from 1,395.50.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Tuesday: 1.9470 West
German marks, down from 1.9500; 1.6775 Swiss francs, down from
1.6790; 6.5700 French francs, down from 6.5835; 2.1925 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.1905; 1.1785 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1822;
and 1,397.75 Italian lire, up from 1,397.50.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $368.75 an ounce from
Tuesday's $365.75. In Zurich, gold closed at $368.50 an ounce, up
from $366.25.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $3.12 to close at $368.84 an
ounce.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery fell to $5.186 a troy ounce from $5.242 late
Tuesday. Silver settled in London at $5.24 an ounce, unchanged.
</TEXT>
