<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-16 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0758</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lower Petroleum Stock Send Prices Higher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices advanced modestly on the New York
Mercantile Exchange following the release of American Petroleum
Institute figures showing a drop in petroleum stocks.
   On other markets, soybean futures dropped sharply and grain
futures were mixed, precious metals prices retreated, copper
continued its advances, and livestock and pork futures were mixed.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 17 cents to 39 cents
higher with the contract for delivery in September at $18.97 a
barrel; heating oil was .44 cent to .95 cent higher with September
at 51.15 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .84 cent to 90 cent
higher with September at 52.93 cents a gallon.
   The API weekly data indicated that gasoline stocks declined 3.5
million barrels in the latest week, while crude oil stocks were down
2.75 million barrels.
   Traders looked upon the data as slightly bullish, prompting the
run-up in prices.
   ``The figures indicate lower-than-anticipated stocks,'' said Jim
Ritterbusch, an analyst with Carson Petroleum Co., a Chicago area
oil distributor. ``The street was looking for only a 1 million
barrel drop in supplies.''
   The strength in demand for oil products in the United States and
market strength in Europe also helped boost energy futures, analysts
said.
   Soybean futures were off sharply on the Chicago Board of Trade
because of an uncertain weather outlook, analysts said.
   Earlier this week, forecasts called for a relatively dry weekend,
but updated forecasts now call for moderate rain over wide areas of
the Midwest, which triggered commercial selling, said Frank Kouba,
an analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in Chicago.
   Corn futures ended the day higher despite forecasts of weekend
precipitation. Giving support to the market were reports that Mexico
will bid this week for 400,000 metric tons of U.S. corn and South
Korea will bid for 150,000 metric tons.
   Wheat futures, which closed mixed, were pressured by reports that
Algeria's bid for 250,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat under the export
bonus program was rejected. Algeria rebid for 100,000 metric tons of
wheat.
   Wheat was \ cent lower to 4} cents higher with September at
$3.99\ a bushel; corn was { cent lower to 1{ cent higher with
September at $2.35 a bushel; oats were } cent to 2 cents lower with
September at $1.38 a bushel; soybeans were 13\ cents lower to 1 cent
higher with August at $6.23{ a bushel.
   Copper prices edged up on New York's Commodity Exchange despite
reports the miner's strike in Peru appears to be losing steam.
   The continuing strike at Canada's Highland Valley Copper mine and
the shutdown of mines in Papua New Guinea helped to support the
market.
   Copper was .35 cent to 1.10 cent higher with August at $1.222 a
pound.
   Precious metals prices fell on the Comex, losing all the gains
made in Tuesday's trading.
   ``This was another in a series of failed rallies,'' said William
O'Neill, an analyst with Elders Futures Inc. in New York. ``There
was little impact on the market by outside fundamentals. The
market's movement was mostly technically oriented.''
   O'Neill said the weakness in precious metal prices continues to
be based on the strong dollar and weak. A weak dollar and strong
inflation draws investors to gold and silver.
   O'Neill also noted that stocks of gold and silver remain high.
   Gold settled $2.50 to $3.20 lower with August at $368.20 a troy
ounce; silver was 5.5 cents to 6.1 cent lower with August at $5.186
a troy ounce.
   Livestock futures were lower and pork futures higher in trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Pork futures were supported by indications that prices in the
cash market will firm, said Paul Georgy, an analyst with Allendale
Inc. in Crystal Lake, Ill. Technical factors also supported the
market, as the rise in prices triggered additional buying by
commission houses.
   Livestock futures were pushed lower by Department of Agriculture
reports of lower prices in the cash market.
   Live cattle were .03 cent to .55 cent lower with August at 74.07
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .23 cent higher
with August at 84.57 cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent to .52
cent higher with August at 47.15 a pound; frozen pork bellies were
1.92 cents to 2 cents higher with August at 26.82 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
