<HEAD>Stock Market Advances in Slow Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks faltered Wednesday after a strong opening
rally fizzled, but the market still finished with a small gain.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.51 points to close
at 2,693.29 after bouncing over the 2,700 mark shortly after the
opening bell.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 5 to 4 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
819 issues up, 662 down and 512 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 150.06 million
shares, up from 148.77 million in the previous session.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 179.47 million shares.
   The market opened strong in what some Wall Street analysts
predicted would be the launching pad for a new rally. But the market
failed to sustain the momentum and began to drift.
   ``I'm perplexed about the action; the action is odd,'' said John
Burnett, senior vice president at Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette.
``You know in the movies how they say `it's too quiet?' I expected
more activity.''
   New government reports on July U.S. industrial production and
capacity utilization and housing starts were in line with
expectations and had little impact on the market, analysts said.
   Nevertheless, the reports helped ease some market concerns that
the economy is starting to heat up again, said Hugh Johnson, senior
vice president for First Albany Corp.
   The Commerce Department reported that new housing starts rose 0.8
percent last month to a seasonally adjusted rate of 1.43 million
units from 1.42 million units in June.
   Industrial production rose a moderate 0.2 percent in July, but
the operating rate for the nation's factories remained flat, the
Federal Reserve Board said, suggesting a further easing of inflation.
   Technology stocks slumped after Intel Corp. announced that it
expected a decline in third-quarter earnings due to a `change in the
company's product mix.' Intel dropped 1] to 28~ on the
over-the-counter market.
   But analysts predicted the market could improve later this week
with the release of the June merchandise trade and July consumer
price reports on Thursday and Friday.
   ``Technically, the stock market is in a positive mode. The upturn
is still intact,'' said A.C. Moore, director of research at Argus
Research.
   The market is expecting a narrowing in the trade deficit to about
$9.4 billion from $10.24 billion in June and a moderate gain of 0.2
percent in consumer prices, Moore said.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market advanced $9.036 billion, or 0.27
percent, in value from Tuesday.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.56 to 192.64.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, General Motors rose \
to 45}, Ford Motor gained ~ to 51~ and Tandem advanced 1[ to 23\.
   IBM closed at 115\, down 1, Johnson and Johnson lost { to 51 and
Exxon fell } to 44].
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 1.02 to 395.73, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index gained 0.67 to 321.81.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market fell
0.12 to 460.79. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 379.60, down 0.22.
</TEXT>
