<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     08-16 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices rose Wednesday in light
trading, boosted by new industry statistics showing a sharp
reduction in U.S. gasoline supplies.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, unleaded regular gasoline
for September delivery jumped 0.87 cent to 52.93 cents a gallon.
Most contracts for later delivery showed similar increases.
   The September-delivery contract for West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, closed 29 cents higher at $18.97
per 42-gallon barrel. Contract months for later delivery posted
smaller advances.
   Heating oil futures, which led the market higher last week, also
posted gains. The September contract rose 0.87 cent to finish at
51.15 cents a gallon.
   Market participants said prices were lifted by the American
Petroleum Institute's latest weekly report, released Tuesday after
the close of trading. The report showed a drop in U.S. gasoline
stocks of around 3.5 million barrels in the week ended Aug. 11, to
222.93 million barrels. A reduction in supplies of gasoline has the
effect of raising prices.
   ``Gasoline was perceived as being bullish,'' said Chris
McCormack, a futures trader at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
``Gasoline led the market higher.''
</TEXT>
