<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 2011EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Airlines-EngineFailure     08-16 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airlines-Engine Failure,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Jets Have Experienced 16 Serious Engine Failures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some airline safety experts say they're surprised
at figures showing that wide-body jets have experienced at least 288
instances of engine trouble in the past six years, including 16
serious incidents that could have led to a crash.
   The figures were obtained from Federal Aviation Administration
records and reported in an article in Wednesday's editions of the
St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch.
   ``It's certainly of concern,'' said Richard Livingston of the
110,000-member International Airline Passengers Association.
``Obviously any time you have an uncontained engine explosion,
you've opened the door to catastrophe.''
   John Nance, a pilot and air safety analyst who generally defends
the safety of airlines, said, ``It is higher than I would have
expected.''
   The 16 serious incidents occurred when engine parts tore into the
engine casing or hurtled out of the engine, according to the FAA
records.
   It is believed that debris thrown from a failed engine severed
hydraulic lines on the United Airlines DC-10 that crashed in Sioux
City, Iowa, on July 19. The crash, which killed more than 100
people, remains under investigation.
   The FAA numbers are based on the agency's service difficulty
reports since 1983 for the General Electric CF6 and Pratt &amp; Whitney
JT9 engines, the ones used on the most U.S. wide-body jets. The
figures exclude smaller aircraft that are far more numerous in
airline fleets.
   The number of incidents detailed in the FAA records is surprising
to some, the newspaper said, because after the Sioux City crash the
National Transportation Safety Board said there have been only 12
other ``uncontained'' engine failures on any type of commercial
jetliner since 1982.
   But that counts only incidents in which there was injury, death
or what the agency regards as an immediate threat to safety.
   Engine makers and airlines, as well as the FAA and the National
Transportation Safety Board, stress that serious engine breakups are
still rare. Blades and other parts breaking away from engines are a
fact of life, since the blades often spin at over 10,000 revolutions
per minute and are weakened by birds, stress and ice.
   But such incidents rarely result in accidents because the parts
usually are contained in the engine casing or spit out in the
engine's exhaust.
   Engine designs use the best available technology, said Bob Hall,
an engineer for the Air Line Pilots Association, ``but just like
anything else in this world, there are times when all that doesn't
come to fruition.''
   Said Nance: ``The problem is not that the engines are going to
come apart. The problem is trying to contain them when they do.''
   Of the 288 instances of engine trouble on wide-body jets, at
least 94 occurred when blades broke from compressors and turbines
and seriously damaged engines but didn't spew parts out of the
engine casing.
   In 58 more cases, records aren't conclusive on whether the blades
simply cracked or broke off, but they indicate the engines often
were seriously damaged.
   The FAA records often aren't clear about the severity of the
damage in the 16 cases of ``engine case penetration.'' Reports in
four of the incidents note the case was violated but don't detail
the damage. Two say parts protruded from or were embedded in the
casing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890816-0263 </DOCNO>
