<FIRST>r f AM-Toronto-Trading     08-16 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toronto-Trading,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Computer Failure Halts Most Trading in Toronto For Three Hours</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A computer equipment failure at the Toronto Stock
Exchange halted most trading for three hours Wednesday, making it
the exchange's longest technically related halt since computers went
into use 26 years ago.
   The shortened trading day didn't harm the market. The exchange's
composite index rose 11.27 points to close at 4,013.36 in a
moderately active trading of 32.5 million shares.
   Trading stopped 11 minutes after the market opened at 9:30 a.m.
and didn't resume again until 12:31 p.m. It closed at its usual time
of 4 p.m.
   Trading continued on the exchange's CATS system _ computer
assisted trading system _ where the exchange's smaller companies are
handled. But only about 20 per cent of the exchange's trading occurs
on CATS.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``It's one of those things you have to accept if you're going to
enjoy the benefits of the computer's assistance in trading,'' said
Fred Ketchen, senior vice-president of Scotia McLeod and chairman of
the exchange's market functions committee.
   Most securities firms were able to circumvent the problem by
routing their trading through other stock markets, he said.
   The exchange attributed the problem to a ``double hardware
failure'' in the trading system, said Revell.
   The primary information-storing computer disk system and its
backup both failed, Revell said.
</TEXT>
