<HEAD>Stanley Buys The Parker Group, A Mass.-Based Fastener-Maker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BRITAIN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stanley Works, the worldwide toolmaker,
announced Wednesday it has completed its purchase of Parker Group, a
manufacturer of fastening products.
   Parker, based in Northboro, Mass., employs about 400 people at
plants in Worcester, Northboro and Southbridge, Mass., and in West
Greenwich, R.I.
   The company makes glue guns, stapling products, riveting tools
and soldering tools.
   Stanley did not release the terms of the purchase.
   ``Parker has developed a leading position in the design,
manufacture and sale of fastening products for home improvement and
consumer markets,'' said Gary C. Schuler, president and general
manager of Stanley-Bostich Inc.
   Stanley Group Vice President David M. Hadlow described Parker as
a ``good strategic fit'' with other Stanley businesses.
   Stanley, based in New Britain, had sales of $1.9 billion in 1988.
</TEXT>
