<FIRST>r f AM-CBOT-Andreas     08-16 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CBOT-Andreas,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exchange Takes No Action Against Archer-Daniels-Midland Exec</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board of Trade has refused to take
action against the chairman of a major grain company in response to
member complaints that his comments about the CBOT have damaged the
exchange, officials said Wednesday.
   CBOT Chairman Karsten Mahlmann said in a notice to members that
to punish Dwayne Andreas for his comments about the exchange would
be inappropriate because Andreas is not a Board of Trade member.
   Last month, Andreas, chairman of Decatur, Ill.-based
Archer-Daniels-Midland Co., criticized the Board of Trade after the
exchange ordered traders to reduce their holdings in the July
soybean futures contract to 1 million bushels.
   The July 11 order was apparently made to break up an alleged
attempt by the Italian grain merchant Ferruzzi Finanziaria SpA to
corner the U.S. soybean market. Ferruzzi has denied making such an
attempt.
   After the order was issued, Andreas said the CBOT has exposed
itself to cornering attempts because it has fallen behind the times.
He said the CBOT had become ``more of a gambling institution than a
hedging center.''
   A petition circulated by members of the CBOT contended that
Andreas' comments constitute actions detrimental to the welfare of
the CBOT. The petition, signed by more than 100 members, asked the
exchange's board of directors to suspend the clearing privileges of
ADM Investor Services Inc., Archer-Daniels-Midland's CBOT clearing
affiliate.
   In a letter dated Aug. 14, Mahlmann reminded Andreas that as
chairman of a member firm, Andreas is obligated to present
information to the exchange on any member in violation of the
exchange's rules.
   ``Accordingly, the Chicago Board of Trade remains open to
receiving any information which your firm wishes to provide in
evidence of possible rule violations under the Exchange's purview,''
Mahlmann wrote.
   A woman who said she was Andreas' secretary said Wednesday he was
unavailable for comment on the letter.
</TEXT>
