<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 2032EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Mexico-MaquiladoraStrike     08-16 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Maquiladora Strike,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Plants Denounce `Gangster Tactics'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>REYNOSA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American-owned assembly plants refuse to
sign with a ``corrupt'' union leader in order to end a 23-day-old
labor dispute because giving in would be ``like spreading a cancer''
throughout the industry, a spokesman said Wednesday.
   ``Nobody is understanding the real issue here; the obvious and
blatant corruption in Mexico,'' said Arnold Kezsbom, president of
the New York-based Service Manufacturing Corp., which manufactures
soft luggage.
   The corporation's assembly plant in this northern border city is
one of 15 companies involved in a union power struggle with a local
leader of the Mexican Labor Federation, or CTM.
   The CTM's Rafael Morales put up strike flags and closed the gates
of the plants July 25 after Abel Hernandez, the union leader
representing the workers, withdrew from the CTM.
   The strike is costing the plants about $500,000 a day in lost
production and at least two have threatened to pull out of Mexico.
   Morales argued that because the plants had no CTM union leader,
he had the right to declare himself in charge, said managers who
have spoken to him.
   The CTM is the most powerful labor union in Tamaulipas state and
few dare to challenge its authority.
   So it was a rare show of force when about 900 out of some 2,000
plant workers affected by the strike ripped down CTM strike flags
Tuesday, locked themselves in their plants and returned to work.
   The workers have vowed to remain inside the plants until the
dispute is solved.
   ``The important thing is that we're at our jobs. We don't want
these plants to close,'' said Gustin Villanueva, a worker at
Invamex, a subsidiary of the Elyria, Ohio-based Invacare Corp.
wheelchair manufacturer.
   The strike flags were replaced early Wednesday by the local labor
arbitration board and Reynosa Mayor Ernesto Gomez Lira.
   Groups of about a dozen of Morales' men stood outside the plants
with orders ``not to let anybody in or out,'' said Juan Olivo, a
laborer at a plant unionized under Morales.
   The labor board, controlled by the CTM, has authorized Morales as
union leader but the plants are arguing against that decision in
federal court and with top federal authorities.
   Kezsbom said in an interview in McAllen, Texas, just north of
Reynosa, that the companies have decided to stand firm against
Morales because he is known as a ``corrupt individual.''
   He said that giving in would be ``like spreading a cancer''
throughout the industry.
   Kezsbom said Morales forces companies to allow his union to
control trucking contracts, transportation of waste and even food
coupons so that workers have to buy food from stores he controls.
   There is no way to control business costs when dealing with a
union head whose demands escalate each day, he said.
   Reporters have been unable to locate Morales for several days at
his headquarters, his home or the places he is known to frequent.
   Kezbom, meanwhile, denounced Gomez Lira's ``gangster-type
tactics'' in dealing with workers in the middle of the night.
   Gomez Lira toured most of the plants about 1 a.m. and told
workers locked inside that they should leave peacefully or the
police would take them out, workers interviewed said.
   Gomez Lira told the Associated Press that he recommended the
workers leave to ``prevent confrontations'' that might occurr.
   But Don King, manager of the West Bend, Wis.-based West Bend
plant, said Gomez Lira ``harassed employees and intimidated them try
to get them to leave.''
   The workers say they have no obligation under Mexican labor law
to sign with the CTM and, in fact, are happy with Hernandez no
matter whom he represents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890816-0269 </DOCNO>
