<HEAD>Marvin Davis Ups Bid for UAL to $275 a Share</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Marvin Davis on Wednesday increased his
bid for UAL Corp. to $6.2 billion and set the stage for a proxy
battle for the parent of United Airlines.
   A spokesman for Davis said the price could go higher after a
review of the company's internal data.
   Davis offered $240 a share, or $5.4 billion, earlier this month,
revitalizing interest in buying Chicago-based UAL. His latest offer
is $275 a share.
   The stock closed Wednesday at $251.75 on the New York Stock
Exchange, down $2.50. Davis' new bid was revealed after the market
closed.
   Last weekend, UAL officials reportedly met with leaders of the
Air Line Pilots Association to discuss a possible
management-employee buyout or recapitalization to put a large chunk
of shares into an employee stock ownership plan as a means of
blocking any hostile takeover.
   Davis emphasized that he does not want to be regarded as an
unfriendly suitor.
   ``Our continuing desire (is) to proceed on a friendly basis,''
said spokesman James N. Fingeroth.
   Meanwhile Wednesday, UAL said it had been served with a
stockholder consent form from Davis asking shareholders to remove
all members of the company's board of directors except Chairman
Stephen M. Wolf, reduce the board's membership to five from 16 and
elect a new slate headed by Davis.
   The Davis spokesman said the document is intended only to
establish a time frame _ Aug. 16 to Oct. 15 _ for determining which
shareholders would be eligible to vote on the measures should there
be a proxy battle.
   ``This is not to be interpreted as a change in Mr. Davis'
policy,'' said Fingeroth, adding that Davis does not now intend to
exercise the option to solicit votes against the current board.
   UAL had no response to Davis' action, said spokeswoman Sara
Dornacker.
   She said the UAL board will meet Thursday, but would not say if
it is a special meeting held in response to the latest Davis moves.
   Jim Damron, spokesman for United's pilots union, also refused to
comment on the developments.
