<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern     08-16 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Settles Pension Payment Suit With Pilots Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines agreed Wednesday to pay more than
$32 million into the pension fund of striking pilots to settle a
2-year-old suit against the financially troubled carrier.
   A statement from the Air Line Pilots Association in Washington,
D.C., predicted the payment will be approved in U.S. Bankruptcy
Court, which has supervised Eastern's finances since the carrier
filed for Chapter 11 protection five days after the March 4 strike
by pilots, flight attendants and machinists.
   The settlement sets a Sept. 15 deadline for the payment of the
$32 million, which represents regular company payments into the fund
and interest from 1985 to 1988, ALPA said.
   A 1987 ALPA suit, filed in U.S. District Court in Washington,
claimed Eastern violated federal law by failing to make scheduled
pension payments. If U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton Lifland does not
approve the settlement, ALPA said it would file another suit.
   Eastern, which was reportedly losing $1 million a day before the
strike, was granted two waivers by the Internal Revenue Service
since 1985 to withhold some pension payments, said Robin Matell, a
spokesman for the Miami-based carrier.
   Since the strike, Eastern has attempted to rebound as a smaller
airline. The company has stated its goal of rebuilding to two-thirds
of its 1,040 pre-strike flight schedule.
   Matell said Eastern, a division of Texas Air Corp., owes a total
of about $98 million in outstanding payments and interest to its
seven employee pension funds. He was unaware of any other employee
legal action similar to the ALPA suit.
   Part of the carrier's plan to emerge from Chapter 11 include
on-time payment to its pension plans. Eastern announced in June it
plans to pay about $100 million into various pension plans by Sept.
15.
   On June 1, Eastern reached an agreement with the U.S. Labor
Department to pay $3.1 million to several benefit plans to settle a
case in which the government alleged the carrier illegally tapped
employee funds to pay corporate expenses.
   Eastern entered into the agreement without admitting or denying
it violated federal pension laws.
</TEXT>
