<FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 2248EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Boeing-Corrosion     08-16 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Boeing-Corrosion,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Corrosion Fix Recommended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aviation industry task force said Wednesday it
gave the Federal Aviation Administration guidelines for a program to
prevent and repair corrosion on Boeing commercial airplanes.
   The 10-month study examined corrosion data from airline reports,
FAA records and a Boeing fleet survey on Boeing 707, 727, 737 and
747 jetliners.
   The task force recommended a corrosion protection, inspection and
repair program for each section of the aircraft studied.
   The task force included Boeing structural specialists, airline
maintenance experts and observers from the FAA and from foreign
regulatory agencies. It grew out of studies that government and
industry groups made after a 1988 accident in which the roof of an
Aloha Airlines Boeing 737 peeled off over Hawaii, sweeping one
flight attending to her death.
   Boeing spokesman Jack Gamble said the task force's
recommendations were drawn up to be used as a basis for the first
industrywide standards on corrosion.
   The FAA will study the recommendations and is expected to propose
a mandatory anti-corrosion program for U.S. airlines. The task force
said foreign agencies were expected to adopt the program for
carriers registered in their countries.
</TEXT>
