<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0293 08-16 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0293,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Share Prices Slip</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei, dollar.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was trading higher against the
Japanese yen Thursday morning on expectations of an improved U.S.
trade deficit, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell
back.
   The dollar opened at 142.25 yen, up 0.45 yen from Wednesday's
close of 141.80 yen. In New York overnight it had closed at 142.20
yen.
   During the morning trading session, the dollar moved in a range
of 142.20 to 142.45 yen, closing the session at 142.26 yen.
   An exchange dealer at Mitsui Bank said Wednesday's announcements
of U.S. housing starts and industrial capacity utilization rates had
little effect on the market.
   ``The upper end (of this morning's range) is restrained by
central bank intervention, and at the lower end buyers appear,'' the
dealer added, speaking anonymously.
   The U.S. Department of Commerce reported that housing starts had
increased 0.8 percent in July, while the Federal Reserve announced
that factory capacity utilization had risen marginally to 83.6
percent.
   Rather than concentrating on these figures, dealers were
anticipating an improvement in the U.S. merchandise trade statistics
for June, to be announced later Thursday by the Department of
Commerce, the dealer said.
   Other dealers said the market lacked direction as it waited for
the trade figures. But most participants expected the U.S. trade
deficit for June to show an improvement.
   On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which
reached a record-high Wednesday by gaining 273.46 points, lost 79.65
points, or 0.22 percent, to close the morning session at 35,004.50.
   Traders reported a shift of buying interest from high-priced
issues, which were mainly purchased for quick profit-taking, to
shares with lower price-earnings ratios.
